<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Howard: Telstra Constrained in Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) -- Australian telecommunications
company Telstra Corp. is being constrained in its deal with Hong
Kong company Pacific Century CyberWorks because of the government's
part-ownership, Prime Minister John Howard said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It can't issue any shares, it can't raise any equity,'' Howard
said on Australia Broadcasting Corp. radio.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a large organization like Telstra, that's a tremendous
constraint and the reason they can't do it is because that would
dilute government ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard wants to sell its remaining 50.1 percent stake in Telstra
but has yet to win enough support in Australia's Parliament for a
full sale.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Telstra and Pacific Century CyberWorks announced
an alliance in which the Australian company will pay $3 billion and
contribute assets to the alliance in return for a 50 percent stake
in an Internet infrastructure company and 40 percent of a mobile
telephony company. Pacific Century CyberWorks will own the balance
of both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he was confident the sale of the government's stake
would go ahead eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am sure in the end we will get strong support in our party
room for the sale of the rest of Telstra,'' Howard said. ''I think
it is in the national interest that it is fully privatized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
