<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Says Economy Improving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan on Friday upgraded its assessment of the two
main pillars of private demand -- personal spending and capital
investment -- and said the economy is improving at a ''moderate
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   In its monthly report for April, the Economic Planning Agency
cited signs of ''more buoyant'' corporate activity, and said the
economy is moving ''toward a sustainable recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said investment in plants and equipment is improving,
primarily in the manufacturing sector. In addition, the report
suggested personal spending may be close to turning a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''While it can't be said that personal consumption has fully
entered a solid recovery track given the low levels of income, it
continues to rally compared with the end of last year,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is fighting to overcome a decade-long economic downturn.
The economy fell back into recession late last year after a short
period of growth.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs of hope, however. Many corporations have
restructured over the past year, and industrial activity has begun
to show signs of perking up.
</P>
<P>
   The key for a sustainable economic recovery will be whether
personal spending picks up as well, the Economic Planning Agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking at the overall picture, it looks like conditions are
improving gradually every month, but we're not at a stage where we
can declare an economic recovery,'' said Takashi Omori, director of
the EPA's national economic affairs division.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, the EPA downgraded its view on housing
construction, noting declines, especially in the construction of
private houses.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA left its assessment of the employment situation as
''severe.'' Unemployment is at a record high of 4.9 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
