<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stars 3, Oilers 0  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME ARON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Brett Hull scored a goal that looked a lot like
his Stanley Cup winner last summer and assisted on another, leading
the Dallas Stars past the Edmonton Oilers 3-0 on Thursday night for
a 2-0 lead in their first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Muller and Scott Thornton also scored for Dallas,
continuing an early playoff trend of production from surprising
players. Hull is the only one of the Stars' top five scorers with a
goal in the two games.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton, which will have Game 3 of the best-of-7 series on its
home ice Sunday, managed only 17 shots as Ed Belfour posted his
eighth playoff shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit, though, goes to a Dallas defense led by
captain Derian Hatcher, whose steamroller hits frustrated the
Oilers and triggered several penalties on retaliatory hits.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton will be happy to get away from Reunion Arena, where it
has lost 11 straight. The Oilers are in jeopardy of a second
straight first-round sweep by the Stars, who have beaten Edmonton
in nine straight playoff games. Dallas is 9-0-1 in the last 10
overall meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Oilers goalie Tommy Salo, who made 30 stops in Game 1, again had
to be his own best defense -- and couldn't, even though he again
made the Stars earn their goals. He made 19 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Muller finished a perfectly executed 3-on-3 with Hull and Modano
by blasting a shot over Salo's left shoulder in the first period,
then Hull put in a bouncing puck from the lip of the crease with
2:05 left in the second. Thornton scored from in front of the net
on a rebound early in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's goal unfolded a lot like his last playoff goal, the one
that beat Buffalo in triple overtime in Game 6 of the 1999 finals.
</P>
<P>
   On that one, Hull was just inside the crease when he pushed in a
rebound past a fallen Dominik Hasek. This time, he was just outside
the crease and it was Salo on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's 24 goals this season were second-most on the league's
lowest-scoring team. Other than Mike Keane, who scored the first
goal in a 2-1 victory Wednesday night, the rest of Dallas' goals
have been by guys with single-digit totals in the regular season.
In fact, the combined total of regular-season goals by Muller,
Thornton and Roman Lyashenko is only 21. None of those three
players were with the Stars during last year's championship run.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, though, was of a star of it and he's off to another
impressive start. He set a record last postseason by allowing one
goal or less in 10 games and he's already done it twice this
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   He's been especially tough on Edmonton. The Oilers have just 12
goals in their last 11 playoff games against him.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton got into a good offensive flow early, but couldn't
sustain it very long. The Oilers were held to one shot on four
power plays while leading scorer Doug Weight went scoreless against
the Stars for a fifth straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton was more aggressive on defense, hitting often while
holding Dallas to 10 fewer shots than Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were again without Jere Lehtinen, their best defensive
forward until an ankle injury limited him to 17 games. He's still
too sore after testing it Sunday in the regular-season finale. He
might play Sunday, when Dallas also hopes to have back defenseman
Sergei Zubov from a torn knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton's Ethan Moreau, who missed the third period of Game 1
with a bruised thigh, was back on the ice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
