<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BP Amoco, Arco Merger Approved  </HEADLINE>
By T.A. BADGER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- More than a year after BP Amoco PLC
started its takeover of Atlantic Richfield Co., the path is finally
clear.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission voted Thursday to step out of the
way of the $27.6 billion deal after BP Amoco agreed to sell all of
Arco's Alaska assets to satisfy anti-competitive concerns.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco has a tentative agreement to sell the Alaska holdings --
oil and gas interests, tankers, pipelines and exploration rights --
to Phillips Petroleum Co. for $7 billion. That sale must be
completed within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco said it expects to complete its purchase of Arco on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sir John Browne, chairman of London-based BP Amoco, said he
planned to ''rapidly implement the plans we have in place to
integrate our operations worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be the second-largest oil company not owned
by a government, behind Exxon Mobil Corp., a merger approved by the
FTC last November.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement with FTC, BP Amoco also must sell some
pipeline and oil storage holdings in Cushing, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   Once the merger goes through, Arco shareholders would get 1.64
shares in BP Amoco for each share they hold.
</P>
<P>
   FTC approval came after months of intense negotiations over how
to resolve concerns about impact of the BP-Arco merger on
competition in the Alaska oil fields and the West Coast retail
gasoline market.
</P>
<P>
   In February, FTC lawyers blocked the merger and prepared to
battle it in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   They said the combination would create ''a colossus'' that would
dominate oil exploration, production and transportation in Alaska
and dictate prices to West Coast refiners, which rely heavily on
Alaska crude.
</P>
<P>
   The divestiture agreed to Thursday would reduce the combined new
company's holding in Alaska from roughly 70 percent to 45 percent,
according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the five FTC commissioners said in a statement
that the consent agreement with BP Amoco ''would entirely eliminate
the overlap ... that allegedly would create a competitive
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky and one of the commissioners,
Mozelle Thompson, issued a separate statement expressing support
for the merger but concern that it would not restrict BP Amoco
exports of Alaska oil.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Exxon Mobil said Thursday it had reached an
agreement with the companies over the sale of the Alaska holdings.
Exxon Mobil had filed a lawsuit seeking an injunction against the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, California, Washington and Oregon, which together
filed a separate antitrust complaint in federal court in San
Francisco against the merger, also announced settlement of their
action, ending any challenge to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, approval of the BP Amoco-Arco combination was met
with considerable relief.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully that will be the end of a long and painful chapter
of regulatory overview ... so we can go back to work,'' Gov. Tony
Knowles said in Juneau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
