<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors in line for higher reimbursement under Medicaid  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- As anyone who has spent time lately in a
hospital emergency room in New York knows, patients are often
present who need immediate attention and there are others whose
complaints are something less than emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials argue that the reason for setting up emergency
rooms was to treat people beset by health crises: car crash and
heart attack victims, kids and adults who break bones playing
sports. It is a distortion of the purpose of emergency rooms to
have them frequently providing treatment for minor cases of the flu
or colds or minor hurts like splinters or ingrown nails, they
argue.
</P>
<P>
   Yet advocates for the poor, for hospitals and for doctors agree
that emergency rooms have become the routine treatment centers of
choice in New York for Medicaid recipients because physicians in
general practice have basically closed their office doors to those
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's ridiculous,'' said Jeannie Cross, a spokeswoman for the
state Healthcare Association, which represents hospitals. ''I don't
think there's a hospital in the world that wants to see people
coming in the ER who should be going to physicians' offices.''
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of reversing that years-long trend, the new state
budget will include a boost in the reimbursement rate to doctors
for routine office visits from a minimum of $7 to about $30.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the state Medical Society, Dr. John Ostuni,
said the ''fee-for-service'' schedule due physicians under Medicaid
has essentially not changed since the program's inception more than
30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''No changes for inflation,'' Ostuni said. ''No changes for
increased overhead costs due primarily to the high medical
malpractice premiums. No changes for the increased paperwork and
other expensive administrative requirements of the Medicaid
program.''
</P>
<P>
   A $7 reimbursement -- it can range up to $18 for visits involving
more extensive treatment -- is unfair by almost any standard, the
Medical Society said.
</P>
<P>
   The same doctors who get $7 for seeing Medicaid patients in
upstate New York get just over $31 for a routine office visit for a
Medicare-covered patient and almost $38 for seeing someone covered
by Workers' Compensation. Illinois pays its doctors $30 for a
routine office visit under Medicaid, Florida $25, Texas $22.84,
Massachusetts $21.85, Pennsylvania $20 and California $18.18,
according to New York Medical Society figures.
</P>
<P>
   There was a method behind New York allowing the
''fee-for-service'' schedule to lag, according to state Assemblyman
Richard Gottfried, a Manhattan Democrat who chairs his chamber's
health committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature and health administrators did not want to
encourage the operation of ''Medicaid mills,'' he said. They are
doctors' practices specializing in the quick and substandard
treatment of patients covered by Medicaid. The philosophy behind
those offices was to see as many patients as possible to maximize
the reimbursements due doctors through the Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   Gottfried said those concerns have eased.
</P>
<P>
   ''Medicaid mills are rarely seen anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is $30 enough to bring substantial numbers of doctors back into
the business of seeing Medicaid patients in New York?
</P>
<P>
   Ostuni, the Medical Society president, has assured legislators
it would be.
</P>
<P>
   ''The re-involvement of physicians in Medicaid will, for the
first time in memory, actually provide Medicaid beneficiaries with
all of the advantages of a true 'medical home,''' he said. By a
''medical home'' Ostuni meant a place in the sense that middle- and
upper-income New Yorkers think of their doctors' offices, as places
to go when they are sick and also where they can get things like
vaccinations and flu shots so they can avoid getting sick.
</P>
<P>
   Gottfried said ''time will tell'' whether the $30
fee-for-service is enough to compel many more doctors to start
seeing Medicaid patients again. But he said it is clear the number
of doctors willing to do so for the $7 fee has dropped to ''nil.''
</P>
<P>
   The state is anticipating that the fee increase will work. State
legislators approving the new fee said it will be ''revenue
neutral,'' meaning that the state will offset the higher costs of
the fee by savings through Medicaid recipients making fewer
emergency room and clinic visits.
</P>
<P>
   Those trips can cost the Medicaid program $100 or more, making
an increase in the fee-for-service to $30 seem like a bargain -- if
more Medicaid patients avail themselves of the supposedly greater
opportunities to see general practitioners in their offices.
</P>
<P>
   Only half-jokingly, Assembly Minority Leader John Faso,
R-Columbia, asked this week whether redirecting more Medicaid
patients to doctors' offices wouldn't create ''problems'' elsewhere
in New York's health care system.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wonder next year whether we're going to be faced with a
plea from the clinics to compensate them for their lost business,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko first covered New York state government for The
Associated Press in 1981. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165,
Capitol Station, Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 0046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators agree on airport revitalization plan  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators say they have agreed on an
airport revitalization plan to fund facility improvements and
subsidize the often expensive cost of in-state airfares in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan announced Thursday, the state will spend $113
million on improvements over the next five years to airport
terminals, runways and access highways. Combined with $487 million
from the federal government and municipalities around the airports,
the program will total $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed ''NY SOARS,'' the Statewide Opportunities for Airport
Revitalization program was introduced by Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno, who said it would boost business in New York, which
has been plagued with air fares that rank among the highest in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Improving airport facilities will increase traffic and
stimulate competition among air carriers, ultimately lowering costs
to business and leisure travelers,'' Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Airports would have to apply for the funding, which would be
administered through the state Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative conference committees have been working to reach a
deal on a budget for the 2000-01 fiscal year that began April 1. By
Thursday evening, only the committee on education still had not
resolved its outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said the members of
that committee should agree by Monday morning. The two legislative
leaders also said they expect to settle a $1.2 billion tax-cut deal
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Those were regarded as the last two hurdles before sending the
spending plan to the full Legislature for a vote. Silver and Bruno
say they want to finish adopting a budget by the start of Passover,
at sunset next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other agreements reached Thursday by legislators, usually in
consultation with Gov. George Pataki's negotiators:
</P>
<P>
   --Revenue-sharing aid will be reintroduced for counties for the
first time in more than a decade. It was eliminated by former Gov.
Mario Cuomo amid tight fiscal times in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The new aid is designed to cover the counties' share of
additional funding created by new programs in the Health Care
Reform Act 2000 (HRCA), which the Legislature and governor approved
in December. Counties complained the new charges amounted to
unfunded mandates while Pataki argued that the counties' share of
revenues through the tobacco settlement plus hundreds of millions
in cost-savings created by the state gives counties the resources
to meet the HCRA costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be sufficient to cover the counties' HCRA
contributions,'' Silver said of the revenue-sharing aid.
</P>
<P>
   --New York's biggest cities outside of New York City will get
special aid in the budget: Buffalo ($20.5 million), Rochester ($15
million), Yonkers ($15 million), Syracuse ($10 million) and Albany
($4.5 million, in the form of a payment in lieu of taxes the city
does not collect on the sprawling Empire State Plaza office
complex.)
</P>
<P>
   --The Metropolitan Transportation Authority will get a special
allocation of $45 million, money legislators said would preclude
the need for a toll hike over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   --The Legislature recommended restoring $34.9 million in road and
bridge aid to localities under the program known informally as
''CHIPS.'' Pataki did not recommend funding for the program in his
budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   --Money will be appropriated to allow the state's Conservation
Fund to end the new fiscal year with a surplus of $4 million. That
will eliminate the need for increases in hunting and fishing
license fees for at least the next year, legislators said.
</P>
<P>
   --The Legislature will appropriate $1 million to help create a
marine pathology laboratory on Long Island, probably at Stony
Brook, to study the current blight of lobsters and other marine
life issues in the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   --The Legislature will not switch control of the state canal
system from the state Thruway Authority to another state agency
such as the Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation,
as had been recommended by some legislators. However, $100 million
in state aid will be available for improvements on the canals -- an
allocation legislators said should prevent toll hikes on the
Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Joel Stashenko contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 0046 </TRAILER>
