<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dog destroyed by judge's order but man on bench getting bit  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- It's the dream of every citizen startled by
a dog galloping amok: ridding the planet of the annoying mutt.
</P>
<P>
   But now a judge, who, allegedly without a hearing and no
witnesses other than himself, ordered the destruction of his
neighbor's 12-year-old beagle ''Baby'' because he saw it one day
running loose, is being accused of abusing that power.
</P>
<P>
   The state Commission on Judicial Conduct on Thursday recommended
removing Buckley from serving as justice in the town and village
courts of Dannemora, near Plattsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Baby's case was one of nine instances of alleged misconduct by
Buckley that were cited by the eleven-member panel. Buckley was
also accused of swearing at defendants and denying them fundamental
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''This record portrays a biased judge who routinely denies
defendants their fundamental rights and ignores proper criminal
procedure,'' the commission ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, 73, a retired phone worker, has been justice of
Dannemora's Town Court since 1987, and an acting Village Court
justice since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's ruling included an account of the judge writing
in his docket that he charged and forgave one defendant without the
accused ever being aware of the charge. He is also accused of more
than once refusing to recuse himself on cases with which he was
personally involved.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges against Buckley:
</P>
<P>
   --In 1997, the judge allegedly misinformed a person heading to
jail of the day a tuberculosis test was given. The test was
mandatory for the person's entry to the jail. The court record says
that when the defendant explained why he had not reported for the
test, Buckley said he was not taking ''the (expletive) blame'' and
sent him to jail without bail.
</P>
<P>
   --Responding to one complaint, Buckley allegedly told the
commission there was something about a defendant that reminded him
of ''gypsy contractors'' so that he gave the accuser in the
harassment case, who was an acquaintance of the judge, more
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   --In one case, Buckley told the commission that he wanted to keep
a probate in jail for his own benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't want to know what I think'' of the ruling, Buckley
said Thursday when contacted at home. When told that his removal
was recommended, he said he agreed with the commission on that
determination and would not appeal to the state's highest court,
the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's all I can say that you can put in the paper,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley added that he is considering resigning. If the
commission's ruling ousting him from the bench goes into force,
Buckley would be prohibited from ever holding judicial office again
in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Buckley's judicial fate, it comes too late for Baby,
who was killed last year after the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was either that, or go to jail for her'' the dog's owner,
Mark Bordeau, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeau said that Buckley added insult to injury by his language
in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know any stupid ass that would go to jail over a
dog,'' the judge is quoted as saying in the commission's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Ten members of the judicial panel voted for Buckley's dismissal.
The other member was absent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 0047 </TRAILER>
