<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Lt. Gov. sues estranged husband over campaign finances  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Former Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross didn't
just lose the election when she ran for governor in 1998. She says
she lost her public reputation, prospects as a political candidate,
and private job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   She says she's also still mired in debt from the campaign and
all of it is partly the fault of her estranged husband, Wall Street
millionaire Wilbur Ross, since he reneged on a promise to finance
her campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross filed a lawsuit against Ross and his accountant
Tuesday, seeking at least $40 million in compensation.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross, who jumped parties and became a Democrat after
Republican George Pataki dropped her as his running mate, charged
that Ross deposited $2.25 million into her campaign account in
January 1998, but secretly had the campaign's accountant withdraw
it only days later.
</P>
<P>
   She says she did not realize the money was missing until just
before the 1998 Democratic primary, leaving her campaign in
disarray. McCaughey lost the primary to New York City Council
Speaker Peter Vallone and, running as a Liberal, the general
election to Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also charged that Ross coerced his wife into signing a
postnuptial agreement in August 1998. In exchange, he replaced
$500,000 of the campaign money. He filed for divorce a little more
than two months later.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed in state Supreme Court in Manhattan
and first reported by Newsday, also named the accountant, Arthur
Fox, and Fox's company, Fox P.C. Fox was simultaneously working as
an accountant for Ross and for the Betsy Ross Empire State
Exploratory Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pledge of financial support by Wilbur Ross was a
fundamental premise of ... her decision to place her political
reputation and future at risk in the costly race for Governor,''
McCaughey Ross' lawyer, Bill Wachtel, wrote in her complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel charged Thursday that Ross and Fox committed fraud by
continuing to report the campaign account had more than $2 million
in it until September. He charged the pair also acted illegally by
later saying the money had been invested in the Penn-Dixie Leasing
Company and failing to report that to the Board of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''While she's no longer the lieutenant governor, Betsy Ross
still feels she owes a duty to the people of New York to ensure
that the integrity of the electoral process is preserved
retrospectively and prospectively,'' Wachtel said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ross, a 62-year-old investment banker, denied their
client acted improperly and said the lawsuit is another example of
McCaughey Ross continuing to ask for money she is not entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   McCaughey Ross has asked a Manhattan judge that she be paid
$25,000 a month while he decides if the postnuptial agreement is
valid.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's been making these charges for two years and we believe
in the fullness of time they will be exposed as being as bizarre
and as empty as her political career,'' Ross' lawyer, Lawrence
Mandelker, said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no mystery and no irregularity involved except in her
mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The name-calling is nothing new for the 52-year-old McCaughey
Ross, who was dogged by allegations from Pataki's administration of
being unstable and erratic.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel brushed aside the name-calling and said his client is
ready to meet with state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer as soon as
possible to determine what illegal acts took place.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ultimate beneficiary of a campaign committee is the people
of New York. They're the ones who have been fooled with here and
the Board of Elections should be looking at this,'' Wachtel said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit asks for at least $15 million in damages from Fox
and Fox P.C. and $25 million in damages from Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel denied the figure is inflated, even though the lawsuit
states McCaughey Ross' campaign only has $90,000 in outstanding
debts. He said what Ross went through is worth compensation and the
campaign contribution should be returned.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and McCaughey Ross, now a senior fellow at the
Washington-based Hudson Institute where she studies Medicare,
married on Dec. 7, 1995. Their divorce is pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
