<HEADLINE> Legislators approve bigger Tuition Assistance Program  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Spending on the Tuition Assistance Program
will go up by $80 million under an agreement reached by state
legislators negotiating the 2000-01 state budget.
</P>
<P>
   According to the legislative conference committee on higher
education, Thursday's deal would mean more TAP grants for college
students in New York and more families eligible for the aid. The
state spent $600 million in the recently concluded 1999-2000 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, maximum TAP grants for freshmen and
sophomores would go up to $5,000 from $4,125. After one year, the
maximum grant would be $5,000 for all students.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also agreed to raise the TAP tuition cap from 90
percent to 95 percent of a student's tuition this year. Next year
the cap will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   TAP would be also be made available to households with incomes
up to $80,000 a year, up from the current $50,500 after deductions.
Tuition would be tax deductible and the amount the state provides
for each tuition grant would go up from the current minimum of $275
to $500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the maximum ''upper cut'' -- grant reduction for
juniors and seniors -- will be lowered from $200 to $100 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement will keep college in the picture for even more
college-bound middle and lower income families,'' said state Sen.
Kenneth LaValle, who headed the legislative conference committee on
higher education with Assemblyman Edward Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   TAP is the state's largest aid program for higher education.
About 259,000 students currently qualify for the grants.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday the committee resolved to:
</P>
<P>
   --Increase state aid to community colleges in the State
University of New York and City University of New York systems from
$2,125 per student to $2,250 per student.
</P>
<P>
   --Spend $10 million on ''opportunity programs'' -- a series of
initiatives designed to help students cope with college. That would
restore spending back to 1994 levels.
</P>
<P>
   --Raise funding for child care programs in SUNY and CUNY systems
by $4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   One issue still under discussion Thursday was how much the state
will spend to help SUNY and CUNY hire additional full-time faculty.
Sullivan said funding would be ''more than last year, but we don't
know how much yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are working to iron out the details of the state
budget which was supposed to have been in place starting April 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 0047 </TRAILER>
