<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assemblyman accused in bizarre burglary case goes to jail  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENESEO, N.Y. (AP) -- A New York assemblyman accused of breaking
into a female aide's home and making long-distance telephone calls
agreed to a felony plea deal that ends his 28-year political career
and puts him in jail for up to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have done some terrible, wrong things -- I have brought shame
upon my colleagues, my family, people who trust me,'' Jerry
Johnson, 57, said in pleading guilty Thursday to second-degree
attempted burglary and drawing a six-month sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plea, Johnson also will admit next week to a second
attempted burglary count in return for another six-month sentence
to be served right after his first sentence. He was taken away in
handcuffs to a jail outside his constituency.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of second-degree burglary, he could have been
sentenced to five to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican who began his political career in 1972, Johnson was
elected to the first of four terms in the state Assembly in 1992
and was up for re-election in November. His mainly rural district
extends across Livingston, Monroe and Allegany counties in western
New York.
</P>
<P>
   By failing to resign his seat by April 1, his successor will not
be selected until the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a case that cried out for understanding,'' said
defense attorney John Parrinello. ''But unfortunately in today's
world, there aren't many people out there that want to understand.
His conduct appears totally aberrant, but he's going to deal with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began in December when the woman, Bonnie
Turner, told police her pocketbook had been stolen from her car.
Authorities turned up evidence that Johnson broke into her house
Oct. 22 and placed an unspecified number of long-distance telephone
calls. The second burglary charge arose from a similar break-in on
Jan. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of immediately surrendering to authorities, Johnson
booked into a psychiatric center in Buffalo on Jan. 27 with the
approval of Livingston County Sheriff John York, a personal friend.
Two weeks later, he pleaded innocent and was freed on $10,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   His plea places him on five years' probation and orders him to
keep away from Turner, who lives near this village 35 miles south
of Rochester. He also paid $804 to cover the cost of the telephone
calls and other damages at her home, and he agreed to continue
mental-health counseling at Steuben County Jail in Bath, 50 miles
south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Before sentencing, the defense noted that Johnson had resigned
his Albany post within the previous 24 hours, but Johnson
automatically relinquishes office on becoming a felon.
</P>
<P>
   His voice quavering with emotion, Johnson turned toward Turner
in the public gallery and solemnly apologized.
</P>
<P>
   A Rochester television station, ABC affiliate WOKR-TV, said
Turner alleged that Johnson stalked her, made harassing phone calls
and broke into her home to steal her underwear.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the U.S. Air Force, Johnson worked his way up
the ranks at Genesee and Wyoming Railroad to become general manager
in 1977. He was elected to an education board in 1972 and later
became a councilman and then town supervisor in the village of
Nunda.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, he was a ranking minority member of the mental health
committee in Albany. He is divorced and has three daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 0048 </TRAILER>
