<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Co. Ordered To Lower Fly Outbreaks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, Ohio (AP) -- The nation's fourth largest egg distributor
was ordered Thursday to reduce fly infestations that neighbors
complained interfered with their everyday activities.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye Egg operates several barns in Ohio and ships to
restaurants and groceries in 20 states. Its 15 million chickens
produce 2.4 billion eggs a year, 4 percent of the nation's total
production.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye Egg must take steps to eliminate the problem within 90
days, although the judge did not specify a penalty. The judge
prohibited construction permits for new egg facilities until the
steps are taken and ordered the company to monitor fly populations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the failure of the defendants to properly manage
the manure at their facilities, the neighbors in the surrounding
area live in misery as a result of house fly outbreaks,'' Common
Pleas Judge Gregory Frost said.
</P>
<P>
   The action is part of a lawsuit the state filed Dec. 1 that
accused the company of dumping dead chickens in a field, polluting
creeks and causing infestations of flies and other insects.
</P>
<P>
   The company said implementing all of the steps could force it
into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye Egg Chief Executive Officer Bill Glass declined to
comment on Frost's 18-page ruling until he had read it. He said the
company plans to follow environmental laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
