<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 More L.A. Convictions Dismissed  </HEADLINE>
By LEON DROUIN KEITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A judge Thursday reversed 10 more convictions
tainted by the expanding police corruption scandal, including those
of four people whose criminal records triggered deportation.
</P>
<P>
   The reversals raise to 60 the number of convictions dismissed at
the request of prosecutors who are scrutinizing criminal cases for
involvement of officers under investigation for framing, beating
and shooting innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys said they would seek help from the U.S.
Attorney General Janet Reno for those who were deported after being
wrongly convicted.
</P>
<P>
   They include Israel Cid, who was a legal U.S. resident before
his arrest but now makes $80 a week in Yucatan, Mexico. Cid, 24,
was raised in the United States and English is his primary
language, attorney Gregory Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though his conviction on a probation violation has been
overturned, ''our client is sitting in Mexico,'' Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman Sharon Gavin
said each case will be looked at individually to see whether the
defendants should be allowed back into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal is focused on the police department's Rampart
station and emerged when ex-officer Rafael Perez, a member of an
anti-gang unit, offered cooperation in exchange for a lenient
sentence for stealing cocaine from an evidence locker.
</P>
<P>
   Some two dozen Rampart officers have quit, been fired or
relieved of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan vowed Thursday to root out police
corruption as the scandal's shadow dimmed his annual
state-of-the-city address.
</P>
<P>
   ''On this you have my word,'' Riordan said. ''We will
investigate corruption in the Los Angeles Police Department. We
will expose it and we will eradicate it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
