<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Lawyer Faces Extradition  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- He's a Colombian attorney, a leader in a
drug eradication program in his country and he now faces
extradition on cocaine trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Manuel Tafur Dominguez, 36, has been held in a
Philadelphia jail since his March 4 arrest, accused by Colombian
officials of arranging a shipment of nearly 7 tons of cocaine to
Spain by way of Jamaica and Cuba. The shipment was seized at the
port of Cartagena, Colombia, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Charles B. Smith on Thursday expressed
doubts about the case against Tafur as he granted him $350,000
bail. Tafur, who has been wanted by Colombian authorities since
September, probably won't be released until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on the information I have now, if he's in jail another
30 days I won't sleep well,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   An extradition hearing for Tafur had been scheduled for Thursday
but was postponed at the request of U.S. prosecutors so the
Colombian government could submit more evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur would be the first fugitive sent to Colombia on drug
charges since the United States and Colombia signed the extradition
treaty in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty, in force since 1982, was written in part by Tafur's
father, Donald Rodrigo Tafur, a former senator who was shot to
death in 1992 outside his son's home in Cali, Colombia, apparently
by drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Tafur had been an executive with a drug-eradication
program in Colombia called Plante, which encourages farmers to
cultivate crops other than coca, the plant used to make cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur was seriously injured in a plane crash in the Andes in
1999 and came to the United States last year to recuperate and be
near his mother, who remarried and moved to New Hope, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur enrolled in the environmental law program at Pace
University in White Plains, N.Y., where he is pursuing a master's
degree. His supporters include the Pace law faculty, which
submitted a brief on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a real travesty that someone like Victor could be
yanked out of a car and thrown into jail on basically no
evidence,'' said Ann Powers, a Pace law professor.
</P>
<P>
   The case centers on a payment that Colombian prosecutors say
Tafur made to a front company, E.I. Caribe, to arrange the drug
shipment. A police search of the E.I. Caribe office found checks
from Tafur totaling 560 million pesos, or about $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur's lawyers said he was engaging in a legitimate financial
transaction on behalf of his mother, Solita Rosade, who in 1998
received a payment of 560 million pesos from the pension of her
deceased husband. According to Tafur's lawyers, Rosade requested
that the money be converted to U.S. dollars and deposited in a
Swiss bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Calling it ''very ironic,'' Tafur's mother said she planned to
use the $350,000 for Tafur's bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0105 </TRAILER>
