<HEADLINE> Kings 130, Warriors 107  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Webber scored 22 points and
Vlade Divac had 15 points and 11 rebounds Thursday night as the
Sacramento Kings rolled past the Golden State Warriors 130-107.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento, seventh in the Western Conference standings,
increased its lead over idle eighth-place Seattle to one game with
four remaining, three on the road against playoff-bound teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings tied their season high for points and snapped a
three-game losing streak, the first time all season the Kings had
dropped three straight at home.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento led by six points after one quarter, stretched the
margin to 17 by halftime and were up by as many as 26 points in the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Hughes had 35 points and 12 rebounds for the Warriors, who
had won two straight. Reserve Sam Jacobson had a career-high 19
points and Jason Caffey added 11.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Anderson and Predrag Stojakovic both had 13 points, Tony
Delk scored 12 and Corliss Williamson added 11 for the Kings, who
made 33 of 46 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento made 9 of 13 shots in the third quarter and continued
going to the free-throw line frequently in building a 91-70 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings opened the third quarter with a 9-2 run, taking a
74-52 lead at the 8:20 mark on a close-range basket by Divac.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento used an up-tempo game to grab a 65-48 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Webber had 13 points and Divac scored 11 as the Kings scored 32
points in both quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' reserves had 24 points in the first half, including
20 in the second quarter, when they owned a 33-22 edge over the
Warriors.
</P>
<P>
Notes: It was Kings coach Rick Adelman's 428th victory, moving him
past Tommy Heinsohn and into 26th place on the career list. ...
Jacobson surpassed his career high in the first half, getting 17
points in 17 minutes. ... The Kings had 11 players score in the
half. ... Kings reserve Jon Barry fouled out in the fourth quarter
after playing just 11 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
