<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest made in gunpoint robberies involving children  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two officers on routine patrol unknowingly
arrested a man believed responsible for robberies of women in which
he allegedly pointed a gun at their children's heads.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Police Commissioner Howard Safir announced that the
officers nabbed the man Wednesday in a Brooklyn subway station
after he allegedly stole a gold chain. The suspect put up quite a
struggle -- for 45 minutes, he held onto the bottom of a parked
train while police tried to talk him into surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   The arresting officers did not immediately recognize the man as
a suspect who terrorized mothers and tots.
</P>
<P>
   ''I kept saying to him, 'There's no way to go, you're going to
get yourself hurt,''' said Officer Andrew Huksloot. ''It's not
worth it for a chain. You're going to get yourself electrocuted,''
Huksloot said he told the man.
</P>
<P>
   Once in custody, Detective Ronald Jackson noticed the suspect's
resemblance to a sketch of the man wanted for three recent gunpoint
robberies involving children.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way he tried to elude arrest, ''We knew something
else had to be going on besides just a chain snatch,'' said
Margaret Lynch, the other arresting officer.
</P>
<P>
   Lemar Jackson, 31, of St. Alban's, Queens, was charged with
robbery, reckless endangerment, endangering the welfare of a child
and assault. He faces up to 25 years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   One woman identified him as the man who put a gun to her
2-year-old daughter's head last week at a Queens subway station.
Two others did not make positive identifications; but police
insisted they had the right person.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old woman who identified Jackson had described at a
news conference on Monday how the robber threatened her child: ''He
put the gun to her head and told me he would blow her brains out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the woman said in a statement through her lawyer,
Steven Gildin of Melville, that the lineup had left her shaken. The
woman has said she intends to sue the city alleging the subway
station had no security.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was petrified. I am a little relieved that he is behind bars
where he belongs, but me and my daughter will continue to suffer
for a very long time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still can't sleep. I still feel like he is coming at me from
my shadows. My daughter even keeps acting out the horrible scene.
I'm afraid we will never get over this,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Queens District Attorney Richard A. Brown said the robber's
conduct ''is about as low as human behavior can get.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is incomprehensible that anyone -- no matter how desperate --
would put a gun to a child's head and threaten to kill the child in
order to rob the mother,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was convicted in 1994 for robbery and sentenced to up to
seven years in prison, said Tom Grant, Parole Department spokesman.
He was conditionally released in 1998, but jailed again on Dec. 31,
1998 for violating the terms of his release.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Jackson was released from prison, and on March 27, a
warrant was issued because he had not been reporting to his parole
officer, Grant said. Jackson has a criminal history dating back to
1985 for robbery, reckless endangerment and criminal possession of
stolen property charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
