<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Connects Enemies in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Fearing for his life in
possible Serb attacks, Besi grabbed a toothbrush and a change of
clothes and abandoned his home a year ago to become a refugee in a
neighboring land.
</P>
<P>
   Like many ethnic Albanians, Besi -- a muscular 25-year-old with
cropped blond hair -- begins to cry when he talks about years of
repression, the $20,000 stolen by Serbian border guards when he and
his family fled to Montenegro and widespread attacks on ethnic
Albanians and their property.
</P>
<P>
   While Besi does not count Serbs among his friends, he has begun
to do something unthinkable even a few months ago -- he is drinking
coffee with them.
</P>
<P>
   True, they are only colleagues at his job in a Western
organization based in this ethnically tense city. But he brews up
the sweet and strong beverage for his bitter ethnic enemies. It's a
start.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before it was very difficult,'' says Besi, who wants to be
identified only by the diminutive of his name. ''But now we drink
coffee together, although not outside the job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balkan ritual of coffee drinking was inherited from the
Turks, who ruled Kosovo for 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern side of this divided city, ethnic Albanians of
all ages bask in the spring sunshine drinking black coffee and
cappuccino. In the tatty sidewalk bars, they listen to a tinny
rendition of Tina Turner.
</P>
<P>
   They seem oblivious to French and American peacekeepers in
armored personnel carriers who guard a bridge across the Ibar River
-- the site of violent confrontations between the Serbs and ethnic
Albanians since the NATO-led force arrived in June.
</P>
<P>
   While the situation seems under control now, the threat of
renewed fighting is real, especially as summer approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I see that bridge, I go crazy,'' Besi said in fluent
English. ''I am still a refugee because Serbs live in my flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Besi returned to the city -- but not his home -- in July. He found
employment and a good wage at a Western agency that he does not
want identified.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dolce Vita bar in the northern sector of the city, a
handful of well-heeled Serbs are drinking coffee and playing cards.
Others are hanging around outside, keeping a watchful eye on the
bridge and the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   The silence of the streets in Kosovska Mitrovica north contrasts
with the muddle, mess and noise of ethnic Albanians and soldiers
going about their lives on the south bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kosovo is a holy land. We lost blood for Kosovo,'' said Dragan
Nikolic, a 20-year-old student. ''It is true that bad things were
done on both sides, but it was war.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0122 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
