<DOCNO> APW20000414.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Carolina Flag Bill Heads To House  </HEADLINE>
By LEIGH STROPE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- The Republican-controlled House now gets
its shot to settle the bitter fight over the Confederate flag
flying from South Carolina's Statehouse dome.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to move the flag to another location on the Statehouse
grounds cleared the Democrat-controlled Senate on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a step in the right direction,'' Republican House
Speaker David Wilkins said. ''I think it really is the only viable
alternative to resolve the issue with honor and dignity and
finality this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The House this week passed a bill to create official state
holidays recognizing Martin Luther King Jr. and Confederate
Memorial Day. Six weeks ago, the same bill failed after rancorous
debate that created racial and political rifts.
</P>
<P>
   The flag debate -- expected to begin within a few weeks -- could
be even uglier, said Clemson University political scientist Dave
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst battles are ahead,'' he said. ''The House is more
partisan. The discussions are going to be an awful lot more
vitriolic.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would remove the banner from the dome and place
a similar, square battle flag behind an existing monument honoring
Confederate soldiers. The flag would fly on the north side of the
Statehouse from a pole no taller than 20 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would remove the Confederate flags hanging in the
House and Senate chambers while protecting monuments, memorials and
buildings erected or named in honor of the Confederacy or civil
rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some black House members think the flag would still be too
visible. The National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People also doesn't support the compromise and has no plans to end
an economic boycott of the state that began Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ''adds insult to injury,'' said Nelson Rivers, field
operations director for NAACP and a former official in the South
Carolina conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're in a box,'' countered House Ways and Means Chairman
Bobby Harrell, a Charleston Republican who supports the flag. The
boycott won't mean much without the flag on the dome, he said.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is the only state that flies the Confederate flag
above its Statehouse. Opponents say it is a racist symbol, while
supporters say it represents Southern heritage and honors
Confederate war dead. Only the Legislature can take down the flag,
which has flown since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   NAACP: http://www.naacp.org/new/current.asp?currentsc
</P>
<P>
   Flag opponents: http://www.getinstep.com
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina Heritage Coalition:
http://www.kudzumedia.com/schc.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0122 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
