<HEADLINE> Poll: State voters favor Gore to Bush  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush must both
secure the backing of the state's large block of independent voters
and make education a priority to win support in Connecticut,
according to the director of the latest Quinnipiac College
presidential poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, released Thursday, found 48 percent of voters support
Democrat Al Gore, while 39 percent back Bush. The remainder were
either undecided, said they would vote for someone else or would
not vote at all, said poll director Douglas Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   He said the survey showed Gore ''has solidified his lead among
Democrats.'' The vice president handily won last month's
presidential primary over Bill Bradley. The poll was the first
since the March 7 primary and the first that gives the vice
president the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush led an October poll, 52 percent to 36 percent, but by
February, Gore had made up the difference, and each received the
support of 45 percent of those polled.
</P>
<P>
   The random phone survey questioned 950 registered voters from
April 5-10 and had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said Connecticut voters perceive Gore to be more
competent than Bush in two key issues -- health care and education.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the nation's strong economy is helping Gore, and
appears to outweigh any negative associations voters might have
because of his association with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to falter in his native state. He was born in New
Haven, while his father attended Yale. The Texas governor narrowly
lost the March 7 primary to Arizona Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz said survey respondents cited a number of reasons for
disliking Bush, ranging from his knowledge of foreign policy to his
preparedness to be president. Voters also were unable to name one
specific quality they liked about Bush, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is facing ''an especially big gender gap,'' in
Connecticut, said Schwartz. Gore leads Bush by 18 percentage points
among women, the poll showed. Schwartz said more women typically
vote Democratic, but the margin of difference between the two
parties is usually about 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also surveyed voters in New Jersey and New York and
reported similar findings. New Jersey voters favored Gore 50
percent to 37 percent. New Yorkers backed the vice president 53
percent to 36 percent for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman fared well in poll from both parties,
Schwartz said. Sixty-two percent of Democratic respondents want the
Democrat re-elected and 53 GOP voters favored Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   If Lieberman ran as the Democratic vice presidential nominee, 26
percent of the respondents said they would be more likely to vote
for the ticket, while 10 percent said they would be less likely to
vote Democratic and 61 percent said it would not make a difference,
Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac College: http://www.quinnipiac.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
