<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Approves $1.83T Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional passage of a $1.83 trillion
budget for next year clears one hurdle for Republicans, but also
signals the start of months of election-year battling with
President Clinton over spending and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   With only a handful of defectors, Republicans pushed their
spending plan through Congress on Thursday. The House approved the
measure by 220-208 and hours later the Senate gave its assent by
50-48.
</P>
<P>
   The budget, which sets Congress' overall tax and spending totals
but leaves details for later, does not need Clinton's signature.
But lawmakers will need his approval for the 13 annual spending
bills for next year they will start writing next month, plus for
any tax legislation they send him.
</P>
<P>
   The budget for fiscal 2000, which begins Oct. 1, defines
differences the two parties are certain to spotlight throughout
this year's campaigns for control of the White House and Congress.
Republicans would use much of the surplus from non-Social Security
programs for tax cuts, while Democrats want a smaller tax reduction
and more spending for domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the American Society of Newspaper Editors that the
GOP plan ''is loaded with exploding tax breaks and untenable cuts
in critical investments. It will take us back to an approach that
failed before and will fail again, back to ideas that didn't work
before and won't work now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., said the GOP plan ''puts us on
track for another appropriations train wreck in September,'' using
the technical term for spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans were equally scornful of the Democratic approach.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP favors tax cuts, said Senate Budget Committee Chairman
Pete Domenici, R-N.M., because ''If we don't do it pretty soon,
there will be no surplus left over to the taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., said the Republican budget plans a
prudent mix of tax cuts, debt reduction and spending on education
and other priorities ''without returning to the bad old days of
spending for today without any eye to the future at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Six Democrats and five Republicans defected in the House. GOP
Sens. Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island, James Jeffords of Vermont,
John McCain of Arizona and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania voted
''no,'' while Sens. William Roth, R-Del., and Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the budget marked the second straight year
Congress had done so by the April 15 deadline. The date is usually
ignored, but the quick action illustrates how GOP leaders are
determined to adjourn Congress early for re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would use the $1 trillion in expected Social Security
surpluses over the next five years to reduce the $3.6 trillion
publicly held debt, with the goal of eliminating it by 2013. The
rest of the $5.7 trillion national debt is money the government
owes Social Security and other federal trust funds.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists say such a dramatic reduction of the publicly
held debt would press interest rates downward and boost the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would use much of the rest of the surplus for a tax
cut of at least $150 billion and perhaps exceeding $200 billion,
depending on lawmakers' decisions and how much economic growth
occurs over the next few months. Democrats want a smaller tax
reduction, with more money set aside for domestic programs and debt
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican budget would set aside up to $40 billion over
five years for any new prescription drug benefits that lawmakers
add to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But action is not required, and the money could be used for
other changes, such as easing cuts in Medicare reimbursements to
many hospitals enacted in the 1997 budget-balancing deal.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties say they want to enact a prescription program this
year. Clinton wants it to cover all elderly Americans, while
Republicans want to limit it to lower-income people or those with
extremely high drug bills.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also calls for $311 billion for defense next year, $5
billion more than Clinton wants. And it would spend $289 billion
for domestic programs, about $30 billion less than Clinton seeks.
</P>
<P>
   Included would be increases for education, veterans and
biomedical research, though final decisions will be made in later
spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining two-thirds of the budget covers interest payments
on the debt, plus benefits such as Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The measure approved Thursday was a House-Senate compromise of
similar budgets each chamber had passed earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic victory for environmentalists, the compromise
dropped nonbinding language assuming that some money would be
raised by allowing oil drilling in Alaska's Arctic National
Wildlife Refuge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0230 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Battles Over Marriage Tax  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON, AP Tax Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a symbolic week of tax votes, senators
are leaving town for a 10-day break without passing a tax cut for
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The House, meanwhile, approved a bill scrapping the entire tax
code by the end of 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led Congress kept the focus on taxes during the
final week before the annual income tax filing deadline, which is
midnight Monday this year for most people because the traditional
April 15 date falls on a Saturday. Lawmakers then left for a spring
recess.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are again demonstrating to the American people: 'We are on
your side,''' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   By a 229-187 vote Thursday, the House passed a bill that would
scrap the federal tax code on Dec. 31, 2004, and set up a
commission that would set about finding an unspecified replacement
tax system by July 4, 2004. The measure goes to the Senate, where
it faces an uncertain future at best.
</P>
<P>
   But it gave House Republicans a chance to rail against the
complexity and unfairness of tax laws and against the Internal
Revenue Service, a favorite target especially during the income tax
filing finale.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it takes something radical to make changes,'' said
the prime sponsor, Rep. Steve Largent, R-Okla. ''It's time. We need
to just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While they didn't defend the current tax code, Democrats claimed
that Republicans want to replace the income tax with a national
sales tax that would hit poorer people the hardest and unwisely
impose a tax on goods and services sold over the Internet,
prescription drugs, clothes and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're going to pull something out by its roots, you have
to plant thoughtful seeds to take its place,'' said Rep. Anna
Eshoo, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republicans came up seven votes short of the 60
needed to cut off debate and proceed to the so-called ''marriage
penalty'' bill. The 53-45 vote forced GOP leaders to shelve the
measure for now, but Democrats support the concept and agreed it
would likely be brought up for debate later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not dead,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont. ''All they
wanted was a political issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said Democrats brought on the delay by insisting
on political points of their own by trying to offer amendments on
issues not directly related to the tax bill, such as a Medicare
prescription drug benefit and tax credits for college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democrats are obstructing this legislation like in-laws
involved in your honeymoon,'' said Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the marriage penalty has broad support across the
political spectrum, but Democrats and Republicans disagree on how
to do it and how much of the projected budget surplus it should
consume.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate GOP bill would gradually reduce taxes by $248 billion
over 10 years for married couples at all income levels, removing
the penalty now paid by 25 million two-earner households compared
with single people. The bill would also cut taxes for couples who
receive a bonus because one spouse earns more than the other and
would also permanently ensure that all couples who claim personal
credits, such as the $500 per-child tax credit, don't lose them to
the alternative minimum tax.
</P>
<P>
   The House earlier this year passed a 10-year, $182 billion
version and President Clinton has proposed fixing the marriage
penalty for couples who take the standard tax deduction at a cost
of $45 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The marriage penalty tax bill is H.R. 6. The bill to eliminate
the IRS is H.R. 4199.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
