<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Army To Battle Corruption  </HEADLINE>
By KATHY GANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan's army rulers made many
promises when they took power last year, but the one that that had
people dancing in the streets was their pledge to root out
corruption and recover billions of dollars in stolen state wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Army leaders say corruption has leached as much as $30 billion
from Pakistan, three times its annual budget. Billions of dollars
more is outstanding in loans to national banks.
</P>
<P>
   Given the job of sifting through mountains of files and
traveling to Switzerland and Britain for proof of wrongdoing by
former leaders was the army government's chief prosecutor, Farooq
Adam.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a massive job,'' he says, sitting behind a desk cluttered
with files, the vast majority of them marked ''most immediate.''
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is endemic in this nation of 140 million people where
the average income is about $400 a year. The leaders who dominated
the last decade of Pakistani politics -- Nawaz Sharif and Benazir
Bhutto -- both have been implicated in corruption cases.
</P>
<P>
   The army leaders who deposed Sharif in October have filed
several corruption cases against him.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Sharif's family business owes millions of
dollars to banks at home and abroad. Authorities say the former
prime minister has taken hundreds of millions of dollars from the
state through commissions and business deals.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, recently sentenced to life in prison on a hijacking and
terrorism conviction, built a sprawling marble palace outside his
hometown of Lahore. Government documents show he had the public
works department build a road, installed 600 telephone lines and
provided it with uninterrupted power supplies. He purchased dozens
of luxury vehicles and a helicopter -- all with government money.
</P>
<P>
   Adam, a former army major, spent five years in jail for plotting
a coup in the 1970s with fellow officers also frustrated over the
level of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were such innocents then. It was nothing like it is
today,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Adam says the level of corruption now is ''obscene.'' And the
job of tackling it onerous and fraught with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our directive is to clean out the system as much as possible
to enable a genuine democratic order to develop,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But people are impatient, and the euphoria that greeted the army
takeover has given way to frustration at the slow pace of the
cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want democracy now,'' says Raja Riaz, a storeowner in
Lahore. ''We want the army to get rid of all the corrupt people,
only then can anything change here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Mohammed Amjad, who heads the National Accountability
Bureau, told Pakistan's monthly magazine Newsline that the problem
is twofold: a lack of expertise in investigating white-collar crime
and a cash economy where transactions are conducted without
receipts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is that we are in a no-win situation. When we go
slowly, which we are deliberately doing, people become impatient,''
said Amjad. ''And if we start arresting people, the same people
turn around and say that we are doing so indiscriminately,
blindly.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups in Pakistan say the National Accountability
Bureau has trampled on basic rights, citing a harsh anti-corruption
law, crafted in large part by Adam, giving the accountability
bureau the authority to arrest and detain a person for 90 days
without charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the first one to admit that this is a tough law, even
draconian, but in our opinion and given the circumstances we are
confronted with we need this law,'' Adam said.
</P>
<P>
   Proving corruption is a tricky task in Pakistan, where
influence, status and family name often combine to stifle police
investigations, frighten would-be informants and ensure a hasty
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   When a case does reach the court it is generally accompanied by
cries of political victimization.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have gone out of our way and I have personally gone though
hundreds of files and discarded any case I thought was politically
motivated,'' Adam said. ''The fact is we are not here to send any
messages, we are here to try to clean up the system to allow for
genuine democratic rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Pakistan's highest-profile allegations have been leveled
against Ms. Bhutto, who was twice elected prime minister and twice
dismissed on charges of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Extensive investigations and mountains of documents say Bhutto,
her jailed husband Asif Ali Zardari and other family members and
colleagues stole as much as $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani court found Ms. Bhutto and her husband guilty of
taking kickbacks from a Swiss company and its subsidiary and
sentenced them to five years in jail, disqualified them from
politics and ordered them to pay more than $800 million in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bhutto says the documents in the case were fabricated and
she is appealing. Adam says the evidence is overwhelming and he
expects to win the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Pakistan news and information http://www.paknews.org
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan government site http://www.pak.gov.pk
</P>
</TEXT>
