<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Fires Help Pollute U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fires in northwestern Canada caused a jump in
air pollution as far away as Nashville, Tenn., a team of
researchers has discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ''For certain periods of time, the northern high-latitude fires
were the biggest source of the carbon monoxide pollution in the
eastern U.S. region we studied,'' said Gerhard Wotawa of the
University of Agricultural Sciences in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Wotawa and Michael Trainer of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration's Aeronomy Laboratory in Boulder, Colo.,
studied U.S. air pollution during the summer of 1995. Their
findings are reported in today's issue of the journal Science.
</P>
<P>
   Canada long has criticized the United States, contending that
pollution from factories in the central and eastern states flows
north.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Environment Minister David Anderson has estimated that
as much as half of Canada's air pollution can be traced to U.S.
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The new study shows that, at least in the summer of 1995,
Canadian forest fires were the largest source of carbon monoxide
and ozone pollution in the eastern U.S., more than 2,000 miles from
the source.
</P>
<P>
   Forest fires often occur naturally in remote high-latitude
areas, usually caused by lightning. During 1995 they burned over 17
million acres in Canada, an area half the size of the state of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Wotawa and Trainer centered their study in Nashville, Tenn.,
collecting data covering several nearby states.
</P>
<P>
   They traced the winds backward and found that high periods of
carbon monoxide in the region occurred in air that had originated
during specific forest fire episodes in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that carbon monoxide levels were nearly
doubled when the plumes of the forest fires passed through the
region. Sometimes, higher ozone concentrations also accompanied the
plumes. The researchers used additional data to show that the
influence reached air quality monitoring stations in Maryland and
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The summer of 1995 was one of the hottest on record in the
eastern U.S., and the forest fires added to air pollution levels
that were already quite high.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers added that similar situations were reported in
1981, 1989 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Science is published by the American Association for the
Advancement of Science.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
<P>
   American Association for the Advancement of Science:
http://www.aaas.org
</P>
<P>
   National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration:
http://www.noaa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
