<HEADLINE> FCC Turns Slamming To States  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under new rules adopted by the Federal
Communications Commission, state regulators will have the power to
pursue unscrupulous long-distance phone companies that illegally
switch people's service without their permission.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC adopted rules to combat the practice known as slamming
two years ago, but MCI WorldCom challenged the rules in court,
saying it wanted the commission to consider an industry plan to
address the problem. A judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia granted the company's request and issued a
stay to suspend the rules that had only been in place a month.
</P>
<P>
   But industry officials apparently never reached a consensus on a
plan, so the FCC decided Thursday that state regulators,
represented by the National Association of Regulatory Utility
Commissions, could act to enforce rules against slamming.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the FCC has received 80,000 complaints about
the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers feel a real sense of violation when they are
slammed,'' FCC Chairman William Kennard said. ''American consumers
... are entitled to have their long-distance carrier of choice
respected.''
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom spokeswoman Julie Moore said company officials had
not yet had a chance to review the decision and wouldn't make any
decisions regarding future legal action until they do.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've always maintained that the investigation and resolution
of slamming complaints should require an objective decision maker
and standardized rules,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that, should the FCC's rules come to fruition, ''We
hope the states will work together to standardize their
implementation of these rules.''
</P>
<P>
   NARUC, which represents state regulators, said 35 state
regulatory commissions have volunteered to enforce anti-slamming
rules and more are expected to do so. The FCC will handle cases
where states haven't taken the enforcement role, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the FCC reaffirmed that, when a consumer has
not paid the slamming company, the customer is absolved of paying
for service for up to 30 days after being slammed. When a consumer
has paid the slammer, the company must pay 150 percent of the money
it received from the customer to the authorized carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The authorized carrier will in turn refund 50 percent of the
charges to the customer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The absolution rules and repayment remedies contained in this
order completely take the profit out of slamming,'' Kennard said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC has fined slammers more than $4.3 million in recent
months and signed consent decrees to prevent future wrongdoing.
Kennard asked his staff to begin compiling a list of the most
egregious offenders and to publicize the company names.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   FCC: http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0235 </TRAILER>
