<DOCNO> APW20000414.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Ups School Safety Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN, AP Education Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If schools getting money for after-school
centers prefer to spend it on metal detectors and counselors, they
can do just that under a new proposal by House lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   A $2.4 billion federal grants program gives schools the
flexibility they want and need, say Republicans on the House
Education and the Workforce Committee, who approved the legislation
25-21 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats -- who lost several attempts to keep the
school-safety grants from dipping into Clinton administration
favorites such as class-size reduction, school construction and
classroom technology -- give the bill a flunking grade.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the bill) torpedoes after-school and summer extended
learning programs that boost test scores and reduce crime,'' said
Rep. William L. Clay of Missouri, the top committee Democrat. He
has promised to fight it when all House lawmakers consider the
grants next month as part of its work on the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats oppose the safety-grants plan because it abolishes an
education program aimed specifically to prevent hate crimes and
allows religious organizations offering safety and drug-prevention
programs to hire staff based on church membership.
</P>
<P>
   The measure continues the Gun-Free Schools Act, which requires
schools to punish all students caught with guns.The approaching
anniversary of the Columbine High School shootings often fueled
tensions for the lawmakers examining school safety for the past two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., failed to get her colleagues to
include trigger locks for guns in the bill, though they accepted
proposals that allow school districts to use grants to promote
child safety locks.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we are going to expel students from schools for having
guns, then we should educate children and parents about the
importance of using child safety locks,'' said McCarthy, whose
husband was killed by a gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Tancredo, R-Colo., whose district includes Littleton,
the site of the 14 killings by two teen gunmen, chastised lawmakers
who he said ''trivialized Columbine'' by using it to push ideas
such as computer grants.
</P>
<P>
   The real deal-breaker for the anti-voucher Clinton
administration was kept out of the bill. The plan by Rep. Pete
Hoekstra, R-Mich., would have allowed some of the money to be given
to parents for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Goodling, R-Pa., committee chairman, said this latest
round of education lawmaking continues the GOP mission of making
federal grant programs flexible because it ''puts the priority on
children rather than federal regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The education bill is H.R. 4141.
</P>
