<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Terrorism Victims Appeal For Help  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is opposing
legislation to make it easier for victims of terrorism to collect
multimillion court judgments by seizing frozen assets of nations
that sponsored the terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, championed by a group of former hostages and
families of terrorism victims, could ''cause the United States to
violate international obligations'' said Deputy Treasury Secretary
Stuart Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement to a House Judiciary subcommittee,
Eizenstat said Thursday that the bill could subject U.S. property
abroad to possible retaliatory confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton administration has continued to object to every
practical proposal we have made,'' complained former hostage Terry
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the former chief Middle East correspondent for The
Associated Press, is attempting to collect a $341 million federal
court award against Iran he received last month.
</P>
<P>
   His is one of a growing number of judgments awarded by U.S.
courts to former hostages and families of terrorism victims under a
1996 law that permits such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of the winning plaintiffs has been able to collect
-- largely because the Clinton administration has blocked their
attempts to tap into frozen assets of countries, including those of
Iran and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department ''has obstructed us every step of the
way,'' said Maggie Alejandre Khuly, whose brother, Armando
Alejandre, was one of four pilots killed in February 1996 when
their small planes were shot down by Cuban fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Khuly and other family members won a $187.6 million judgment
against Cuba in December 1997 that they have been unable to
collect.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got hit over the head with a hammer'' by the administration
when attempting to collect a $247 million judgment against Iran,
Stephen Flatow of West Orange, N.J., testified.
</P>
<P>
   Flatow's 20-year-old daughter, Alisa, was killed in a 1995
bombing in Israel while there as a college student.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Anderson was held in Lebanon and Flatow's daughter
killed in Israel, both have accused Iran of sponsoring the
terrorism that led to their ordeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Iranians are still in the terror business and our own
government has the dubious distinction of keeping them in it,''
Flatow testified.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, his wife and daughter won their judgment last month
from U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson after Iran failed
to show up for the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson later had Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers served
with papers seeking to obtain $41 million of the overall judgment --
representing compensatory damages -- from a fund containing frozen
Iranian assets.
</P>
<P>
   The fund contains money Iran paid for U.S. arms in the 1970s but
never received.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, currently a journalism professor at Ohio University,
said administration officials seemed sympathetic -- until Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright invited Iran to enter a ''new
relationship'' with the United States last month.
</P>
<P>
   The overture came after Iranian moderates gained seats in
parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''Phone calls were not returned, meetings were not held,''
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was held for 2,454 days, the longest of the captives in
Lebanon. He was abducted at gunpoint in March 1985 and released in
December 1991.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a bill that would limit the administration's ability
to block such judgments. It is sponsored by Rep. Bill McCollum,
R-Fla., in the House and by Sens. Connie Mack, R-Fla., and Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to send a strong message to terrorists and their
state sponsors that they cannot get away with murder,'' said
McCollum.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 3485.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0237 </TRAILER>
