<HEADLINE> USDA Offers Conservation Incentive  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration hopes some extra
cash will revive farmers' interest in a land-idling program that's
designed to curb runoff into lakes and streams.
</P>
<P>
   Just over 1 million acres is enrolled through the program, well
short of the administration's goal of reaching 4 million acres by
2002. The Agriculture Department announced Thursday it would offer
signing bonuses and other incentives totaling $350 million to
encourage more producers to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   The program, created in 1996, is restricted to strips of land
along waterways.
</P>
<P>
   ''Higher payments should persuade more landowners to
participate, protecting ever more environmentally sensitive land
along streams, rivers, wetlands and public water supplies,''
Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the program has been relatively low because many
farmers didn't feel it paid enough to compensate them for the loss
of crop and pastureland, officials say. The land must be kept out
of production for 10 to 15 years and planted to grass or trees.
Farmers receive an annual payment in return, which averages about
$80 to $120 an acre in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers will be offered an upfront bonus of $100 to $150 an
acre, depending on how long the land is to be idled, and the
Agriculture Department is going to pay more of the cost of planting
cover. USDA also is raising the annual rates for pastureland
enrolled in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may help, but that really remains to be seen whether it's
going to be a sufficient incentive to increase signup,'' said
Rosemarie Watkins of the American Farm Bureau Federation.
</P>
<P>
   More than half the land now enrolled in the program is in four
states: Illinois, Iowa, Montana and South Dakota. The program is
part of the larger Conservation Reserve Program, under which 31.4
million acres of farmland are idled nationwide at a cost of $1.3
billion a year. It's known as the ''continuous signup'' portion of
CRP because farmers can enroll at any time
</P>
<P>
   The incentive money is part of a proposal by the Clinton
administration to increase spending on farm conservation programs
by $2.7 billion over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Agriculture Department site: http://www.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0237 </TRAILER>
