<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Addresses Nation's Editors  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Asked by newspaper editors, President Clinton
turned aside the idea of seeking a pardon for any alleged crime in
the Monica Lewinsky and Whitewater investigations. ''I have no
interest in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton did not say unequivocally Thursday that he would
decline a pardon if Vice President Al Gore is elected and offers
it. Republicans seized upon the loophole as proof of Democratic
duplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again, Clintonian speak rears its ugly head,'' said
Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson. He called the
matter ''the question of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   During a question-and-answer session at the American Society of
Newspaper Editors annual meeting, Clinton spoke emotionally about
the impact of his affair with Monica Lewinsky -- and the impeachment
that it spawned. He said he did not want a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wouldn't ask for it. I don't think it would be necessary,''
the president said. ''I won't be surprised by anything that
happens, but I'm not interested in being pardoned.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart sharply criticized the
editors for their questions -- limited to four by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are purportedly reasonably intelligent people but I
think it demonstrates just how isolated some newspaper editors are
from the rest of the country,'' Lockhart said. ''They get a chance
to ask the president about anything, any challenges that face
America and ... the best they can come up with is two questions
about impeachment. The country has moved past this. Unfortunately
many major newspaper editors haven't. It may be some reason for
declining circulation.''
</P>
<P>
   In reply, N. Christian Anderson III, ASNE president and
publisher-chief executive officer of The Orange County Register,
expressed regret that the White House limited the number of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''All four questions were thoughtful and concerned issues that
are on the minds of many Americans represented by newspaper editors
who are much closer to their communities than Mr. Lockhart might
imagine,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   A pardon was a subject Clinton has never directly addressed.
Former White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff told the House
impeachment hearings in 1998 that Clinton would not pardon himself
nor accept a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in what his office said was a reference to Ruff's comment,
repeated that assertion in an appearance before the editors
Wednesday. The GOP's Nicholson accused Gore of distorting events by
saying Clinton had stated his position about possible pardons when
Clinton, in fact, had not.
</P>
<P>
   ''Surprise, surprise, Al Gore is twisting the truth,'' Nicholson
said. ''This is just another example of why Al Gore's credibility
is shot and why he can never be trusted with the presidency of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton remains under a legal cloud despite being acquitted of
perjury and obstruction of justice charges by the Senate last year
after his impeachment by the House. Independent Counsel Robert Ray,
who succeeded Kenneth Starr in the investigation of the Whitewater
and Lewinsky cases, has said he is weighing whether to indict
Clinton after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   It clearly irked Clinton to have this embarrassing issue arise
after a speech in which he boasted about the nation's booming
economy and criticized the Republicans' $1.83 trillion budget as
''loaded with exploding tax breaks and untenable cuts in critical
investment.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the Whitewater investigation ''a lie and a fraud from
the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has written the full story yet,'' he said, adding, ''I
can imagine why you wouldn't, particularly given the way a lot of
this has been covered.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've paid quite a lot,'' Clinton said. ''I struggled very hard
to save my relationship with my wife and my daughter. ... I made a
terrible mistake of which I am deeply regretful. But I think that
the average, ordinary person reviewing the wreckage left in that
would say that I paid for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended with a curt ''Next question'' -- only to be asked
whether he would devote a section of his presidential library to
the impeachment saga.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have to deal with it, it's an important part of it,''
Clinton said. ''But I have a slightly different take on it than
many of you do, or at least in the Washington media does. ... I am
proud of what we did there because I think we saved the
Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not ashamed of the fact that they impeached me,'' the
president said. ''That was their (Republicans') decision, not mine.
And it was wrong. As a matter of law, the Constitution and history,
it was wrong. And I am glad I didn't quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks to ASNE:
http://www.whitehouse.gov/library/PressReleases.cgi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0238 </TRAILER>
