<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LPGA Course Yields Low Scores  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Calif. (AP) -- A course that typically frustrates many
golfers was a bit more forgiving in the opening round of the Longs
Drugs Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Co-leaders Cindy Figg-Currier and Rachel Hetherington shot
6-under-par 66s at Twelve Bridges Golf Club to lead the tournament
by one stroke.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when Juli Inkster won with an 8-under total, only 10
golfers broke par over four rounds. Being pushed back two weeks on
the LPGA schedule has made the course drier and the weather more
agreeable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had heard they had good weather here and you can tell
because the course and the greens are in great shape,''
Hetherington said. ''The fairways are terrific and so are the
greens.''
</P>
<P>
   A tricky wind that gusted to 22 mph in the afternoon made the
course more difficult. There were 21 golfers who broke par, most of
them benefiting from morning tee times. Rain the night before
softened the greens and the winds were only a minor factor early
on.
</P>
<P>
   ''The greens were rolling nice in the morning, but they can get
quick,'' Figg-Currier said. ''I expected to play in a downpour. We
got a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Figg-Currier, who was also tied for the first-round lead a year
ago after shooting a 68, played in the first group of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Following a par at No. 1, Figg-Currier birdied the next three
holes. She finished with seven birdies and a lone bogey on No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Teeing off about two hours later, Hetherington also birdied Nos.
2 through 4. The Australian-born Hetherington caught Figg-Currier
with the last of six birdies at No. 16, making an eight-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   One shot behind the leaders was Michelle Bell, who had to take
the last three years off due to a serious problem with her immune
system. In the first morning group off the back nine, Bell had six
birdies. Her only bogey came when she landed in the lip of a bunker
on No. 16 and two-putted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The course played a lot longer than it did in the pro-am and
practice rounds,'' Bell said. ''The advantage was that the greens
held. You could really fire at the pins.''
</P>
<P>
   In a group at 69 were Brandie Burton, Jill McGill, Cristie Kerr,
Mhairi McKay and Carin Koch, who finished second in the 1998 Longs
Drugs Challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Juli Inkster and Se Ri Pak both shot 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Annika Sorenstam rallied after playing the front side 1 over.
She recorded her first birdie at No. 10 and rolled in a 25-foot
putt on the par-5 12th for an eagle. She finished with a 71,
getting her round going after she and her caddy scared a wild
turkey off the 10th green.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a lucky turkey, I wish I hadn't scared it away,'' said
Sorenstam, who made a long birdie after the turkey departed.
</P>
<P>
   Divots: Colleen Walker injured her hand and dropped out of the
tournament after playing eight holes. ... Two Hall of Fame golfers
struggled: Pat Bradley had a 76 and Patty Sheehan shot a 77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0239 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Players Battle Cold at Harbour Town  </HEADLINE>
By PETE IACOBELLI, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) -- Dan Forsman faced his toughest
critics at home. So Harbour Town was no problem.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old, who hasn't won since the 1992 Buick Open, had
to listen to his 10-year-old son, Thomas, ask him, ''Dad, are you
ever going to win again?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as he prepared to leave his home in Provo, Utah, for the
MCI Classic, Forsman said his wife, Trudy, sensed her husband was
torn about the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''My wife kept saying, 'Gee, why are you going? You sound like
you're kind of indecisive about going?''' Forsman said Thursday.
''And I said I really feel like I need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Good decision.
</P>
<P>
   Forsman had a 5-under-par 66 to hold a one-shot lead over Edward
Fryatt and Sean Murphy after the first round. Forsman said he
remembered how much he enjoyed the seaside setting, narrow fairways
and true greens of Harbour Town Golf Links.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the confidence, the 'C' word and I'm talking
confidence,'' Forsman said. ''That's really the essence of what
happened out there for me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Masters champion Vijay Singh and everyone who chased him through
Augusta National's azaleas last week couldn't keep up with Forsman
in the cold, windy conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, second last week, had an eagle and birdie through his
first five holes, but couldn't gain any more shots to end at 68.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III, a Harbour master with four MCI victories, was
tied with Forsman on the 18th hole. However, he sailed his approach
into the marsh bordering the green and took a double-bogey 6 for a
68.
</P>
<P>
   Things were just as unkind to others who fought for the green
jacket a week ago. Tom Lehman took double bogey on his final hole
for a 70, while Loren Roberts and Carlos Franco shot 73s.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe David Duval, Tiger Woods and Phil Mickelson were the smart
ones. They didn't show up.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was difficult out there, no question about it,'' said
Singh, who had a 70. ''But I was happy with the way I hit the ball,
kept myself focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Herron joined Els and Love at three under.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Beem, one of those uninvited to the Masters despite winning
last year's Kemper Open, was tied with Frank Nobilo at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Forsman may have been the luckiest one on the course. He started
early when it was merely overcast instead of the frigid wind that
Love, Lehman and Els faced coming in.
</P>
<P>
   After opening with a bogey, he birdied Nos. 4-7 and missed putts
within 15 feet on 8 and 9. He landed a sand wedge within 8 feet for
his final birdie on No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Forsman saved par on 18, known for its red-and-white striped
lighthouse in the background, with a testy 6-footer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stepped up and knocked this thing right in the heart,'' said
Forsman, who last led a tournament in 1998 when he lost to Duval at
the Disney event in Orlando, Fla. ''And I tell you what, it was a
great feeling to shoot five under at Harbour Town.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
