<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meyer Happy To Be Back at Boston  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL, AP Track Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Running 26 miles, 385 yards in a foreign country,
even in a field of about 18,000, can seem like a lonely experience.
Not for Elana Meyer in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old South African relishes running the Boston
Marathon, and Monday, in her fourth appearance in the prestigious
race, she will be among the top women's contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boston is my favorite big race,'' said Meyer, the third-place
finisher in 1994 and the runner-up in 1995 and 1997. ''When I came
here in 1994, it was my first marathon, so it's special to be back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't know what to expect in '94, but the whole experience
was great. So many people along the course cheering makes it
special. It helps a lot, from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer was so invigorated by the crowds that she ran 2 hours, 25
minutes, 15 seconds -- still her career best.
</P>
<P>
   Extra special for Meyer were the South Africans sprinkled along
the course from the little starting town of Hopkinton to the finish
line in the Back Bay section of Boston, urging her and making her
feel at home by waving their national flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes, I hear them shouting my homeland,'' she said.
''There are even some Afrikaneers. I can also hear them calling my
name. Yes, I have even met some of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last time I was here, me and Colleen De Reuck (also of
South Africa) were running alongside Fatuma Roba (of Ethiopia) and
there was some guy running with us with a South African flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston is not the only place where South Africans gather for
marathons. Last year, when Meyer ran in the London Marathon, there
were about 10,000 South Africans lining the route, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're not running in your home country, it's always nice
to get support,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer is popular wherever she runs because of her engaging,
peppy personality and her consistently strong performances. In
addition to her three top three finishes at Boston, she has
finished third at the 1998 and 1999 Chicago Marathons, fifth at the
1999 London Marathon and fifth at the 1997 Tokyo Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   She has had even greater success at shorter distances.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, she was the Olympic silver medalist at 10,000 meters.
In 1994, she ran a world-best 15:10 for 5 kilometers at Providence,
R.I., and won the Tufts 10K in 31:39. In 1997, she won the Kyoto
City Half-Marathon in 67:36 and the Cooper River 10K in 31:19. In
1998, she was runner-up at the World Half-Marathon Championships in
68:32. Last year she won the Kyoto Half-Marathon in 67:37 and
Atlanta's Peachtree 10K at 31:34, and this year, she won the Tokyo
Half-Marathon in 67:33 and the Sendai Half-Marathon in 69:04.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer missed the 1998 Boston race because of an inflammation of
the lower back, and was disappointed at having to withdraw at the
last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Boston has lifted her spirits and hopefully she
will be able to lower her time, and perhaps end Roba's three-race
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in good shape,'' Meyer said. ''I'll be very happy if I can
run my best race. Hopefully this will be my time to dip under
2:25.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking 2:25 might not even be good enough to win. Roba has run
2:23:21 and 2:23:25 the past two years, after making her Boston
debut in 1997 in 2:26:23.
</P>
<P>
   ''She knows the course very well,'' Meyer said of Roba. ''It
will be very hard to beat her. Anything shorter than a marathon I
can beat her. But in Boston, she has run some very good races.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, she can't keep winning Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Boston Marathon is such a great race with a lot of
history. I would like to win it. It will be good preparation for
the Olympic marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   In each of her previous lead-ups to Boston, Meyer trained in
Colorado Springs, Colo., with De Reuck and a group of other
runners. This time, she decided to train at home.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather is nice there this time of year,'' she said.
''It's a perfect place to train. It's better training at home with
your training partners and near your roots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you lose focus when you're away from home.''
</P>
<P>
   The spectators, especially the South Africans, at the Boston
Marathon Monday will not let Meyer lose focus or forget her roots.
They'll be there rooting for her, as usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
