<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top QB Prospect Is Low-Key  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RABY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Chad Pennington, expected to be the
first quarterback selected, is taking a low-key approach to
Saturday's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   No dining out at New York's finest restaurants. More like
hanging out with his family in Knoxville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being a Heisman Trophy finalist and throwing for 4,000
yards and 38 touchdowns last season, the Marshall quarterback isn't
getting the red-carpet attention QBs Tim Couch and Peyton Manning
received as the overall No. 1 picks in the two previous years.
</P>
<P>
   No, Pennington will be a lower selection in the first round, so
he plans to watch television with his parents -- with his cell phone
in tow.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will mean everything to me, because they've been at my side
my whole life,'' Pennington said Thursday. ''There's only one time
you experience this change from college to the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Not getting the same attention as Couch and Manning doesn't mean
Pennington isn't wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The team that appears the most interested -- the San Francisco
49ers with the 16th pick -- also is the team Pennington mentions the
most.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a quarterback, you couldn't go to a better place because of
the offensive history. Steve Young. Joe Montana, and the type of
receivers they always have,'' he said. ''It would be a fun place to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers need help at quarterback even if Steve Young returns
for his 16th pro season. Young suffered a concussion in October and
sat out the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh Steelers, with the eighth overall pick, also have
looked at Pennington. The Steelers haven't had a quarterback play
effectively since Kordell Stewart's first season as a starter in
1997. But the club is expected to go for help at wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Denver was thought to be interested in Pennington, but traded
away the 10th pick to Baltimore on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pennington led Marshall to a 13-0 record and top 10 ranking last
season. The academic All-America and former Rhodes scholar
candidate is known as much for his intelligence as his arm.
</P>
<P>
   He impressed scouts during interviews at the NFL combine. And
Carolina's George Seifert, who coached Pennington at the Senior
Bowl in January, even compared his leadership to that of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have called Pennington, who threw 24 touchdown passes to
Randy Moss in 1997 alone, the best available among an ordinary crop
of quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think versatility is my strong point. I think whoever picks
me will be pleased,'' Pennington said. ''I'm not a cocky guy. I'm
confident in my abilities and I take pride in being a team guy, a
team leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennington has received tips from the Indianapolis Colts'
Manning, Detroit's Charlie Batch and Chicago's Cade McNown about
getting acclimated to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest thing they tell me is to have fun and enjoy it,
because you're playing the game that you love,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Pennington, Marshall's Rogers Beckett is perhaps the
only other Thundering Herd player with a good shot at being
drafted. He's listed as high as the second-best safety available.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just hope somebody is willing to take that chance,'' Beckett
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0241 </TRAILER>
