<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Royals didn't need another game-ending home run
to win. Carlos Beltran's ninth-inning single was good enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who won their last three games on ''walk-off''
homers, kept up their string of last at-bat wins when Beltran's
single gave them a 6-5 victory over the Baltimore Orioles on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all about attitude,'' manager Tony Muser said of the
Royals' start, which included a 6-1 opening homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ''These guys grew up a lot last year,'' Muser said. ''They were
relaxed and methodical in spring training and focused on areas that
needed work. Now they are playing together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, who blew a 5-0 lead before rallying in the bottom of
the ninth, got game-ending homers the past three days from Johnny
Damon, Mark Johnson and Rey Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it's early, but the feeling we have in this clubhouse
is very special,'' said Mike Sweeney, who hit his league-leading
sixth home run in the first inning. ''The crowd sticks around, even
when we get down. It's an exciting time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In other games, it was New York 5, Texas 1; Tampa Bay 6, the
White Sox 5 in 12 innings; Boston 4, Minnesota 3; and Detroit 2,
Seattle 0.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, whose three-run, ninth-inning homer gave Kansas City a
7-6 win Wednesday over Baltimore, led off the ninth with a single
off B.J. Ryan (1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Damon followed with a sacrifice bunt and Carlos Febles walked.
Beltran followed with a single that dropped just in front of left
fielder B.J. Surhoff, whose throw to the plate wasn't in time to
catch Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ''We played some good baseball, and we played some bad
baseball,'' Orioles manager Mike Hargrove said. ''Realistically, we
probably should have won two out of three. But Kansas City is a
good ballclub, and hot right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken went 0-for-4, striking out twice -- including a called
third strike that ended Baltimore's four-run eighth inning -- and
remained four hits short of 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore tied it on Mike Bordick's single off closer Ricky
Bottalico (2-0) in the ninth, after Jeff Suppan matched a career
high with eight strikeouts over seven-plus innings for Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
Yankees 5, Rangers 1
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada hit a tiebreaking triple with the bases loaded and
Orlando Hernandez (2-0) shut down Texas on two singles for eight
innings.
</P>
<P>
   New York made it a rough homecoming for Kenny Rogers (1-2), who
gave up eight hits in Texas' first complete game this year. Back at
Yankee Stadium for the first time since pitching in pinstripes in
1997, he walked two in the sixth to set up Posada's hit.
</P>
<P>
Devil Rays 6, White Sox 5, 12 innings
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn's RBI single with two outs in the bottom of the 12th
helped Tampa Bay snap a five-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's line drive to left field off Tanyon Sturtze (0-1) drove
in Kevin Stocker from second base. The bullpen held the White Sox
scoreless over the last seven innings. Jim Mecir (2-0) got the
win.
</P>
<P>
Red Sox 4, Twins 3
</P>
<P>
   Wilton Veras drew a bases-loaded walk to break an eighth-inning
tie and Boston rallied to win at home.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Wells (0-1) loaded the bases in the eighth, but was helped
when Denny Hocking threw out Nomar Garciaparra at the plate on a
fly ball to left field.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Guardardo came in and walked Jason Varitek and Veras to
score the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Wakefield (1-0) got the win and Derek Lowe pitched the ninth
for his second save.
</P>
<P>
Tigers 2, Mariners 0
</P>
<P>
   Juan Gonzalez, making his first home start for Detroit, hit an
RBI double to break up a scoreless tie in the eighth inning.
Gonzalez, who hadn't started since the opener last week in Oakland
because of a right hamstring strain, went 2-for-4.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Halter drew a leadoff walk off Arthur Rhodes (0-1) in the
eighth before Gonzalez scored him easily with a drive up the
right-field gap.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Brocail (1-1) pitched one scoreless inning and Todd Jones
got his third save.
</P>
</TEXT>
