<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton cancels plans to chair Arab event, civil rights reportpostponed  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Hillary Rodham Clinton scrapped plans to headline a
charity dinner for an Arab-American group because Israelis were not
on the guest list.
</P>
<P>
   And a federal civil rights panel postponed discussion of a
report said to criticize Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's New York City
Police Department amid news that the panel's chairwoman had
contributed to the first lady's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights denied any connection.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Giuliani from denouncing the probe.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't take much to figure out this is a political
operation,'' Giuliani said Thursday after a campaign stop on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Newsday reported the panel's chairwoman Mary Frances Berry
contributed $250 last year to Clinton and another $300 to the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, which has pledged support
to her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Berry defended her donation.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have a right to make campaign contributions to anyone
they please,'' Berry said Thursday. She said she would continue to
participate in the commission's discussion of the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the report) is about Giuliani's office, not Giuliani. It's
about the police department in New York. It's not about Hillary
Clinton and it's not about the senatorial campaign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's spokesman David Aronson said it was unclear
when the draft report would be discussed and declined to explain
the delay. The report had been scheduled for discussion today.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission is preparing a report on the NYPD
that several sources say is expected to be highly critical and
could call for the appointment of a federal monitor to oversee the
department. The commission began its probe into the police force
last year in the wake of the shooting of Amadou Diallo and the
torture of Abner Louima at the hands of New York City cops.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing held by the commission in New York City last May,
Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir defended the police
force. But the Rev. Al Sharpton and others described the NYPD as
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of the commission were appointed by Democrats and
two by Republicans. The panel has no enforcement powers but can
make recommendations to the president, Congress and federal
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first lady canceled plans to headline a charity
dinner for an Arab-American group because representatives from the
Israeli Embassy were not invited. Several Arab states do not
recognize the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under these circumstances, Mrs. Clinton will no longer be able
to serve as honorary chair of the Mosaic Foundation event,'' a
statement from the first lady's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mosaic Foundation is made up of the wives of Arab
ambassadors to the U.S. who raise money for charity. This year's
dinner on May 3 is to benefit Save the Children. Clinton has served
as honorary chairwoman for the dinner for the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin called Clinton's
decision to back out ''a classic Clinton flip-flop.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously she's pandering for the Jewish vote,'' Serafin said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is courting New York's large Jewish population in her
bid for the U.S. Senate against Giuliani. She strained her
relationship with some Jews last year after a visit to the West
Bank. There, Clinton embraced Soha Arafat after the wife of Yasser
Arafat accused Israelis of using poison gas on Palestinian women
and children. The first lady distanced herself from Mrs. Arafat's
remarks the next day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
