<HEADLINE> House Republicans Break $1M Mark  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At least four House Republicans threatened
with the loss of their seats this fall have already raised more
than $1 million for their re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list is Rep. Jim Rogan, a California
Republican who is among the Democrats' top targets this fall. He
has taken in almost $4 million through March 31 and had almost $1
million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Congressional Committee released the
fund-raising figures in advance of Saturday's deadline for
reporting them to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''These record-breaking fund-raising figures clearly show that
Americans support the progress Republicans have made on issues
important to our families,'' NRCC spokeswoman Marit Babin said.
''People have responded to our message of reducing the marriage tax
penalty, returning local control of education and restoring
character and morality in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan was one of the House managers who presented the case for
impeaching President Clinton to the Senate. He had $965,000 in his
account as of March 31, compared with $255,356 at the same time two
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Rogan spent $1.3 million on his campaign, which he won
with 51 percent of the vote. This year, he faces a strong
challenger, state Sen. Adam Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   The other House Republicans who have broken through the
million-dollar mark include Reps. Anne Northup and Ernie Fletcher
of Kentucky and Heather Wilson of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Clay Shaw of Florida, facing a strong challenge from state
Rep. Elaine Bloom, had $1.3 million in the bank as of March 31 --
more than twice as much as the $530,127 cash on hand he had two
years earlier. Despite Bloom's candidacy, NRCC Chairman Tom Davis
of Virginia said he expected Shaw to win re-election.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats, while declining to release campaign finance
figures for most of their candidates, did tout the success of their
candidate for the Virginia seat being vacated by retiring
Democratic Rep. Owen Pickett. Lawyer Jody Wagner raised $337,000
during the first three months of 2000, compared with $264,000 for
GOP state Sen. Edward Ed Schrock, Democratic officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a huge deal,'' Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee spokesman John Del Cecato said. ''She has really stunned
a lot of people with how successful she's been. Her fund-raising
strength shows how much support she has in the district.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Cecato also cited former Rep. Jane Harman, trying to reclaim
the California congressional seat she gave up to run for governor
in 1998. Harman raised $863,000 during the first three months of
the year, compared with $820,000 for Republican incumbent Steve
Kuykendall, according to figures supplied by both parties. Harman
also had almost twice as much money in the bank, $700,000 versus
$370,000 for Kuykendall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
