<HEADLINE> Deal Reached on Health Appeals  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Patients denied care by their HMOs could
appeal the decisions to an independent review panel under a
tentative agreement reached by House and Senate negotiators working
on legislation to give patients more say about their health care.
</P>
<P>
   While a few key aspects of the appeals process have yet to be
worked out, members of a House-Senate committee said Thursday they
had agreed in principal that patients could have their disputes
heard by independent medical experts who would have the final word
on whether treatments or services should be provided.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we've made an awful lot of progress,'' said Ohio Rep.
John Boehner, a Republican committee member. The bipartisan group
has been working for more than a month to combine House- and
Senate-passed versions of a bill giving Americans more rights when
dealing with managed care organizations and other health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, review panels would be hired by health
plans according to a set of standards developed by the government
that would prohibit conflicts of interest between the panel and the
health plan and bar health plans from selecting reviewers that have
been promised incentives that would lead them to make biased
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Senate aides said health plans could contract with university
medical schools that would appoint doctors to consider appeals
according to their expertise. Cancer specialists would hear appeals
of cancer treatment decisions, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   The review panels would have two central duties. They would
decide whether patient disputes were eligible for the appeals
process and send appeals that were approved to be reviewed by
medical experts.
</P>
<P>
   No agreement had yet been reached on standards that reviewers
would follow in deciding whether disputes could be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a way to go,'' said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said services that are specifically not covered under
health plan contracts, such as cosmetic surgery, could not be
appealed. But if a patient's doctor thinks a treatment is medically
necessary even though the plan says it won't cover it, patients
could appeal to a review panel.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most important aspects of the agreement, lawmakers
have agreed that review panels are not bound by what the health
panel has defined as ''medically necessary'' treatments. They are
free to make an independent assessment of patients' cases based on
scientific studies and clinical evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans covered by managed care organizations are
concerned that, in their quest to keep costs down, HMOs are wrongly
denying care and turn down patients who take their complaints to
review boards controlled by HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, the Oklahoma Republican who chairs the
committee, called the appeals process ''a very significant
provision'' that would let patients in ''every employer-sponsored
plan in the country'' have the right to an external review.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's work is far from over. Still to be decided is
how many Americans will be covered by the federal protections and
whether patients will be allowed to sue health plans if they are
not satisfied with the outcome of the appeals process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0243 </TRAILER>
