<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program To Up Newsroom Minorities  </HEADLINE>
By DARLENE SUPERVILLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new education and training center and
encouragement for high school reporting are some of the steps major
journalism organizations hope will improve newsroom diversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Forum announced Thursday its commitment of $5
million to an ''aggressive national effort,'' including a $1
million partnership with the American Society of Newspaper Editors
and the Associated Press Managing Editors to recruit minorities for
the newspaper business.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ASNE said it will use a $500,000 grant from
the Miami-based John S. and James L. Knight Foundation to develop a
program to stoke interest in careers in the industry by renewing
and encouraging interest in journalism among high school students.
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives are in response to statistics showing a
negligible increase in the percentage of minority journalists. They
were announced during the newspaper editors' annual conference
here.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has been going on has not worked,'' said Charles L.
Overby, chairman and chief executive officer of The Freedom Forum,
a foundation devoted to a free press. ''We have got to look for and
embrace radically new ideas ... because the traditional approaches
have not worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper editors' association reported this week that the
number of minority journalists working at daily newspapers
increased in the past year by one-third of 1 percentage point, to
11.9 percent, according to its annual newsroom employment survey.
</P>
<P>
   But while the overall number of minority journalists increased,
the percentage of blacks in newspaper newsrooms dropped slightly,
the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Minorities make up about 12 percent of newsrooms but more than
28 percent of the U.S. population -- a disparity that has remained
unchanged from the mid-1970s, when they filled 4 percent of the
staff at newspapers and made up 19 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   N. Christian Anderson III, ASNE president and publisher of The
Orange County Register, said the emphasis on journalism in high
schools could be of help to smaller newspapers who are ''really
desperate for people and ... particularly desperate for people of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to partnering with ASNE and APME, the Freedom
Forum's plans include:
</P>
<P>
   -- A state-of-the-art journalism education and training center at
Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tenn., to aid the professional
development of minority journalists. It will seek students from
community colleges, schools without journalism programs and people
interested in switching careers. Under development, the institute
is expected to begin operating late next year.
</P>
<P>
   -- Other partnerships to create programs aimed at improving
newsroom diversity.
</P>
<P>
   -- Funding four ''diversity fellows'' to visit colleges,
universities and junior colleges with high minority enrollments to
find talented recruits for careers in print journalism.
</P>
<P>
   -- Expansion of its Chips Quinn Scholars program, a year-round
training program of paid internships and scholarships for minority
college students pursuing journalism careers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   American Society of Newspaper Editors: http://www.asne.org
</P>
<P>
   Knight Foundation: http://www.knightfdn.org
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Managing Editors://www.apme.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0244 </TRAILER>
