<DOCNO> APW20000414.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Logjam Broken on African Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of delay and tough negotiations,
legislation extending new trade benefits to African, Central
American and Caribbean nations finally appears headed for
enactment.
</P>
<P>
   Top House and Senate leaders, hoping to send off the
Clinton-administration-backed bill before tackling an even more
contentious China trade package, reached tentative agreement
Thursday night on a proposed compromise.
</P>
<P>
   According to participants, House leaders agreed to a Senate
proposal to give Caribbean and Central American nations many of the
same duty-free benefits to be extended to sub-Saharan African
nations.
</P>
<P>
   And House negotiators, in turn, agreed to some Senate
restrictions on apparel imports designed to protect the
hard-pressed U.S. textile industry.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., hailed the acceptance of
''the parameters of an agreement'' after the deal was worked out in
a private meeting among top House and Senate leaders in the office
of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert said he hoped for a vote ''as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spokesman John Feehery said the speaker hoped the
compromise measure could be brought up after Congress returns from
its spring recess later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''The speaker believes this is a good deal for the American
consumer,'' Feehery said.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise was also endorsed by Rep. Charles Rangel of New
York, the senior Democrat on the House Ways and Means Committee,
which has jurisdiction over trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good tentative agreement,'' Rangel spokesman Dan Maffei
said. ''Congressman Rangel was confident that what was outlined
will pass both houses.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed the House and Senate last year in
significantly different forms, has been subject to intense
negotiations since November.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal must next be approved formally by negotiators
from each chamber. But with the bipartisan blessing of both the
Republican and Democratic leaders, this was not viewed as a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some details of the deal were sketchy, but those close to the
negotiations said House leaders agreed to accept a more expansive
Senate version in terms of countries covered.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed bill only dealt with the 48 countries of
sub-Saharan Africa. The Senate bill -- and now the compromise --
covers these nations, plus 24 Caribbean and Central American
nations as well.
</P>
<P>
   In another compromise, House leaders agreed to go along with a
cap on the volume of goods to receive duty-free treatment, while
Senate leaders agreed to lower restrictions than in the original
Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders also agreed to drop a Senate-passed requirement
that African-assembled apparel use U.S. fabric and thread, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the poorest countries in Africa would be eligible
for duty-free treatment in U.S. markets with no restrictions for
four years, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts manufactured in Caribbean and Central American
countries would be subject to some restrictions not applied to
other apparel, however, in a nod to U.S. textile manufacturers,
said congressional officials who spoke on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has made the Africa bill a top trade priority.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and congressional leaders hoped to
handle the measure before taking up an even more contentious trade
bill later in the spring, extending permanent trade benefits to
China to help ease the way for China's entry into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The Africa-Caribbean-Central American legislation would lower or
eliminate tariffs and quotas on products from the regions covered
as well as marking it easier for U.S. businesses to invest.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation has been opposed by senators from textile
states, who contended it would harm America's garment industry, and
by labor and environmental groups that said it failed to set
standards for protecting workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The bill, H.R. 434, may be found at
http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0245 </TRAILER>
