<HEADLINE> NHL Playoffs Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Jaromir Jagr has good reason to doubt the importance
of home ice
in Pittsburgh's quirky playoff series with Washington.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Home-ice advantage doesn't mean anything. We proved that
tonight,'' the Pittsburgh star said Thursday night after the
Penguins' 7-0 victory in Washington, the Capitals' worst playoff
loss ever.
</P>
<P>
   Because of scheduling problems in Pittsburgh, the seventh-seeded
Penguins will be home for Games 2 and 3 in the Eastern Conference
first-round series. Usually, the higher-seeded team is home for the
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's victory came two days after Washington coach Ron
Wilson said he would be willing to play all seven games in
Pittsburgh and would ''go in there and beat 'em anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't sit well with the Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was up on the bulletin board,'' Pittsburgh right wing
Matthew Barnaby said. ''It definitely made us angry. You want to be
taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other Eastern Conference openers Thursday, Philadelphia
beat Buffalo 3-2 and New Jersey edged Florida 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western Conference, defending Stanley Cup champion Dallas
beat Edmonton 3-0 to take a 2-0 series lead. In openers, Detroit
beat Los Angeles 2-0 and Colorado defeated Phoenix 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the only game tonight, Buffalo is at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, the only team to win on the road in the first two
days of the playoffs, scored on three of its first four shots
against goalie Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   Janne Laukkanen had two goals and Robert Lang, Martin Straka,
Jiri Slegr, Jan Hrdina and Tyler Wright also scored. Jagr, the NHL
scoring leader, had four assists.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was about the most embarrassing effort of the season,''
Washington's Terry Yake said. ''We got outplayed in every aspect of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-goal deficit was the biggest in 138 playoff games for
the Capitals. They've lost by six goals three times, including a
7-1 loss to Pittsburgh in 1995. Pittsburgh was a goal shy of
matching its biggest playoff victory, an 8-0 rout of Minnesota in
1991 that clinched the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has won four of its last five playoff series against
Washington, but the Capitals won the opener each time.
</P>
<P>
   ''One game doesn't a series make,'' Penguins coach Herb Brooks
said. ''But it's a good start.''
EASTERN CONFERENCE:
Flyers 3, Sabres 2:
</P>
<P>
   At Philadelphia, rookie Simon Gagne scored with 14:27 left and
Brian Boucher, the rookie goalie making his first playoff start,
made 18 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Jones and Daymond Langkow gave Philadelphia a 2-0 lead in
the first period, a rare early edge against goalie Dominik Hasek.
Buffalo's Stu Barnes and Miroslav Satan scored in the second.
Devils 4, Panthers 3:
</P>
<P>
   At East Rutherford, N.J., Scott Stevens, Petr Sykora and Sergei
Brylin scored in the first 15:28 as New Jersey opened a three-goal
lead and held off Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Scott Gomez also scored and Martin Brodeur made 20 saves.
Peter Worrell, Mike Sillinger and Rob Niedermayer scored for the
Panthers. Pavel Bure, the NHL goal leader with 58, was limited to
an assist.
WESTERN CONFERENCE:
Stars 3, Oilers 0:
</P>
<P>
   At Dallas, Brett Hull had a goal and an assist and Ed Belfour
made 17 saves for his eighth playoff shutout as the Stars beat
Edmonton for the second straight night.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Muller and Scott Thornton also scored for Dallas,
continuing an early playoff trend of production from surprising
players. Hull is the only one of Dallas' top five scorers with a
goal in the two games.
Red Wings 2, Kings 0:
</P>
<P>
   At Detroit, Chris Osgood made 19 saves for his seventh playoff
shutout and Vyacheslav Kozlov and Sergei Fedorov scored goals.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlov scored at 1:43 of the second period on a shot that hit
Los Angeles defenseman Jere Karalahti in the back and caromed into
the net past goalie Stephane Fiset. Fedorov scored into an empty
net with 12.8 seconds remaining.
Avalanche 6, Coyotes 3:
</P>
<P>
   At Denver, Sandis Ozolinsh, who failed to score a goal in the
final 20 games of the regular season, scored twice as Colorado beat
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Shjon Podein added two goals for the Avalanche, who shrugged off
the absence of injured star Peter Forsberg. Dave Andreychuk and
Alex Tanguay also scored for Colorado. Travis Green, Shane Doan and
Teppo Numminem scored for Phoenix.
</P>
</TEXT>
