<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian Drama Back in Court  </HEADLINE>
By MARK STEVENSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- In a remarkable turn of events, Elian Gonzalez's
relatives dared the federal government to take him by force and won
a court reprieve that keeps the 6-year-old boy in the United States
-- at least for a few more days.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives defied the government's order to make Elian
available Thursday for a flight to Washington and a reunion with
his father. In a last-minute plea for their cause, they distributed
a home video in which Elian tells his father he does not want to
return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were expected to provoke a showdown. But a federal
appeals court temporarily blocked anyone from taking Elian out of
the country until it decides whether to hear the relatives' claims.
A government response to the order was due today.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the Justice Department informally agreed not
to transfer custody of Elian to his father for three or four days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our miracle happened!'' shouted Mercedes Franco, 59, one of
the thousands of protesters in Little Havana. ''That boy is a
miracle. I feel like screaming everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people had crowded the narrow streets around
Elian's great-uncle's house expecting to block federal agents from
taking the boy. Their joy spilled into the rest of the
neighborhood, with drivers clogging traffic, blasting salsa music
and waving Cuban flags into the night.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno appeared to be speeding the case to
its conclusion by meeting for 2{ hours Wednesday with Elian and his
relatives and then issuing the flight ultimatum. But when it became
clear that the family would not heed the deadline, Reno said she
would respond in a ''reasonable, measured way.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have the authority to take action,'' said Reno, who still
is criticized for how the government dealt with the Branch
Davidians in 1993. ''But responsible authority means not only
knowing when to take action, but how and when to take that
action.''
</P>
<P>
   The family said Reno's order was unacceptable because they want
a reunion with Juan Miguel Gonzalez in which they would not have to
relinquish custody of Elian. The father has said he will only meet
with the relatives once Elian is back in his care.
</P>
<P>
   For Juan Miguel, who came to Washington on April 7 in hopes of
bringing his son back to Cuba, the latest delay prolonged his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has said he would not feel safe coming to Miami to pick
Elian up, given the political passions rumbling here. The father
made an obscene gesture Thursday to a small group of Cuban-American
protesters who heckled him in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Elian appeared on TV around the country Thursday, speaking in
Spanish on a home video given to the Spanish-language network
Univision. Animatedly addressing his father, he says: ''I don't
want to go to Cuba. ... I want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel's attorney, Gregory Craig, said the Miami relatives'
actions Thursday ''emotionally damaged and exploited this most
wonderful little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued by two fishermen while clinging to an inner
tube in the Florida Straits on Thanksgiving Day. His mother and 10
other people fleeing Cuba drowned when their boat sank.
</P>
<P>
   His Miami relatives have cared for him ever since and have been
fighting in court for an asylum hearing. The Clinton administration
has ordered Elian back to his father, saying only he can speak for
the boy on immigration matters. The Cuban government has called for
Elian's return.
</P>
<P>
   Government sources have said the Justice Department is prepared
to send U.S. marshals and immigration agents into the house to
remove Elian. But on Thursday, the government blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ''A second miracle is happening in the case of Elian,'' said
Raul Gonzalez, a 72-year-old accountant who lives in the
neighborhood. ''It seems that God is guiding us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many said they believed the showdown was merely delayed,
not prevented.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel very happy because we might get some justice,'' said
Ofelia Perez, 72, who came to America from Cuba in 1966. ''But we
can't let our guard down.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writer Michael J. Sniffen contributed to this
report from Washington.
</P>
