<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Toledo Vows Market Economy  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- For most of his Peruvian supporters, Alejandro
Toledo dresses in casual shirts and jeans, promising jobs and
education in messages garnished with measured doses of street
slang.
</P>
<P>
   For bankers and international lenders, the
economist-turned-candidate dons a suit and tie and eloquently
describes, in educated Spanish and near-perfect English, how he
will toe a tough fiscal line.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to have a market-based economy but with a human
face,'' he told The Associated Press before Sunday's election.
''You don't have to be afraid of those words: human face. That's
what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the style Toledo has assumed to deliver that
message, it has propelled the 54-year-old former World Bank
official into position to possibly end President Alberto Fujimori's
10-year presidency in a runoff election.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has described his opponent as an undisciplined,
free-spender who would plunge Peru back into the economic chaos of
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't slowed down Toledo, who has gained a measure of
respect from foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank, one of the world's largest investment banks, has
said it does not believe Toledo would ''engage in irresponsible
macroeconomic policy if elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has also faced barbs from Fujimori's supporters that he
is a phony, an actor who changes persona in accord with whatever
audience he faces.
</P>
<P>
   But pollster Manuel Torrado said Peru's poor majority does not
find anything unpresidential in chameleon-like behavior.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years, Fujimori has deftly maintained a ''man of the
people'' image with regular jaunts into the nation's interior,
wearing a poncho when he is in the high Andes and an ankle-length
''cushma'' -- a cotton robe worn by several different Amazon tribes
-- when he is in the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Peruvians are used to that kind of metamorphosis because of
Fujimori,'' Torrado said.
</P>
<P>
   Born a bricklayer's son, Toledo says he shined shoes as a
youngster to help make ends meet. He went on to earn two graduate
degrees and a doctorate from Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has never held public office. He took less than 4 percent
of the vote in 1995, when Fujimori won a landslide re-election.
</P>
<P>
   But in this race, riddled with reports of government abuses and
accusations of fraud, Toledo has managed to cut deep into
Fujimori's bedrock support among the poor, capitalizing on a harsh
two-year recession.
</P>
<P>
   He promises to raise salaries of teachers, police and public
employees and to create at least 400,000 jobs by lowering taxes to
boost business investment. The message has a strong appeal in a
country where only half the labor force has steady work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0251 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't To Probe Ex-CIA Officer Case  </HEADLINE>
By C. BRYSON HULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A Justice Department investigation will be
launched in the 1993 arms-dealing case involving former CIA officer
Edwin P. Wilson, government attorneys say.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure came Thursday in the department's response to a
motion by Wilson to hold 17 current and former CIA and Justice
officials in contempt of court for allegedly hiding evidence that
would have helped his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''The allegations of this case have been referred to (the Office
of Professional Responsibility), which will conduct a thorough
investigation,'' a footnote near the end of the government's
eight-page motion said.
</P>
<P>
   Justice spokesman Myron Marlin said the department will not
begin looking into the matter until a court appeal by Wilson, 71,
is settled.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who was sentenced to 52 years in prison, is appealing
his federal conviction for illegally shipping 20 tons of plastic
explosives to Libya from Houston's Intercontinental Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson alleges prosecutors introduced into evidence a crucial
affidavit by then-CIA Executive Director Charles A. Briggs that
they knew was false.
</P>
<P>
   Now in a federal prison in Pennsylvania, Wilson contends the
affidavit swore he ''was neither asked or requested, directly or
indirectly, to provide any services, directly or indirectly, to the
CIA,'' after his 1971 retirement, except for one Libya-related
assignment for which he was paid $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among the nearly 800 pages of once-classified documents are
papers showing Wilson was asked to perform several dozen services
for the CIA, including acquiring an anti-tank weapon for an agency
operation and helping relocate a Laotian general who was a valuable
CIA source.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department on Thursday argued that no one
intentionally misled the judge and jury and that only someone who
was in the courtroom could have committed contempt. Of the 17, lead
prosecutor Theodore Greenberg was the only one in the courtroom
during the trial, and nothing he did constituted contempt, Justice
Department lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's attorney, David Adler, was skeptical that the OPR
investigation will lead to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there's anything that the government is incapable of doing,
it's investigating itself. OPR's record of investigating abuses by
the Justice Department is abysmal,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0253 </TRAILER>
