<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disappointed couple sues Publisher's Clearing House  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORWICH, Conn. (AP) -- A disappointed couple who said they
dressed up and waited for the ''Prize Patrol'' on Super Bowl Sunday
is suing Publisher's Clearing House, claiming the mail order
company went too far in its efforts to sell them magazines.
</P>
<P>
   James and Cynthia Harnage of Norwich filed their lawsuit in
Norwich Superior Court this week, alleging the New York company
sent them repeated notices that they had won a $21 million ''Super
Prize'' in the company's sweepstakes. Their lawsuit claims fraud,
breach of contract and says the couple suffered emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $21 million in damages, the Harnages asked for a
restraining order preventing the national company from sending
similar mailings to other unsuspecting victims. A court date has
not been set.
</P>
<P>
   The Harnages are the first Connecticut residents to sue the
company under the new federal Deceptive Mail Prevention and
Enforcement Act, Christopher L. Irving, director of consumer
affairs for Publisher's Clearing House, told The Norwich Bulletin.
</P>
<P>
   Irving dismissed the suit as ''frivolous.'' He said the
company's practices have been challenged in court before and there
is nothing illegal about them.
</P>
<P>
   The couple said their ordeal began when they received a
''Document of Title'' purporting to be ''Official Correspondence''
from the publishing company. It stated ''Congratulations! Your
Recent Entry Was a Winner!'' and went on to say they were
''Approved for $21 million!''
</P>
<P>
   The Harnages said they were longtime subscribers to the clearing
house but had never received this type of correspondence. After
receiving several other notifications, they said they were
convinced they would receive the prize money on Super Bowl Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting to receive a knock on their door Jan. 20, they said
got all dressed up and waited. The knock never came.
</P>
<P>
   James Harnage, who was on worker's compensation at the time and
is now an unemployed retail manager, said the family spent money
they didn't have around Christmas anticipating the award.
</P>
<P>
   ''When they didn't show up, for six or seven weeks afterward I
felt useless,'' Harnage told The Bulletin. ''I felt like a fool for
being gullible enough to fall for it. I had thoughts of killing
myself. I think other people in my position might have done rash
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
