<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Apple Is Big Winner in Fed Money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New York City and Los Angeles were the cities
that received the most federal funds last year, the government
says.
</P>
<P>
   The two urban areas got more federal dollars than 41 states.
</P>
<P>
   New York, the nation's most populated city with about 7.4
million residents, drew $44.2 billion in federal funding in fiscal
1999, according to data released today by the Census Bureau.
California's Los Angeles County was next among counties and
county-equivalent areas, as termed by the Census Bureau, at $43.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the federal government distributed $1.5 trillion in
funding in fiscal 1999, a 4 percent increase from the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   About 48 percent, or $735 billion, went for three programs:
Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid. The money covers items such
as domestic benefits, subsidies, grants, goods and services, and
salaries and wages.
</P>
<P>
   Federal direct payments to individuals for retirement and
disability in 1999 reached $523 billion, a 3.2 percent increase
over 1998, with Social Security alone totaling $415 billion, a 3.1
percent increase. Medicare payments were down 0.4 percent to $209
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department domestic spending, which includes payroll,
defense contracts and grants, and military pensions, totaled $237
billion in 1999, a 4.9 percent increase over 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among states, California received the most federal money, $166
billion, followed by New York at $102 billion and Texas at $98
billion.
</P>
<P>
   New York City and Los Angeles County, though, did not top the
list when it came to per capita spending: Fairfax City, Va., was
first at $101,192; New York City was 769th at $5,952, and Los
Angeles County was 1,653rd at $4,659.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fairfax City is immediately close to Washington, D.C. They are
heavily impacted with federal employees, so that means a lot of
defense and non-defense contracts, and the costs of salaries,''
said Gerard Keffer, chief of the Census Bureau's Federal Programs
Branch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 0321 </TRAILER>
