<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Playboy Trying Another Casino Club  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Playboy Enterprises Inc., whose British casino
gambling licenses were revoked in the early 1980s, has signed a
letter of intent with Ladbroke Casinos Ltd. to develop a London
gaming club.
</P>
<P>
   The Playboy Casino Club will offer casino gaming, dining
facilities and a bar, the company said Thursday. The complex will
also feature a separate nightclub and retail space. Several West
End locations are currently under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed London casino would be operated by a joint venture
company, in which Ladbroke will own an 80.1 percent interest with
Playboy initially owning 19.9 percent, with an option to increase
to 49 percent. In addition, the joint venture will enter into a
trademark licensing agreement under which Playboy will receive a
licensing fee.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy spokesman Bill Farley says the joint venture is subject
to approvals from the Gaming Board of Great Britain and the
appropriate licensing agencies.
</P>
<P>
   If the government approves, Ladbroke will transfer one of its
gaming licenses to the joint venture, with a Playboy Club opening
in London in 18 to 24 months, Farley said.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy casinos, including the Playboy Club on Park Lane, were a
mainstay of London's party scene in the 1960s and remained open
until 1981, when their gambling licenses were revoked because of
violations of British gaming regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy chairman and CEO Christie Hefner said the company's
marketing expertise will combine with Ladbroke's extensive
operating experience. Ladbroke Casinos is a division of Ladbroke
Group PLC, a British hotel and gambling company with gaming
operations in Britain, Egypt and South America.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based Playboy Enterprises publishes Playboy magazine,
operates two television networks and distributes programming via
home video and DVD globally. The company also operates Playboy.com
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy posted losses in fiscal 1999 of $5.3 million on revenue
of $347.8 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
