<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford To Spin Off Visteon Parts Unit  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will spin off its Visteon parts
unit to its shareholders, creating the world's second-largest
automotive supplier. It also plans to give its shareholders up to
$10 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The company said today that current Ford shareholders would get
100 percent of the shares in a newly independent Visteon Corp. That
transaction will take place this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe independence for Visteon will result in it being a
stronger competitor and is in the best long-term interest of both
Visteon employees and Ford Motor Company shareholders,'' Ford
chairman William Clay Ford Jr. said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's second biggest automaker also announced a plan to
give its stockholders $20 per share or an equal value of new Ford
common stock. The cash payouts would be limited to $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company had been pressured to use its $11.5 billion cash
reserve for a stock buyback or other move to reward investors and
improve its stock price, which has been lagging in the past few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Scott Merlis with Wasserstein Perella Securities said
the reward for stockholders was much larger than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact Ford is willing to distribute $10 billion in cash to
its shareholders -- that's one of the best value enhancement
programs in the industrial world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Ford was up 2
percent, or $1.18} a share at $55.62{.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's move to make Visteon independent follows General Motors
Corp.'s spin off of its Delphi parts unit last year, creating the
world's largest auto parts company.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that the parts companies will be stronger by
competing for business outside of their parent companies --
something they could not do well unless they're independent. The
automakers benefit by increasing competition -- thereby reducing
costs -- for parts.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said its shareholders would receive Visteon stock based on
the number of Ford shares they own and the total number of Ford
shares outstanding when the deal is completed. The exact ratio of
Visteon shares per Ford share has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Visteon has about 81,000 employees in 130 countries. It had
revenues of $19.4 billion and earnings of $735 million in 1999,
ranking behind Delphi and ahead of the auto parts division of
Robert Bosch GmbH of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the year, Ford has made several moves toward pushing
Visteon out of the nest. Ford appointed Peter Pestillo, its
longtime head of labor relations, as the parts unit chairman and
CEO last fall. A Visteon separation was the central point in
negotiations with the United Auto Workers last fall.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, Visteon salaried workers were told that paychecks
dated April 15 would be the first to sport the Visteon orange logo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the UAW contract, about 23,500 workers at Visteon will
remain Ford employees for life -- with Ford paychecks and pensions --
when Visteon becomes independent. Those workers also will be free
to transfer back and forth between Ford and Visteon.
</P>
<P>
   New workers at a separate Visteon would be covered by an
agreement that mirrors the one the UAW has with Ford; that
arrangement will continue for two contracts after the new deal
between the union and Ford expires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1017 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
