<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge Then Start To Recover  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened sharply lower Friday as inflation
jitters extended Wall Street's selling spree.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index was down as much as 161 points in the
opening minutes of trading before recovering some lost ground. It
was down 76.61, or 2.1 percent, at 3,600.17 at midmorning, dropping
deeper into bear-market territory.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused index already plunged 769 points, or 17
percent, in the first four days of this week, and it is now at its
lowest level since early December. With the latest decline, the
Nasdaq is off almost 30 percent from its March 10 record of
5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market occurs when there is a sustained drop of more than
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 218.18 points at
10,705.37. It had been down even more earlier. The blue-chip index
is down a more modest 9 percent from its Jan. 14 record of
11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market barometer, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index,
was off 20.41 at 1,420.10.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop in
high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors pushed those
issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an unprecedented 86
percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave many young, unproven
companies market values they did not yet deserve, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   A government report Friday morning of an unexpectedly strong
rise in consumer prices in March added to Wall Street's unease.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rekindled worries that the Federal Reserve not only
would raise interest rates again, but might be even more aggressive
in trying to cool down the economy. The Fed has raised rates five
times since June, in each case with a quarter-point boost in
borrowing charges. Now there are worries the Fed's next move might
be a half-point increase.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates slow the expansion of business by making
it more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest losers this morning, Emulex was off 28 5/16 at
54| on dismal results for its third fiscal quarter. And JDS
Uniphase was down 5 13/64 at 87 7/64.
</P>
<P>
   There were some gainers, however. Sun Microsystems was up 2} at
80{ as investors responded to its favorable earnings report late
Thursday. And Ford Motor was up 1 at 55 7/16 after the company said
it would spin off its Visteon auto parts unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was off 11.64 at
477.58.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues led advancing issues by more than a 3-to-1
margin. Volume was 148.9 million shares vs. 148 million shares the
same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Markets overseas also were broadly lower: Japan's Nikkei stock
average fell 0.45 percent. In afternoon trading, Germany's DAX
index was down 2.58 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 2.77
percent, and France's CAC-40 was down 3.07 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
