<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans June Germany Summit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will travel to Germany in
June for a summit on ''third way'' politics, part of a larger
European trip.
</P>
<P>
   Others invited for the June 2-3 summit are leaders from
Argentina, Brazil, Britain, Chile, France, Israel, Italy, South
Africa, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Portugal and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The session, convened by German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
deals with ''progressive governance,'' also called third-way
governance, an alternative to the traditional liberal/conservative
approaches. It continues discussions that began in Florence, Italy,
in November.
</P>
<P>
   The White House confirmed Thursday that Clinton would attend the
summit as part of a longer European trip. The German government
announced the visit Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While abroad, Clinton also will pick up the prestigious
Charlemagne prize in Aachen and take part in a European Union
summit in Lisbon, Portugal, on May 30-June 1. From Germany, Clinton
is expected to go to Moscow to meet with new Russian President
Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting including Clinton had originally been scheduled for
May in Berlin, but was postponed after British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said he couldn't make it because of elections for London
mayor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
