<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Friday, April 14, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nasdaq Down 124; Dow Down 207
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were sharply lower this morning as
inflation jitters extended Wall Street's selling spree. Just before
11 a.m. EDT, the Nasdaq composite index was off 124.66 at 3.552.12.
It had been down as much as 161 points earlier in the session. The
technology-focused index already plunged 769 points, or 17 percent,
in the first four days of this week, and it is now at its lowest
level since early December. The Dow Jones industrial average was
down 207.94 at 10,715.61. Analysts say the most fundamental reason
for the drop in high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors
pushed those issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an
unprecedented 86 percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave
many young, unproven companies market values they did not yet
deserve, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT:
Dow Industrials:        10715.61 - 207.94
NYSE Issues:         Advances  623  Declines 1891  Unchgd  487
NYSE Volume:         258,450,300
Most Active NYSE issue:         America Online56|   - 1 15/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1409.49 - 31.02
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          894.54 - 20.69
Nasdaq Composite Index        3552.12 - 124.66
Gold(final) -    $285.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Prices Surge in March
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices jumped 0.7 percent in March,
the biggest gain in almost a year, and above the 0.5 percent many
analysts had expected. The Labor Department reported the rise was
fueled by sharp increases in gasoline and other energy prices.
Outside the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core'' rate
of inflation rose 0.4 percent, the strongest pace in five years.
The core rate rose twice as fast as many analysts were expecting.
The government said rising prices for housing, transportation and
household furnishings accounted for most of the increase.
</P>
<P>
   Business Inventories Rise 0.5 Percent
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department reported today that
business inventories rose 0.5 percent in February, following a 0.5
percent increase in January.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Production Up 0.3 Pct.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve said today that industrial
production at the nation's factories, utilities and mines rose 0.3
percent in March, as expected, a fresh sign that the manufacturing
sector is on solid footing. Operating capacity, meanwhile, edged
down to 81.4 percent, well below levels associated with a pickup in
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Code Hidden in Microsoft Software
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. engineers included a secret
password in Internet software that could be used to gain illegal
access to hundreds of thousands of Web sites, The Wall Street
Journal reported today. The rogue computer code was discovered in a
three-year-old piece of software by two security experts, the
newspaper said. Contained within the code is a derisive comment
aimed at a Microsoft rival: ''Netscape engineers are weenies!''
Steve Lipner, who manages Microsoft's security-response center,
described such a backdoor password as ''absolutely against our
policy'' and a firing offense for the as-yet unidentified
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Iomega's Earnings Up, Sales Down
</P>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Iomega Corp.'s first-quarter profits
increased more than 50-fold, as cheaper operating costs for the
company's mainstay Zip computer storage drives more than offset a
decline in sales. The company earned $31.7 million, or 12 cents a
share, compared to $569,000, or zero cents per share, a year ago.
Those figures don't include a $20.1 million, one-time boost as the
company decreased funds set aside for taxes. Including those funds,
Iomega's net income for the first quarter of 2000 was $51.8
million, or 19 cents a share. The results blew past Wall Street's
expectations, which were pegged at just 4 cents a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, Arco Merger Approved
</P>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- More than a year after BP Amoco PLC
started its takeover of Atlantic Richfield Co., the path is finally
clear. The Federal Trade Commission voted yesterday to step out of
the way of the $27.6 billion deal after BP Amoco agreed to sell all
of Arco's Alaska assets to satisfy anti-competitive concerns. BP
Amoco has a tentative agreement to sell the Alaska holdings -- oil
and gas interests, tankers, pipelines and exploration rights -- to
Phillips Petroleum Co. for $7 billion. That sale must be completed
within 30 days. BP Amoco said it expects to complete its purchase
of Arco on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford To Spin Off Visteon
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. will spin off its Visteon parts
unit to its shareholders, creating the world's second-largest
automotive supplier. It also plans to give its shareholders up to
$10 billion in cash. The company said today that current Ford
shareholders would get 100 percent of the shares in a newly
independent Visteon Corp. That transaction will take place this
summer. ''We believe independence for Visteon will result in it
being a stronger competitor and is in the best long-term interest
of both Visteon employees and Ford Motor Company shareholders,''
Ford chairman William Clay Ford Jr. said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Says Economy Is Improving
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan today upgraded its assessment of the two main
pillars of private demand -- personal spending and capital
investment -- and said the economy is improving at a ''moderate
pace.'' In its monthly report for April, the Economic Planning
Agency cited signs of ''more buoyant'' corporate activity, and said
the economy is moving ''toward a sustainable recovery.'' The agency
said investment in plants and equipment is improving, primarily in
the manufacturing sector. In addition, the report suggested
personal spending may be close to turning a corner.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Corporate Bankruptcies Surge
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Corporate bankruptcies in Japan surged 39.9 percent
in March from a year earlier, marking the fifth consecutive
increase, a private credit research company said today. Most of the
1,770 bankruptcies hit smaller firms. All but 54 of them were
capitalized under 50 million yen, or $467,000, Teikoku Databank
said. Liabilities left behind by the insolvent companies last month
fell 46.4 percent from February to $6.04 billion, it said. For the
fiscal year ended March 31, the number of bankruptcies fell 3.5
percent to 16,887 from the previous fiscal year. Liabilities in the
latest reporting year totaled $105.24 billion, down 25.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy Trying Another Casino Club
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Playboy Enterprises Inc., whose British casino
gambling licenses were revoked in the early 1980s, has signed a
letter of intent with Ladbroke Casinos Ltd. to develop a London
gaming club. The Playboy Casino Club will offer casino gaming,
dining facilities and a bar, the company said yesterday. The
complex will also feature a separate nightclub and retail space.
</P>
<P>
   Most Asian Markets Close Lower
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stocks markets ended the week lower
today, dragged down by steep declines overnight on Wall Street.
South Korea shares closed sharply lower. The Korea Composite Stock
Price Index fell 36.12 points, or 4.3 percent, to 800.89. The
Taipei market's Weighted Stock Price Index fell 287.99 points, or
3.00 percent, to 9,374.61. In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index fell
209.80 points, or 1.3 percent, closing at 16,142.76. The Japanese
225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 91.74 points, or 0.45 percent,
to close at 20,434.68.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Consumer prices: up 0.7 percent
</P>
<P>
   Business inventories: up 0.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production: up 0.3 percent
</P>
</TEXT>
