<HEADLINE> Clinton issues proposal to eliminate national debt by 2013  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODBURY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton today proposed
using at least $350 billion of the federal budget surplus over the
next 10 years to eliminate the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech this morning to more than 1,300 business and civic
leaders on Long Island, Clinton said that if the federal government
dedicates about 40 percent of the projected $750 billion budget
surplus to reducing the debt, the United States would be in the
black in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   She told the Long Island Association that if she's elected to
the Senate, her top priority would be the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything else we want to do -- from health care and research,
for education for public schools and higher education, or the
environment -- everything else we want to do depends on us making
the right decisions about where we go with the economy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She opposes proposals for across-the-board tax cuts currently
being promoted by the Republican leadership in Congress. Clinton
said she would reject ''any risky tax plan that would bust a hole
in that budget and put our prosperity at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, she scrapped plans to headline a charity dinner for
an Arab-American group because representatives from the Israeli
Embassy were not invited. Several Arab states do not recognize the
state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Mosaic Foundation is made up of the wives of Arab
ambassadors to the United States who raise money for charity. This
year's dinner on May 3 is to benefit Save the Children. Clinton has
served as honorary chairwoman for the dinner for the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Kim Serafin called her decision to
back out ''a classic Clinton flip-flop.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is courting New York's large Jewish population in her
bid for the U.S. Senate against Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a federal civil rights panel postponed discussion of
a report said to criticize Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's New York City
Police Department amid news that the panel's chairwoman had
contributed to the first lady's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Commission on Civil Rights denied any connection.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Giuliani from denouncing the probe.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't take much to figure out this is a political
operation,'' Giuliani said Thursday after a campaign stop on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Newsday reported the panel's chairwoman, Mary Frances Berry,
contributed $250 last year to Clinton and another $300 to the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee, which has pledged support
to her Senate bid.
</P>
<P>
   Berry defended her donation.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have a right to make campaign contributions to anyone
they please,'' Berry said Thursday. She said she would continue to
participate in the commission's discussion of the NYPD.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the report) is about Giuliani's office, not Giuliani. It's
about the police department in New York. It's not about Hillary
Clinton and it's not about the senatorial campaign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's spokesman, David Aronson, said it was unclear
when the draft report would be discussed and declined to explain
the delay. The report had been scheduled for discussion today.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission is preparing a report on the NYPD
that is expected to be highly critical and could call for the
appointment of a federal monitor to oversee the department. The
commission began its probe into the police force last year in the
wake of the shooting of Amadou Diallo and the torture of Abner
Louima at the hands of New York City cops.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing held by the commission in New York City last May,
Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir defended the police
force. But the Rev. Al Sharpton and others described the NYPD as
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Six members of the commission were appointed by Democrats and
two by Republicans. The panel has no enforcement powers but can
make recommendations to the president, Congress and federal
agencies.
</P>
