<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post Office Named After Slain Carrier  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton signed a bill Friday to name
a post office in Chino Hills, Calif., after a postman killed
shortly after a shooting at a Jewish community center last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to visit the family of Filipino-American
letter carrier Joseph Ileto Saturday night in Los Angeles, said
White House spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   A substitute carrier who had worked for the Postal Service for
two years, the 39-year-old Ileto had just started walking a mail
route in the city's Chatsworth section on Aug. 12, 1999 when he was
gunned down in a driveway and left to die. Ileto was born in the
Philippines and immigrated to the United States when he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr., a white supremacist, has been charged
with killing Ileto and with hate-crimes violations in the wounding
of three boys, a teen-age girl and a receptionist at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty against Furrow. A
trial has been set for Nov. 14.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Office Workers Back Strike  </HEADLINE>
By TODD RICHMOND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Office workers at Miller Brewing Co.'s
corporate headquarters have authorized their union to call a strike
if contract talks fail.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 employees voted Thursday on a strike issue for the
first time in 20 years and 97 percent agreed to let their
bargaining agents schedule a walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Office &AMP; Professional Employees International Union, Local 35,
said there was no immediate strike date. It represents about 200
workers in the corporate headquarters and brewery such as
accounting clerks, payroll specialists and schedulers.
</P>
<P>
   ''These people took a real stance,'' union business manager Judy
Burnick said. ''They want to send a strong message to the company
that they won't accept a concessionary contract. These employees
are prepared to strike. That's a big step when you haven't had a
strike vote in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders and Miller officials are to resume discussions
April 19 with a federal mediator. Miller is optimistic about a
settlement, company spokeswoman Dianne Markut said. Miller is the
nation's second biggest brewer after Anheuser-Busch Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have talked since February when a three-year
contract expired. The latest contract extension expires April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in health-care premiums and wage increases tied to
merit have been at the center of discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's proposal calls for increasing family health-care costs
by nearly $100 a month, Burnick said, while office workers at
Miller breweries in North Carolina and Texas pay $16 a month for
family coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are also frustrated with a clause that provides wage
increases on a merit basis. That plan allows only three to four
employees to earn top performer status, the union said. Union
negotiators want a straight 3.5 percent increase instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1124 </TRAILER>
