<DOCNO> APW20000414.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 1241.45; Nasdaq Down 146.37  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks tumbled once again today as already
nervous investors reacted to worse-than-expected inflation news.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, deeply entrenched in bear territory,
was off 146.37 at 3,530.41 in late morning trading, near its lows
of the session.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused index already plunged 769 points, or 17
percent, in the first four days of this week, and it is now at its
lowest level since early December. With the latest decline, the
Nasdaq is off almost 30 percent from its March 10 record high close
of 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market occurs when there is a sustained drop of more than
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 241.45 at 10,682.10.
The blue-chip index is down a more modest 9 percent from its Jan.
14 record of 11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market barometer, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index,
was off 23.39 at 1,417.12.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop in
high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors pushed those
issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an unprecedented 86
percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave many young, unproven
companies market values they did not yet deserve, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   A government report Friday morning of an unexpectedly strong
rise in consumer prices in March added to Wall Street's unease.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rekindled worries that the Federal Reserve not only
would raise interest rates again, but might be even more aggressive
in trying to cool down the economy. The Fed has raised rates five
times since June, in each case with a quarter-point boost in
borrowing charges. Now there are worries the Fed's next move might
be a half-point increase.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates slow the expansion of business by making
it more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe that this portends a pick up inflation, but
feel that some people on the Street will think it does,'' said
Bruce Steinberg, chief economist for Merrill Lynch. ''We caution
that today's CPI figure may have a negative market impact if it is
not outweighed by other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest losers this morning, Emulex was off 37 15/16
at 45 on dismal results for its third fiscal quarter. And JDS
Uniphase was down 5 at 87 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   There were some gainers, however. Sun Microsystems was up 4
15/16 at 82 11/16 as investors responded to its favorable earnings
report late Thursday. And Lucent was up 1 15/16 at 55\.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was off 13.33 at
475.89.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues led advancing issues by more than a 3-to-1
margin. Volume was 349 million shares vs. 340 million shares the
same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
