<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 11:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 229.85; Dow Off 303.81  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply Friday as inflation jitters
extended Wall Street's selling spree.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index had plunged 229.85, or 6.3 percent,
at 3,446.93 at late morning, dropping deeper into bear-market
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq already had plunged 769 points, or 17 percent, in the
first four days of this week. With the latest decline, the
technology-focused average is off almost 32 percent from its March
10 record of 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market is considered a sustained drop of more than 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 303.81, or 2.8
percent, at 10,619.74 at late morning. The blue-chip index was down
a more modest 9.4 percent from its Jan. 14 record of 11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop in
high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors pushed those
issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an unprecedented 86
percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave many young, unproven
companies market values they did not yet deserve, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   A government report Friday morning of an unexpectedly strong
rise in consumer prices in March added to Wall Street's unease.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rekindled worries that the Federal Reserve not only
would raise interest rates again, but might be even more aggressive
in trying to cool down the economy. The Fed has raised rates five
times since June, in each case with a quarter-point boost in
borrowing charges. Now there are worries by investors that the
Fed's next move might be a half-point increase.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few bright spots in the market Friday were Sun
Microsystems, which issued a strong earnings report after the close
of trading Thursday, and Ford, which said Friday it was giving up
to $10 billion in cash to shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
