<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow, Nasdaq Each Plunge 300  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks took a beating today, sending the Nasdaq
composite index and Dow Jones industrials plunging more than 300
points each, as already nervous investors were further upset by to
worse-than-expected inflation news.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, deeply entrenched in bear territory, was off 291.56
at 3,385.22 in midday trading after falling as much as 301.67.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused index already plunged 769 points, or 17
percent, in the first four days of this week, and it is now at its
lowest level since early December. With the latest decline, the
Nasdaq is off more than 32 percent from its March 10 record high
close of 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   A bear market occurs when there is a sustained drop of more than
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 362.68 at 10,560.87.
The blue-chip index is down almost 10 percent from its Jan. 14
record of 11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   The broader market barometer, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index,
was off 57.67 at 1,382.84.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a momentum market on the way up, it is a momentum
market on the way down,'' said Nick Sargen, a chief investment
strategist for J.P. Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the most fundamental reason for the drop in
high-tech stocks is a growing sense that investors pushed those
issues too far last year, when the Nasdaq rose an unprecedented 86
percent. The frenzy for technology stocks gave many young, unproven
companies market values they did not yet deserve, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   A government report Friday morning of an unexpectedly strong
rise in consumer prices in March added to Wall Street's overall
unease.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rekindled worries that the Federal Reserve not only
would raise interest rates again, but might be even more aggressive
in trying to cool down the economy. The Fed has raised rates five
times since June, in each case with a quarter-point boost in
borrowing charges. Now there are worries the Fed's next move might
be a half-point increase.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates slow the expansion of business by making
it more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe that this portends a pick up inflation, but
feel that some people on the Street will think it does,'' said
Bruce Steinberg, chief economist for Merrill Lynch. ''We caution
that today's CPI figure may have a negative market impact if it is
not outweighed by other factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest losers this morning, Emulex was off 37 45/64
at 45 15/64 after an analyst said the data-storage company may have
problems shifting to new products. The value of LML Payment Systems
was cut in half, down 14} at 14}.
</P>
<P>
   Even traditional stalwarts were taking it on the chin, including
Oracle, down 6 15/16 at 65, and Qualcomm, down 15} at 110}
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was off 28.45 at
460.77.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues led advancing issues by more than a 4-to-1
margin. Volume totaled 528 million shares vs. 482.5 million from
the same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
