<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge blocks NYC welfare contracts  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge blocked the city from awarding more than
$100 million in welfare-to-work contracts to a company with ties to
a former adviser to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice William Davis agreed with City
Comptroller Alan Hevesi, who said the contract approval process had
been ''corrupted.'' The judge said Hevesi does not have to follow
city law and register, or give final approval to, two contracts
worth $104 million to Maximus of McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus was hired to help move thousands of welfare recipients
into employment, job training or treatment under the Giuliani
administration's plan to overhaul the city's welfare program.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Hevesi refused to register 17 workfare contracts to
Maximus and other companies worth about $469 million, saying they
were not awarded through a competitive bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   The contracts had been awarded through a procedure allowed in
some cases as an alternative to sealed bids, if the mayor approves.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi accused Giuliani of corrupting the process ''to provide
public benefits for his political cronies.'' He was referring to
Richard Schwartz, a former mayoral adviser and architect of the
welfare-to-work programs. His company, Opportunity America, a
subcontractor of Maximus, stood to get about 30 percent of the $104
million, Hevesi said.
</P>
<P>
   Because city law requires the comptroller to register a contract
if the mayor approves them, Hevesi registered 15 contracts ''under
protest'' but refused to register the other two involving 80,000
welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani sued over the issue, but the judge said Hevesi has
broad powers over city finances and is charged with ensuring
compliance with rules for procuring contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ''His objections should be considered, especially where, as
here, there is compelling evidence that the contracting process has
been corrupted,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Maximus and welfare officials had met as early as four
months before the city asked for contract proposals. The judge also
said Maximus denied to city officials that another company helped
prepare its proposal, and denied being investigated for crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis noted that Opportunity America had helped prepare the
contracts and that Maximus was the subject of a federal
investigation involving its attempts to get a contract from West
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But David Mastran, chief executive officer of Maximus, said
company officials ''believe that the contracting process was fair,
open and competitive. Maximus did not have a competitive advantage
over others vying for the same contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said he was ''gratified by the judge's decision, which
confirms our finding that the contract process was corrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about workfare, which I support,'' he said. ''This
is about a corrupt process.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Kahn, the lawyer who argued the city's case, promised
an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that the decision was incorrect, that the
contracting process was proper and legal and carefully designed to
move thousands of welfare recipients into meaningful jobs,'' Kahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Maximus Inc. site: http://www.maximus.com/
</P>
<P>
   New York City Comptroller's Office:
http://www.comptroller.nyc.ny.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
