<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Team Formed To Warn on Steroids  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medical researchers are trying to find a way
to warn young people and body builders that steroids are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The newest effort will involve a combination of the Internet,
post cards and alert bulletins, the National Institute on Drug
Abuse announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has set up an Internet site at
www.steroidabuse.org and said it will distribute 250,000 copies of
a Community Drug Alert Bulletin and 150,000 copies of an updated
report about anabolic steroids.
</P>
<P>
   Also, 500,000 postcards with messages about the harmful effects
of steroids are being distributed during April in nearly a thousand
locations nationwide, including gyms, movie theaters, shopping
malls, bookstores, restaurants and clubs.
</P>
<P>
   NIDA said use of steroids has increased from 2 percent of
10th-graders in 1998 to 2.7 percent last year and that studies show
fewer people are worried about their long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about body image and athletic performance may be
leading teens, as well as adult men and women, to use steroids, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Anabolic steroids is the common name for synthetic substances
related to testosterone, the male sex hormone. While these drugs
have medical uses, such as treating delayed puberty and some types
of impotence, their use can also cause problems.
</P>
<P>
   According to NIDA, the abuse of anabolic steroids can reduce
sperm production, shrink the testicles, and cause impotence and
irreversible breast enlargement in boys and men. Girls and women
can develop more masculine characteristics such as deepening of the
voice and excessive body hair.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, abuse of anabolic steroids can stunt bone growth in
adolescents and damage the heart, liver and kidneys, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Institute in the public education effort are the
National Collegiate Athletic Association, American College of
Sports Medicine, American Academy of Pediatrics, National
Association of School Nurses, National Federation of High Schools,
International Students in Action and Dr. Drew Pinsky, host of MTV's
''Loveline'' and drDrew.com.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net:
</P>
<P>
   National Institute on Drug Abuse: http://www.nida.nih.gov or
http://www.drugabuse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
