<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Down; Gold Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mostly lower against other
major currencies in European trading today. Gold rose.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 95.58 cents in late European trading, up
from 95.34 cents on Thursday. Later, in midday trading in New York,
the euro traded at 95.47 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included 105.06 Japanese yen, down from 105.79; 1.6440 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6486; 1.4752 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4650.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound was quoted at $1.5863, down from $1.5890.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading in New York, the dollar bought 105.03 yen, and
the pound was worth $1.5858.
</P>
<P>
   Based on euro rates, the dollar is worth 2.0458 German marks,
down from 2.0510; 6.8622 French francs, down from 6.8766; 2.3054
Dutch guilders, down from 2.3102; 2,025.60 Italian lire, down from
2,029.85.
</P>
<P>
   Gold closed in London at $282.20 bid per troy ounce, up from
$280.50 on Thursday. In Zurich the bid price was $282.20, up from
$280.35. Gold in Hong Kong closed at $280.85 on Friday, down 60
cents from 281.45 late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver closed in London at $5.13 bid per troy ounce, up from
$5.12.
</P>
</TEXT>
