<HEADLINE> Detroit Cops Probe Serial Killings  </HEADLINE>
By JOSEPH ALTMAN Jr., Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Police worldwide are trying to match a suburban
Detroit man's account of at least 16 slayings since the early 1990s
to information they have about unsolved murders in their cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the investigation keeps going on, bodies keep popping up.
The numbers keep increasing,'' Detroit Police Officer Octaveious
Miles said Thursday. ''There is a similar pattern that ties them
all together that creates a trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investigators warned that John Eric Armstrong, a
26-year-old husband and father, may be exaggerating. Though Detroit
police say they have physical evidence linking him to the deaths of
five prostitutes, agencies elsewhere have been unable to tie him to
any unsolved slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are gaps in his timeline that we are concerned about,''
Detroit police Cmdr. Dennis Richardson told the Detroit Free Press.
''However, nothing outside of Michigan has been confirmed yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, of Dearborn Heights, was arraigned today on five
charges of murder and three attempted murders of Detroit-area
prostitutes. Murder carries a mandatory sentence of life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   District Court Magistrate Irma J. Chenevert-Bragg entered
innocent pleas for Armstrong as he hung his head, trying to avoid
TV cameras lining the courtroom wall. He was ordered held without
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong is suspected in at least 11 other slayings since 1992:
three in the Seattle area, including the lone male victim, two in
Hawaii, two in Hong Kong and one each in North Carolina, Virginia,
Thailand and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Armstrong spent eight years as a crewman aboard the
USS Nimitz, going from port to port strangling women. He may also
be linked to the deaths of several prostitutes in Japan, Korea and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, he told us he either killed, or tried to kill,
every prostitute he'd ever had sex with,'' Assistant Police Chief
Marvin Winkler told The Detroit News. ''He expressed remorse
several times, and was crying like a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   However, police in Newport News, Va., said Thursday they have
not yet found any connection between Armstrong and any unsolved
murders in the area based on when the Nimitz was there.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong was arrested early Wednesday in an area of Detroit
frequented by prostitutes, whom he seemed to target in particular,
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began when police found the bodies of three
strangled prostitutes in a Detroit railroad yard on Monday. They
had been placed there over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know when you find three bodies at different states of
being decomposed ... you know it is the same person. The scene kind
of talks to you,'' Winkler said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy began investigating after receiving a call from the
FBI, Navy Lt. Cmdr. Larry Thomas said. The Navy was trying to
confirm the suspect's identity and whether he had been enlisted.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong moved eight months ago to Dearborn Heights and has
worked for the past month at Detroit Metropolitan Airport as an
aircraft refueler.
</P>
<P>
   Police said he asked for help and was cooperating with their
investigation. He was answering questions without a lawyer present,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared lucid, although a psychological exam likely will
follow arraignment, Assistant Wayne County Prosecutor Robert
Agacinski said.
</P>
<P>
   In a twist, investigators realized Armstrong had called in the
report of a body found in the Rouge River Jan. 2, Dearborn Heights
police Lt. Gary Tomkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong told police he spotted the body of 39-year-old Wendy
Jordan while he was leaning over a bridge to vomit, Tomkiewicz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was unusual circumstances,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler said the first slaying that police think is linked to
Armstrong occurred in 1992 in North Carolina. Police in Armstrong's
hometown of New Bern, N.C., said he has no criminal record there.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
