<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe Stocks Lower on U.S. Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- European stocks fell Friday after the release of
stronger-than-expected American consumer price data pulled down
U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies fell
10.82 points, or 2.8 percent, to 374.13, while the Dow Jones Stoxx
50 Index fell 156.8 points to 4,795.0.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks fell after an economic report indicated that
consumer inflation jumped higher than expected last month. The news
helped keep the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index firmly in
bear-market territory -- it is now off more than 30 percent from its
March 10 high.
</P>
<P>
   Pan-European technology index Easdaq lost 5.0 percent, while the
London-based TechMARK and Frankfurt's Neuer Markt had similar
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, ended down 12.46 points
at 418.33. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index was down 147.1 points
at 5,034.3.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Lawson, technology analyst for Teather and Greenwood, said
that although the global technology slide was a much-needed reality
check, ''the growth that underpins these companies hasn't
disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   He predicts a bumpy ride before the Nasdaq corrects, as wary
investors sell into any recovery.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Milan, Europe's key bourses ended lower as
both U.S. technology and blue-chip stocks fell on data that showed
the consumer price index grew at the fastest rate in five years
during March.
</P>
<P>
   London's FTSE-100 Share Index fell 2.8 percent, to 6,178.1, with
technology, telecom and media stocks falling furthest.
</P>
<P>
   Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index fell 3.1 percent to 7,214.83, with
losses across the board, and Siemens and SAP the heaviest losers.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris CAC-40 Index was down 3.2 percent to 6,065.71, Milan's
MIBtel Index rose 0.2 percent to 30,160 and Amsterdam's AEX Index
fell 1.5 percent to 650.54.
</P>
</TEXT>
