<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Activist Turner Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. (AP) -- Albert Turner Sr., a civil rights activist
who led the mule wagon that carried the body of Martin Luther King
Jr. at his funeral, died while awaiting surgery for abdominal
bleeding, a relative said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Turner said his 64-year-old brother was being prepared
for an operation to remove part of his colon when his heart stopped
Thursday afternoon. Doctors at Selma Baptist Hospital were unable
to revive him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It took everybody by surprise because he was in real good
spirits,'' said Turner. ''Nobody thought this was
life-threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner was Alabama field secretary for the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference in 1965, when he helped lead the aborted
Selma-to-Montgomery voting rights march that was blocked by
stick-swinging state troopers. The day came to be known as ''Bloody
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Selma attorney J.L. Chestnut said it was fitting that Turner led
the wagon carrying King's body in 1968 as the nation watched the
slain civil rights leader's funeral procession in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''The wagon showed King's connection with the poor people,''
said Chestnut. ''Al was selected to carry that wagon because he was
King's point man during the entire civil rights struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, Turner was among a group of civil rights
workers put on trial on federal charges of voter fraud in west
Alabama, where activists claimed Republicans were trying to
diminish black voting. Turner was found innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was no accident that the government indicted both Albert
and his wife on charges of voter fraud, and that the government
lost both times,'' Chestnut said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had said Turner, wife Evelyn and a third defendant
had altered absentee ballots collected from rural blacks in order
to get more votes for candidates they backed. Turner and his
codefendants said they changed ballots only when voters, many of
them elderly and poorly educated, asked them to, which is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Turner also served on the Perry County Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was smart, and he knew how to get people to support his
ideas,'' said fellow commissioner Charles LeCroy. ''He will be
greatly missed.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner lived in Marion all his life and traced his ancestry back
to slaves who worked cotton on plantations there. He said last year
that racial differences had faded in the town.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in Marion have a lot of get-up about them,'' Turner
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They like to be out front about things,'' he said. ''People
here get along.''
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete, Turner's brother said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1529 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Won't Check Female General  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Defense Department's inspector general
decided Friday there are no grounds to formally investigate a
misconduct allegation against the Army's highest-ranking female
officer.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation, made last week by a retired Army officer whose
identity has not been made public, had added a further twist to the
already tangled affair involving Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy. She
caused a stir by accusing a fellow general of sexual harassment.
The Army is investigating her charge.
</P>
<P>
   When the unidentified retired officer sent an e-mail to the
Defense Department inspector general's office last Friday he
claimed to have knowledge of ''personal misconduct'' on Kennedy's
part. The nature of the alleged misconduct has not been made
public. At the time, officials said it appeared to have little
substance. The inspector general's office, nonetheless, was
obligated by law to see whether a formal probe was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The answer is no,'' a senior defense official said Friday,
speaking on condition he not be identified. ''There is nothing
there on which to base an investigation. Case closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Army officials have declined to comment on the Kennedy case,
citing privacy concerns and a policy of not discussing
investigations by the inspector general until they are completed.
The Army has not even confirmed for the record that Kennedy filed a
complaint or that the Army inspector general is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kennedy nor the officer she accused of sexually
harassing her in 1996, Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith, has responded to
media requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with knowledge of the case said this week it appeared
the Army inspector general would need at least several more days,
if not weeks, to finish interviewing people and complete a report
on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy accused Smith of inappropriate touching during a visit
in her Pentagon office. It is unclear whether she told any of her
superiors about the incident at the time, but last fall she made it
known after the Army announced in August that Smith would be the
Army's next deputy inspector general. In that post, he would be
responsible for investigating misconduct including behavior such as
that of which he stands accused.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is single. Smith is married.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith was announced as the next deputy inspector
general of the Army on Aug. 27, he never assumed the position. His
status has been on official ''hold'' since last November, according
to Army personnel records.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is the Army's deputy chief of staff for intelligence and
one of only three female three-star generals in the military. She
is due to retire in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1539 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Fall on Wet Outlook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices finished lower
in trading Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade after an early
rally sparked by weather concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures prices were higher in early trading, but backed
away from gains on forecasts of weekend rain in the Midwest,
followed by more showers next week.
</P>
<P>
   Early gains were in response to 30- and 90-day National Weather
Service forecasts which call for higher-than-nomal temperatures and
lower-than-normal rainfall in the soybean crop-growing region.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures prices followed soybean prices lower on the
expectation that the hard red winter wheat crop will get a good
drenching, which should help crop development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the forecasts of rain next week, the sell-off of
corn futures was due to fears losses on the New York Stock Exchange
would trigger liquidation of commodities holdings to cover
positions in other markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery was 2 cents lower at $2.55} a bushel; May
corn was 1\ cents lower at $2.26\ a bushel; May oats were unchanged
at $1.23{ a bushel; May soybeans were 5} cents lower at $5.32{ a
bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle and pork futures prices were mixed in trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Strong wholesale pork prices gave a lift to hog futures prices.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle were .10 cent lower at 69.35 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle were .02 cent lower at 84.60 cents a pound; June lean
hogs were .12 cent higher at 75.17 cents a pound; May pork bellies
were .15 cent higher at 96.65 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
