<HEADLINE> Man Charged in Comedian Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A man was charged with trying to extort money
from ''Family Feud'' host Louie Anderson by threatening to reveal
the comedian allegedly asked him for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Richard J. Gordon, 31, of Mesa, Ariz., and a second man, Matthew
Auten, were arrested Tuesday after Gordon allegedly picked up a
$250,000 cashier's check from an FBI agent posing as Anderson's
assistant, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon alleged that Anderson once asked him to come home with
him and urged the comedian to pay money ''so your secrets don't get
out and blow your future.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's lawyer told federal authorities earlier this month
that Gordon received nearly $100,000 from Anderson but demanded
another $250,000, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the voice of the Fox animated children's show ''Life
With Louie,'' paid at first because he was afraid the story would
hurt his career, the court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Nathanson, a publicist representing Anderson, said in a
statement that being ''a target of criminal activity is an
unfortunate and increasingly common byproduct of celebrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and Auten remained in custody Friday.
</P>
