<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Get Food To Ethiopia Quick  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW ENGLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- The lives of millions of starving
Ethiopians can be saved if international donors respond quickly to
new requests for food aid, the U.N. special envoy to the Horn of
Africa said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Bertini, who is also head of the U.N. World Food
Program, said more relief food than originally estimated is needed
to prevent a humanitarian catastrophe as the number of people
threatened by a drought-induced food shortage increased.
</P>
<P>
   ''More and more people are at risk because the rains have not
come,'' Bertini told a news conference. ''We will be coming back in
the next few weeks with additional requests. We do not know how
much more will be requested, it needs to be further assessed ...
but I expect it will be more than 100,000 tons.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Millions of lives can be saved if the international community
can come forward with contributions quickly and generously,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Ethiopian government made a formal appeal for
836,800 tons of emergency food aid to assist an estimated 7.7
million people. The World Food Program agreed to call for pledges
amounting to 250,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   Bertini said the original assessment was carried out in
November. But the failure of the annual short rains means that the
original food estimate needs to be revised upward.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva on Friday, the World Health Organization appealed for
$6.5 million to provide medical help in Ethiopia for the next three
months. Spokesman Valery Abramov said both drugs and more medical
personnel are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that diarrheal diseases represent the biggest
threat, as well as respiratory diseases, measles, meningitis and
possibly cholera,'' Abramov said.
</P>
<P>
   In Addis Ababa, Bertini said she was generally pleased with her
discussions Thursday with Prime Minister Meles Zenawi but remained
concerned that he ruled out the use of two ports in neighboring
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Landlocked Ethiopia is embroiled in a 23-month border war with
Eritrea. The war has prevented aid agencies from shipping in
sorghum, wheat, maize and cooking oil via the Red Sea ports of
Assab and Massawa. Before the conflict broke out in May 1998, 75
percent of Ethiopia's relief food needs came in through Assab.
</P>
<P>
   Now aid groups are forced to use the port of Djibouti in the
Gulf of Aden and Berbera on the northern Somali coast. Up to
120,000 tons of grain a month are expected to land in port in the
coming months. Some experts think Djibouti and Berbera won't be
able to cope with the amount.
</P>
<P>
   Bertini is on a weeklong tour of the Horn of Africa that will
also take her to Eritrea, Djibouti and Kenya. In those nations and
Somalia, millions of people also are suffering from drought and
food shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
