<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newman Says One More Film Only  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- From actor-racer Paul Newman, the message is
catch me while you can on the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I'm going to try to do one more film as a swan song
and then get out,'' the 75-year-old actor said during his
appearance Wednesday on ''Late Show With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman has made similar statements to other reporters, including
those aired this week on AP Network News.
</P>
<P>
   ''At some point you've gotta get out of this,'' Newman said in
the radio interview. ''You've got to really retire and I don't want
to retire on my knees. I've been retiring now every year for 15
years, so at some point you gotta make it stick or people won't
believe you. I'd love to do one really memorable film to go out
on.''
</P>
<P>
   He made the comments as part of the promotion for his latest
film, ''Where the Money Is,'' which was opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oscar-winning actor and food company
executive/philanthropist said he has no plans to give up car
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite suffering bruised ribs when his car crashed into a tire
barrier at the Daytona International Speedway in January, Newman
told Letterman, ''As long as my pulse holds up, I think I'll
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he feels safer driving at Daytona than on a freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Newman is president of Newman's Own Foundation, which gives
millions of dollars to charities each year from proceeds of his
food line.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-eyed legend, who has starred in more than three dozen
films since his debut in the 1954 film ''The Silver Chalice,''
plays a likable bank robber in his latest film, which co-stars
Linda Fiorentino.
</P>
<P>
   Newman says in Esquire's May issue that he wakes up surprised
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm at that age when you really start thinking about what the
end is going to be like and how gracefully you're gonna do that,''
he said. ''If I would have to say I was preoccupied with anything,
it would be that; just wondering how graceful that exit is gonna
be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
