<HEADLINE> Gonzalez, Wife Attend Prayer Service  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE PFLEGER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Juan Miguel Gonzalez sought the tranquility of
a church Friday, escaping for a short time the turmoil swirling
around him in his battle to be reunited with his son Elian.
</P>
<P>
   First at the Washington National Cathedral, and then at the
United Methodist Building, Gonzalez joined his wife Nersy
Carmenante and others in prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was good for Juan Miguel and his wife to have an experience
that's peaceful,'' said Joan Brown Campbell, a former official of
the National Council of Churches who accompanied them.
</P>
<P>
   At the cathedral, the chief mission church of the Episcopal
Diocese of Washington, the Gonzalez family was given a tour and a
chance to pray. They said the Lord's Prayer in Spanish, Campbell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Translator Daphne Gereg said Gonzalez told her that he ''wanted
to his son home as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez met later with about 50 representatives of various
religions at the United Methodist Building across the street from
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Fassett, general secretary of the general board of church
and society of the United Methodist Church, said the meeting was
intended to ''express the concern of the religious community and to
underscore our need to articulate humanitarian values and try to
lift the conversation above the issues of clashing ideologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassett says he prayed with Gonzalez and the other religious
representatives, seeking ''guidance for America, for us, for
clarity of vision for people of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Churches and Society of the United Methodist Church
is collecting funds to pay for the services of Gonzalez's attorney,
Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said Elian, the 6-year-old Cuban boy at the center of
an international custody battle, has been baptized as a Catholic.
</P>
</TEXT>
