<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill OK'd To Study Undersea Energy  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress approved money to study an energy
source buried under the sea and the arctic permafrost that has the
potential solve many of the earth's energy problems or cause the
earth irreparable damage.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday voted by voice to authorize $47.5 million
over five years for the Department of Energy to study methane
hydrates, ice-like crystals of methane with the energy potential
equal to more than twice that of all other fossil fuels combined.
</P>
<P>
   The House earlier this month passed the bill, which now goes to
the president, who is expected to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Akaka, D-Hawaii, who wrote the Senate bill, said
methane hydrates were a staggering resource: ''As our nation's
energy resources dwindle and our reliance on imported energy
increases, we cannot afford to miss this important opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If only 1 percent of the methane hydrate resource could be
made recoverable, the United States could more than double its
domestic natural gas resource base,'' the House sponsor, Rep. Mike
Doyle, D-Pa., said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kripowicz, who deals with fossil fuels for the Energy
Department, told the House Science Committee's energy and
environment panel last year that the natural gas potential of
hydrates approaches 400 million trillion cubic feet, 80,000 times
the world's current known natural gas reserves.
</P>
<P>
   There is no existing technology to make extraction commercially
viable, and scientists have warned that the methane, if allowed to
escape its subterranean deposits, could destablize sea bottoms and
accelerate greenhouse gas accumulations.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists writing in the journal Science last November
theorized that the release of frozen methane from the ocean 55
million years ago was responsible for an abrupt warming of the
Earth that had a devastating effect on deep-sea life.
</P>
<P>
   The bill directs the Energy secretary, working with the
secretaries of Interior, Defense and Commerce, to study both
methane hydrates as an energy source and the technologies needed
for safe, efficient development.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy secretary would have the authority to award grants
and enter into cooperative agreements with universities and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 1753.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1630 </TRAILER>
