<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Jews May Be Pawns of Power  </HEADLINE>
By AFSHIN VALINEJAD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHIRAZ, Iran (AP) -- Thirteen Iranian Jews on trial for espionage
may be caught in the power struggle between reformists and
hard-liners in Iran's government.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal allies of President Mohammad Khatami are trying to move
toward better ties with the United States and the West. But
religious hard-liners, who control certain government sectors such
as the judiciary, want to preserve the anti-Western spirit of the
1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the trial will affect Khatami because convictions
and heavy sentences are likely to provoke an international backlash
and set back his reforms -- precisely what the hard-liners want.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way this case is moving, and the manner in which it is
being dealt with, appears to be either part of the power struggle
between the two factions or is influenced by it,'' said Saeed
Laylaz, a journalist for several Tehran newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   A long, drawn-out trial that ends with acquittals could also
have an impact on the president. His opening up to the West would
be delayed as the United States and other countries wait for the
verdict before improving ties.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has warned that the conduct and outcome of the
trial could affect the thaw in relations that began when Khatami
was elected president in 1997. France and Germany have called for a
fair trial, and European diplomats arrived at the courthouse
Thursday in the southern city of Shiraz for the start of the
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   After 90 minutes, the trial was adjourned to May 1 to give
defense counsel more time to prepare. But that was enough to raise
questions about the fairness of the proceedings, which were closed
to the public for national security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial judiciary chief Hossein Ali Amiri told reporters
Thursday that four of the defendants had confessed and that Judge
Sadeq Nourani had ruled the confessions admissible.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Amiri was referring to confessions made
in court Thursday or previously. Iranian media reported last fall
that suspects in the case had confessed but did not say what they
had confessed to. Defense lawyer Esmail Naseri said Thursday there
had been no confessions in court.
</P>
<P>
   Naseri said any pretrial confessions were ''irrelevant'' and
inadmissible because they had not been made in the presence of a
defense counsel.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge may not accept his view. The Jews are being tried
in a revolutionary court where the judge is also the prosecutor. He
investigates the case and hands down the sentence and verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Iranian officials had said the 13 Jews faced charges
of spying for Israel and the United States. Both countries have
denied any links to the accused.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the judiciary said in a statement that the 13 face
charges of spying for Israel alone.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the defendants face long prison terms or the death
penalty. In the event of a conviction, only Iran's supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, can grant a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei is a hard-liner and an opponent of ties with the West.
His authority supersedes that of Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, conservative allies of the Khamenei have repeatedly
tried to thwart Khatami's reform program by using banning liberal
newspapers, arresting editors and impeaching an interior minister
deemed too reformist.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Afshin Valinejad has reported from Iran for The
Associated Press since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1650 </TRAILER>
