<HEADLINE> Teen-ager Suspected in Fla. Blaze  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- A 17-year-old burning trash on his family's
property is suspected of starting a fire that burned more than
15,000 acres this week.
</P>
<P>
   Florida agriculture investigators have determined the cause of
the fire was a trash fire that got out of control when an aerosol
can in the trash exploded.
</P>
<P>
   The giant fire was nearly contained Friday morning. Firefighters
were celebrating a heavy drenching of rain that began Thursday
afternoon and was expected to continue throughout the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''We couldn't ask for better timing,'' said Gerry LaCavera, a
spokesman for the Florida Division of Forestry. ''I've heard some
say that yesterday in an hour we got a month's worth of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not identify the teen-ager suspected in the
fire, but said he was cooperative in the investigation. The state
attorney's office in Collier County will decide if any charges
should be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-ager was questioned by a Florida Department of
Agriculture investigator and released.
</P>
