<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whistlers Meet in N.C. Convention  </HEADLINE>
By ESTES THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISBURG, N.C. (AP) -- Whistle a happy tune, whistle the blues,
whistle a passage from Beethoven -- it doesn't matter what at the
27th annual International Whistlers Convention, just pucker your
lips and blow.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, you don't even have to blow.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have some whistlers who whistle entirely by whistling in.
No air goes out,'' said Allen deHart, the convention founder and
assistant to the president at Louisburg College, where the
competition began Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Winners will be announced Saturday in the adult, teen, child and
''allied arts'' divisions, the last for people who whistle with
their fingers or practice ventriloquism.
</P>
<P>
   Kilgour Shives, 84, of Vancouver, Canada, attending for the
seventh time, prefers to whistle a capella rather than with a taped
musical accompaniment as he must do at the competition, but likes
the challenge anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ''I get enjoyment when people hear me whistle,'' Shives said. He
planned to compete with opera accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiharu Takamoku came from Osaka, Japan, to compete. He spoke
little English but whistled clearly and handed out laminated cards
announcing the Japan Whistlers Association.
</P>
<P>
   One judge, Barry Rector of Vancouver, said whistling isn't as
popular a commercial art as it was 100 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whistlers that had a talent were hired by the rich and famous
to come whistle in their parlors,'' Rector said during a break
Thursday in a whistling class, where 20 or so students brushed up
on their vibrato and were counseled to keep a glass of water and
lip balm handy.
</P>
<P>
   The contest began in 1974 when the local arts festival held a
singing competition and Darrell Williams of Durham asked to whistle
his selection. He was the first whistling competition winner. He
returned the next year, bringing five or six other whistlers with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Once there were hundreds of contestants, but this year there
will be between 60 and 100 finalists; serious whistlers submitted
tapes in advance and some were eliminated. Still, if people show up
wanting to whistle, they can.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to have more whistlers because our standards were
lower,'' deHart said. ''We now have more professional whistlers,
but we never turn anybody down even though we have had some very
poor whistlers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The professional whistlers are egotistical and jealous, and
they say, 'Why do you let these whistlers in?' We say because art
should be free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1654 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
