<HEADLINE> OSCE Plans Chechnya Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe will launch a medical assistance program in Chechnya, the
group's chairwoman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Benita Ferrero-Waldner, who is also Austria's foreign minister,
said the OSCE plans to open a headquarters in the village of
Znamenskoye in northern Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Koshman, Russian President Vladimir Putin's envoy in
Chechnya, said Russia welcomes the OSCE. He said the organization
has been less critical of alleged human rights abuses than the
Council of Europe, which has suspended Russia's voting rights and
called for an international inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has bristled at foreign criticism of its campaign in
Chechnya, saying the fighting is an internal affair not requiring
mediation of the type the OSCE provided during the previous war in
1994-6.
</P>
<P>
   During her one-day trip to the breakaway region, Ferrero-Waldner
visited Znamenskoye and brought donations of medical supplies and
children's toys to residents, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner toured a hospital and newly opened school and
looked at a building the OSCE may use as a Chechen headquarters,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television news showed her smiling and walking gingerly
along a mud-clogged street, surrounded by heavily armed guards and
armored vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrero-Waldner said Friday she supports an independent but
national investigation into rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Violations of human rights, which took place on both the
Russian and Chechen sides, should be investigated in an independent
national forum,'' Russia's RTR television quoted her as saying in
Russian translation.
</P>
</TEXT>
