<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bavaria Said To Have E. German Files  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- State officials in Bavaria obtained about
500 highly sensitive East German secret police files on
high-ranking West German officials shortly after the Berlin Wall
fell, a weekly magazine reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Renegade communist agents were promised jobs and cash to steal
the files, Focus magazine reported. It said the files contained
sensitive information dating back decades on West German
politicians and government employees, including current German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and President Johannes Rau.
</P>
<P>
   The state Interior Ministry confirmed Friday that an undisclosed
amount of information was obtained from the East German secret
police, known as Stasi, but said most of the material was
immediately destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to appear in next week's issue but released to other
media early, Focus said CIA agents also took part in the program,
called ''Eunova,'' which lasted three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Munich-based magazine said the files were turned over the
Bavarian state Office for the Protection of the Constitution in
early 1990 -- after the Wall fell but before German unification that
October.
</P>
<P>
   It said copies were made of the files, which included telephone
conversations with precise details that Stasi agents obtained from
eavesdropping, before the originals were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Focus said Schroeder was monitored as early as 1978, when he
headed the youth wing of the Social Democratic party, and that he
was declared of special intelligence interest starting in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Rau's telephone conversations were monitored by the former East
German trade office located in Duesseldorf, the state capital of
North-Rhine Westphalia state where he was then governor, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Interior Ministry confirmed that Bavaria received
dossiers on residents of West Germany that the East had gotten
using ''eavesdropping measures.'' But the statement went on to say
that the papers, ''in so far as they did not deal with the security
of affected persons, were ... on March 29, 1990, destroyed without
delay and without analysis and without copies made of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ministry statement said officials only made copies of
so-called ''target control cards,'' which revealed the names,
telephone numbers, and addresses of individuals and institutions,
but not information from eavesdropping on those targets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1658 </TRAILER>
