<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Campaigning Closes Early  </HEADLINE>
By PETER W. MAYER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Campaigning for regional elections officially closed
Friday, two days before a vote largely seen as a test for Italy's
premier and his conservative rival ahead of next year's
parliamentary balloting.
</P>
<P>
   Some 42 million eligible voters -- roughly 75 percent of the
country's population -- will vote in 15 regions Sunday for regional
presidents and legislatures. Regional governments play a large role
in running local transport and health systems.
</P>
<P>
   The voters, however, have focused more on the acrimonious
exchanges between Premier Massimo D'Alema, head of a center-left
coalition government since October 1998, and media magnate Silvio
Berlusconi, whose center-right alliance includes former
neo-fascists and the autonomy-seeking Northern League movement.
</P>
<P>
   Their chances of winning the next premiership hinge on their
coalitions' showing in the regional elections. Parliamentary
elections will be held next March.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi has demanded that D'Alema step down if the
center-left fares poorly in Sunday's elections. The media tycoon
mounted a multimillion dollar campaign, including a nine-day cruise
on a luxury liner he leased for $1.25 million to canvass support
for the center-right candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi has repeatedly criticized D'Alema's inclusion of
hardline communists in the governing coalition and suggested the
premier may be an unreformed communist.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema has in turn criticized the center-right's links to the
Northern League and its volatile leader Umberto Bossi.
</P>
<P>
   Bossi has toned down only recently calls for northern Italy's
secession. His party's strong anti-immigration stance has led to
comparisons to policies of Austria's far-right leader Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema also denounced Berlusconi's posh cruise as ''arrogant
display of wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   The center-left coalition won nine of the 20 regions in 1995
elections and won another two in 1999 when center-right coalitions
collapsed in the southern Campania and Calabria regions.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, D'Alema was widely praised for his management during
the Kosovo war, but constant strains among the coalition partners
forced him to temporarily resign at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, whose business includes three TV networks,
magazines, and film, advertising and real estate interests, served
as premier for eight months in early 1992 until his coalition,
which included Bossi's movement, unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   Italy has 20 regions. The five not holding elections on Sunday
scheduled balloting for other times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
