<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NU, ConEd shareholders approve merger  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Shareholders of Northeast Utilities and
Consolidated Edison Inc. on Friday swiftly approved the companies'
proposed $3.5 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which would create one of the largest electric
companies in the country, could save $1.5 billion in operating
expenses over 10 years, the companies have said. Officials have not
said how those savings might affect the cost of heating and
lighting homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have more than 6.4 million electric
and gas customers throughout New England and New York.
</P>
<P>
   NU shareholders met in Hartford, while Con Ed shareholders
convened in New York. The deal still must be approved by state and
federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, announced in October, NU investors could
exchange each of their shares for $25 in cash or Con Ed stock. Con
Ed would also pay an additional $1 a share if the two working
reactors at NU's troubled Millstone nuclear power plant in
Connecticut were sold.
</P>
<P>
   Michael G. Morris, NU president, has said he is confident there
will be offers for the Millstone units, despite a history of
problems. All three Millstone reactors were shut down several years
ago due to safety concerns. In the past year, Millstone 2 and 3
gained federal approval to restart. Millstone 1 is being
decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger has met criticism from environmentalists
seeking the shutdown of the Millstone reactors and Connecticut
Attorney General Richard Blumenthal. Blumenthal maintains the deal
could mean higher rates, lower quality service and job losses --
issues he says have not been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This merger as currently planned is a disastrous disservice to
the people of Connecticut,'' Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he will appear Monday before the state Department of
Public Utilities to argue against the deal.
</P>
<P>
   NU, based in Berlin, is the largest electric utility in New
England with more than $4 billion in annual revenue and more than
1.7 million customers in Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Hampshire,
Rhode Island, New York and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed, headquartered in New York, has more than 3.3 million
electric customers and 1.4 million natural gas customers. The
company has generated more than $7 billion in annual revenues in
New York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed employs about 14,000 people in New York and northern New
Jersey. NU has about 9,000 workers in Connecticut, Massachusetts
and New Hampshire. Eugene R. McGrath, chairman, president and chief
executive officer of Con Ed, has said no layoffs are planned. But
he has said there would be gradual job cuts through attrition,
reduced hiring and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath is set to continue as chairman and chief executive
officer; Morris would be president of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities -- www.nu.com
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison--www.conedison.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
