<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions Imposed on N.Korea, Iran  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States imposed new sanctions Friday
against Iran and North Korea for ''knowingly engaging in the export
of military technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The sanctions will have no impact, at least over the short term,
because of existing sanctions against both countries. In making the
announcement, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin would not
say where the technology was exported, but North Korea is believed
to have had dealings in such materials with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other countries interested in preventing
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction have banded under the
Missile Technology Control Regime to try to discourage exports of
such technology.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin would not specify what types of equipment Iran and North
Korea exported but said the materials were subject to MTCR
controls. He called the violations ''major.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the breaches were ''Category 1'' offenses, the most
serious breach under the MTCR rules. Category 1 items include
complete missile systems, major subsystems, rocket stages or
guidance systems, production facilities for MTCR-class missiles or
technology associated with such missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said an MTCR-class missile is capable of delivering a
1,100-pound payload of 186 miles or more. An example is the Scud,
used by Iraq against Saudi Arabia and Israel during the Persian
Gulf War. One struck a U.S. Army barracks and killed 29 soldiers
and wounding 99.
</P>
<P>
   The new penalties are for a North Korean entity, the Changgwang
Sinyong Corp. of North Korea; and four Iranian entities: the
Ministry of Defense and Armed Forces Logistics, the Aerospace
Industries Organization, the Shahid Hemmat Industrial Group and the
Sanam Industrial Group.
</P>
<P>
   Under law, penalties required for Category I violations deny to
sanctioned entities, at least for two years, new U.S. government
contracts and individual export licenses for items that are under
government controls.
</P>
<P>
   In North Korea's case, sanctions are applied not just to the
particular corporation but also to all activities of the North
Korean government related to MTCR items. In Iran's case, only the
four named entities are sanctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said although the United States does not trade with the
North Korean entities now, ''addressing the causes that have led to
these sanctions are an additional hurdle that must cleared if we
are to improve economic and trade relations.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Iran, he said the new sanctions will not affect the
recent easing of U.S. imports on such items as caviar, pistachios
and carpets. This is because none of the sanctioned companies
produce these products, Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
