<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dissolves Restraining Order  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HOLMES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A judge dissolved a restraining order
Friday that had barred The Associated Press from publishing details
about a state-funded agricultural loan program.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Suzanne Covington said there was no
constitutional reason to keep secret public documents that had been
given to the AP by the Texas Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   Covington said the AP and its reporter, Chris Williams, did
nothing improper in obtaining the information for news stories.
Williams requested the documents under the state open records law.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were financial documents showing the details of a
$360,000 loan between Permian Sea Shrimp and Seafood Ltd. and the
First National Bank of Monahans.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Agricultural Finance Authority, part of the
Agriculture Department, guaranteed 80 percent of the loan after
reviewing the information later provided to the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Permian raises shrimp in West Texas in Pecos County, about 200
miles northwest of San Antonio, using salty water pumped from
aquifers. It has been current on its loan payments.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Margaret Cooper issued a temporary
restraining order April 5 preventing the AP from publishing
information about the loan guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp farmer Bart Reid and the First National Bank of Monahans
argued the Agriculture Department wrongly released trade secrets to
the AP.
</P>
<P>
   Covington lifted Cooper's order after about four hours of
testimony Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   David Donaldson, a lawyer for the AP, said the judge recognized
that the restraining order issued by Cooper was unconstitutional.
''We (the public) have an interest in what's going on'' when state
dollars are used, Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said after the decision that the privacy of his financial
records -- not the First Amendment right of a free press -- was the
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
