<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Anti-Milosevic Rally Held  </HEADLINE>
By DUSAN STOJANOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Waving flags and chanting ''Slobo go
away,'' more than 100,000 opponents of Slobodan Milosevic demanded
elections and an end to oppression Friday in one of the largest
protests to date against the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators streamed into central Belgrade's Republic Square,
defying warnings by Milosevic's allies to stay away and evading
police checkpoints in a bold attempt to join forces against the
strongman's grip on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had enough of terror of Europe's last dictator,''
opposition leader Vladan Batic shouted into a microphone. The crowd
roared: ''Slobo Saddam,'' referring to the Iraqi strongman.
</P>
<P>
   The protest was the biggest opposition gathering in Belgrade
since last August and the first since the traditionally squabbling
opposition came together in January to sign a joint declaration
aimed at pushing Milosevic aside.
</P>
<P>
   In the most visible show of reconciliation, Vuk Draskovic and
Zoran Djindjic, the two opposition leaders whose political and
personal rivalry has plagued the anti-Milosevic effort, reluctantly
shook hands at the speaker's stage.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said,
''This large demonstration shows again that the Serbian people are
fed up with the repressive and undemocratic regime President
Milosevic has inflicted upon them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly the Serbian people have voiced their outrage today
about Milosevic's desperate attempt to silence his legitimate
critics,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is internationally isolated and impoverished a year after
NATO bombed the country to stop Milosevic's repression of ethnic
Albanians in the southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has ignored opposition demands for early elections,
apparently fearing he could lose them. The government has been
cracking down on free media, opposition leaders and their
supporters since the 78-day NATO air war.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why are we here?'' Draskovic asked. ''Because the life we are
leading is no longer a life, because we are being killed, beaten,
arrested. Because we live in misery, humiliation and sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's ruling Socialists and his political allies warned
Friday the gathering was aimed at destabilizing Serbia, the
dominant Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to keep people at home, the state held a television
film festival, showing pirated copies of James Bond's ''The World
Is Not Enough'' and the Oscar-winning ''American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension built throughout the day, beginning as police bused
reinforcements to the capital. Riot police took up positions inside
key government buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Police patrols staked out toll booths leading into the city,
turning back buses bringing opposition supporters to the capital.
Demonstrators were undeterred, setting out to walk the remaining
miles, streaming through the suburbs, jamming streets and bridges,
waving flags and carrying posters.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to undermine media coverage, authorities withheld
passports and detained a group of foreign journalists at Belgrade's
airport for a night, preventing them from entering the country to
cover the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Live coverage of the rally on the leading nongovernment
television station, Studio B, was jammed. It could not be seen in
several parts of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   After walking for almost 24 hours from Novi Sad, a city 50 miles
northwest of Belgrade, a hundred students from the anti-government
group Otpor, or Resistance, appeared at the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once Milosevic is toppled, we'll walk to Australia. No
problem,'' said one of the students, who identified himself as
Veso.
</P>
<P>
   Student leader Vladimir Pavlov demanded that the opposition
leaders pledge to stay united to ''fight as one against the
regime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1726 </TRAILER>
