<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Takes Blame For Rwanda  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Shamed by its inaction, the Security
Council accepted responsibility Friday for having failed to stop
Rwanda's 1994 genocide and vowed to do more to prevent another
slaughter of innocents.
</P>
<P>
   In their first formal response to a critical report of the U.N.
role in the genocide, ambassadors acknowledged the expose's key
findings: that world governments lacked the political will to stop
the massacre of half a million people and deprived the U.N.
peacekeeping mission in Rwanda of the resources needed to save
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''I doubt any in this chamber can look back at that time without
remorse and a great deal of sadness at the failure to help the
people of Rwanda in their time of need,'' said Canadian Foreign
Minister Lloyd Axworthy, who presided over an open meeting of the
council.
</P>
<P>
   The brutality ''made a mockery, once again, of the pledge 'never
again,''' he said, referring to the promise made after the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   While no formal statement or resolution was adopted, each of the
15 council members spoke, acknowledging the U.N. failures and
vowing to do more, particularly with the new U.N. mission in
Rwanda's neighbor, Congo.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 500,000 people, most of them minority Tutsis, were
killed in the Hutu-sponsored genocide that began after the April 6,
1994 downing of the Rwandan president's plane.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations had a 2,500-strong U.N. peacekeeping mission
in the country at the time, but governments pulled out all but a
few hundred Tunisian and Ghanian troops after 10 Belgian
peacekeepers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan was head of U.N. peacekeeping
operations at the time and was singled out in the December report
for having failed to pass on warnings about the impending genocide.
He commissioned the report last year and said he fully accepted its
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Several ambassadors applauded Annan's willingness to subject
himself and the United Nations to the scrutiny of an independent
inquiry. And they welcomed his recent decision to appoint a panel
to recommend ways to improve U.N. peacekeeping operations. The
panel will draw on the findings from the Rwandan report and another
self-critical analysis of the massacre of Muslims at the
U.N.-protected enclave of Srebrenica during the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the ambassadors at the council meeting were first
briefed by former Swedish Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson, who
chaired the report panel. He outlined its findings and the lessons
the Security Council could learn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mobilize the political will to provide the troops that the
United Nations needs at short notice,'' Carlsson told them. ''And
show the same determination to exercise your responsibility for
international law, peace and security -- wherever the crisis and
whatever the continent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's U.N. ambassador, Joseph Mutaboba, said the council
could do more beyond pledging to prevent another bloodbath. He
called for a ''mini-Marshall Plan'' to help Rwanda rebuild itself.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is possible to shock the world again, but by doing
something dramatically positive, at last,'' Mutaboba said. ''It's
never to late to make things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to the pending U.N. peacekeeping operation in the Congo,
Axworthy announced that council members had asked U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke to head a team of ambassadors to go to the Congo
early next month. The team will assess the status of the peace
process and prospects for the deployment of U.N. observers to
monitor a fragile cease-fire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1727 </TRAILER>
