<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian Case Tough for Kids To Process  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN MEADOWS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Crystal Agnew understands it. After
all, what kid would walk away from trips to Disney World, a puppy,
a rabbit named Esperanza and, to top it all off, a swimming pool?
Not her, she knows.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Crystal, 15, doesn't really believe 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez has any business deciding whether he should stay in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's only a little boy. I don't think he understands what is
going on,'' said Crystal, an eighth-grader at Conniston Community
Middle School 90 miles north of Miami. ''It's like a big playground
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In schools across the country, children Elian's age and older
are just as inundated as the rest of America with the saga
unfolding in South Florida. Like adults, they struggle to figure
out how one child became a national obsession. And, like adults,
they don't share the same opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he has enough brains to choose if he wants to go back
to his dad,'' said Shane Buck, 15, of Plainview, Neb., enjoying a
day off from school at the Westroads Mall in Omaha. Of one thing,
he's sure: ''I don't think it should be a national matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston's Roxbury section at the Maurice J. Tobin School, 68
percent of students are Hispanic, though none are Cuban. On Friday
afternoon, eighth-grader Thomas Brown -- in baggy jeans and striped
T-shirt -- said his social-studies class has spent time talking
about Elian. Though he didn't think the boy was old enough for an
independent decision, Thomas said he was ambivalent about what
should happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's confusing for him. He's got his father telling him one
thing, and the rest of the family telling him something else,''
said Thomas, 14. ''If that was me, I wouldn't want outside persons,
or the government, trying to make decisions for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Beniquez, 12, another honor-roll student at the Tobin
school, agreed. ''Everybody's in his business,'' the sixth-grader
said. ''He's too little to decide for himself. Everybody's, like,
deciding for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Erin Finlayson was shopping at a mall in Lubbock,
Texas. She said she's been watching coverage while getting ready
for school. ''I think the U.S. would be a lot safer,'' she said.
''Cuba doesn't have anything for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   At West Palm Beach's Conniston school, many children, including
13-year-old Albert Pavon, whose parents came to the United States
from Cuba in the early 1980s, have strong opinions about the Elian
situation. They all agree the boy should be granted citizenship.
And the father?
</P>
<P>
   ''If he really wants his kid, he should stay here with him,''
said 14-year-old Jessica Rosario. ''He should be glad for his son --
that he is now free from Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessica has changed her mind since Elian first arrived. At
first, like her mother, she believed Elian should be returned to
Cuba. No more.
</P>
<P>
   ''God had a reason for him to be here,'' said the tall, Hispanic
girl. ''His mom died bringing him here. He lived through the two
days in the water and stuff. He should be allowed to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   One theme kept coming up: the attention. After 4{ months, many
students said they were overwhelmed by the media attention and are
ready for a resolution. Thomas Brown, the Boston student, certainly
is.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we first heard about it, on the front page of newspapers,
that's all you'd see,'' Thomas said. ''After a while, you just
don't care no more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1735 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No apologies from State Police superintendent on reform timeline  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The head of the New Jersey State Police said
Friday anyone who thinks an overhaul of the department can be
accomplished quickly lives in a ''dream world.''
</P>
<P>
   Col. Carson Dunbar was speaking with members of the state's
Black Ministers Council, which is holding a weeklong planning
session here. Dunbar laid out the reforms he's made so far but told
critics he would not be bullied into making more changes any more
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar staunchly defended his promotion of 300 troopers and
repeatedly told the ministers that he will maintain his timetable
for improving a division tainted by charges of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar has ordered cameras installed in patrol cars, issued a
zero-tolerance policy for discrimination and harassment and is
restructuring the internal affairs unit.
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to have every state trooper read a report by the
attorney general's office that accused their ranks of targeting
minority motorists for drug prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   But for him to have rebuilt the State Police in the five months
since he was appointed is unrealistic, Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they expect everything to be resolved in a short period of
time, they live in a dream world. I do not,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting Dunbar said that any hasty changes would lead
to more problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bad management decisions end up with bad results,'' Dunbar
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers group has led criticism of the State Police since
an April 1998 shooting of four unarmed minority motorists on the
New Jersey Turnpike. Since then, the group's executive director,
the Rev. Reginald Jackson, and others have challenged Dunbar on his
handling of the racial profiling allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Jackson said Dunbar was wrong to promote troopers
before he revised the system. Dunbar said he had to be fair and he
would not withhold a promotion based solely on suspicions that a
trooper engaged in racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not be goaded into acting without proof,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   He invited the ministers to see for themselves the effect of his
changes and asked them to participate in a continuing review of
State Police operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I challenge you to travel the Turnpike today,'' Dunbar said,
telling the ministers that they would not see minorities being
routinely stopped along the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent also had a promise for troopers who did
target minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those few who have also caused problems in the past also know
this is a new day,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. praised Dunbar's work and
said he supports the time he is taking to make the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to last, in order to make people's lives better, the
process has to be done right,'' said Farmer, adding that New Jersey
has done more ''than any other state or the federal government to
prohibit the practice of racial profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Stanley Justice said this was the first time many in
the group had met Dunbar. Ministers liked his answers, but they
expect him to follow through with actions, Justice said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will give him the fact that he hasn't been here long
enough,'' Justice said. ''After a while that will not be an
excuse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
