<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Group Boosts Tribune Earnings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Tribune Co., the parent company of the Chicago
Tribune and the Chicago Cubs, reported an 18 percent increase in
first quarter earnings from operations, driven by continued growth
in its television group.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three months of 2000, Tribune's earnings from
operations rose to $85.5 million, or 32 cents a share, from $72.7
million, or 27 cents a share, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The results reported Friday matched Wall Street expectations,
according to a survey of analysts by First Call/Thomson Financial.
Tribune shares fell 31\ cents to $37.56\ in trading at 4:30 p.m. on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings from operations exclude non-operating items in both
periods. With those items, Tribune's net income fell to $71.2
million, or 26 cents a share, from $343.3 million, or $1.30 a
share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Non-operating items in the latest quarter reduced earnings per
share by 6 cents mainly due to an adjustment in the valuation of
Tribune's derivatives securities. Non-operating items swelled last
year's earnings by $1.03 a share due to an increase in the
valuation of derivatives and Tribune's sale of WGNX-TV in Atlanta
and shares of America Online common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter increased 9 percent to $782.4 million
from $719.8 million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Profits at Tribune's broadcasting and entertainment division
rose 33 percent in the quarter to $84 million. The company
attributes the gain primarily to growth at its WB affiliates and at
its flagship WGN superstation. The division's revenues rose 18
percent to $311.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune publishing division's profits edged up to $109
million from $108 million. Revenues rose 3 percent to $397 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company reports advertising revenues at its newspapers,
including the Orlando Sentinel, increased, while revenues from
classified ads were flat. Newsprint and ink expenses fell 6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co. last month agreed to acquire Los Angeles-based Times
Mirror Co. in a $6 billion deal that will create the nation's
third-largest newspaper company.
</P>
<P>
   Diversified operations of the new company will include 22
television stations and Internet news sites that will attract 3.4
million visits a month.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Tribune Co. site: http://www.tribune.com
</P>
</TEXT>
