<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killings, Threats Rise in Colombia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA (AP) -- The human rights situation in Colombia has
deteriorated significantly in the past year, with killings, death
threats and kidnappings all on the rise, U.N. High Commissioner for
Human Rights Mary Robinson said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the allegations have implicated paramilitary
groups, who allegedly operate with the support or acquiescence of
the Colombian military, Robinson told the 53-nation U.N. Human
Rights Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The report, part of an annual review of countries, was likely to
fuel the criticism about a proposed $1.7 billion U.S.
anti-narcotics aid package for Colombia that would massively
increase Washington's support for the country's armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian President Andres Pastrana was in London and Washington
this week lobbying for the U.S. aid and nearly $2 billion more from
European donors to back his Plan Colombia for fighting narcotics in
the Andean nation.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worry the U.S. portion of the aid, which would finance a
Colombian military strike into rebel-held jungles where poor
peasants grow drug crops, could aggravate a troubling panorama in
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a huge concern about the humanitarian effects that
action might generate,'' said the U.N. human rights director in
Colombia, Anders Kompass, releasing Robinson's report
simultaneously in Bogota on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson noted complaints that members of the armed forces and
police were responsible for human rights abuses, and urged that
''deep concern over the widespread impunity'' for such violations
be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   To put an end to paramilitary activity, she urged the government
to take ''stringent measures,'' including the arrest, trial and
punishment of ''those who, by whatever means, participate in or
support paramilitary groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Decades of violence in Colombia involving government troops,
drug gangs, left-wing guerrillas and right-wing paramilitaries have
displaced more than 1.5 million people and killed tens of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's report said 1,836 people were killed in massacres
last year, an increase of 36 percent on 1998. It said 402 massacres
were reported, a rise of nearly 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rights office ''has received reports indicating that members
of the military forces participate directly in the organization of
new paramilitary groups and in disseminating threats,'' it added.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson highlighted the plight of Colombia's internally
displaced people.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency estimates that violence by armed groups
has driven at least 800,000 people from their homes since 1996.
Almost all have remained in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Some 123,000 people were displaced in the first six months of
last year alone, it says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
