<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Prices Surge in March  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer prices surged in March, reflecting
higher costs for everything from gasoline to housing. The
unexpectely bad news on inflation triggered the worst one-day point
drop in Wall Street history.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report prompted investors, already suffering a dismal
week, to unload stocks feverishly. The selling turned into a panic
as the session wore on.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow plunged 617.78 points, or 5.7 percent, at 10,305.77, its
lowest level in a month. At its lowest point Friday, the index was
off 722 points. The Nasdaq dropped 355.49 points, or by 9.7
percent, to 3,321.29, its lowest finish since Nov. 17, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to investors and economists: the core rate of
inflation, which ignores volatile food and energy prices, jumped by
the largest amount in five years.
</P>
<P>
   On a wild day on Wall Street, Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan renewed a warning that while technological improvements
have helped investors manage risk better, the nation's financial
markets are not immune to a sudden loss of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the general human experience that when confronted with
uncertainty, whether in financial markets or in any other aspect of
life, disengagement is the normal protective reaction,'' Greenspan
said in a speech.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, asked about Wall Street's
dramatic slide in an appearance on CNN, said: ''We're watching
developments in the markets, as we always do.'' But Summers
stressed that the fundamentals of the U.S economy remain sound.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index, the most closely watched inflation
gauge, shot up 0.7 percent last month, the biggest spike in close
to a year, which followed a sizable 0.5 percent increase in
February, the Labor Department said.
</P>
<P>
   While the overall figure surprised economists and investors, it
was the 0.4 percent increase in the core rate of inflation,
reflecting fairly widespread price increases, that really stunned
them. The core rate took its biggest leap in five years, a rise
twice as fast as many analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Fed has been worried that inflation would accelerate but
had not seen evidence of a 'smoking gun.' ... It's fair to say that
the gun has smoked,'' First Union economist David Orr said of the
core rate.
</P>
<P>
   Higher prices for housing, clothing, airline fares, medical care
and other items all contributed to the jump in the core rate, which
had risen by a mild 0.2 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hallmark of the report is that price increases are so
broad-based. Prices for everything from apparel to sporting events
are rising more quickly. It indicates that we will see stronger
inflation numbers as we make our way though the year,'' said Mark
Zandi, an economist with RFA Dismal Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation report raises the odds that the Federal Reserve
might boost interest rates by half a percentage point when
policy-makers meet May 16, economists said. Still, many believe the
Fed will stick with its steady-as-she-goes approach and boost rates
by a quarter of a point.
</P>
<P>
   ''The report was a significant surprise,'' said Ken Mayland,
economist with ClearView Economics. ''It certainly is going to
raise eyebrows at the Fed. In previous meetings, the Fed has talked
about increasing interest rates at a faster pace. Certainly the
core inflation number is something that is going to cause them to
give even more consideration to that.''
</P>
<P>
   The central bank has raised rates five times since June 30, each
a quarter of a point, to slow the red-hot economy and keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   A huge 4.9 percent increase in energy costs, the largest since
last April, helped catapult overall consumer prices in March.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline prices rose 11.1 percent and natural gas went up 1.9
percent, both increases the largest since September. However, fuel
oil prices, which posted a record increase in February, fell in
March by 14.2 percent, the biggest decline in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Production limits by oil-producing nations largely accounted for
the rise in overall energy costs. Crude oil prices hit $34 a barrel
in early March, the latest in a series of nine-year highs that have
sent gasoline prices soaring. Given that oil prices have fallen
since then, economists believe the April CPI report should show
lower energy prices.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by oil-producing countries to boost production should
eventually provide additional relief.
</P>
<P>
   Of more concern to economists, though, were increases in other
prices that they did not believe were linked to higher energy
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Housing costs, a big chunk of the total CPI, rose 0.4 percent
reflecting low supply and strong demand, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Clothing prices rose 0.3 percent, and medical care costs grew by
0.5 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports, industrial production rose 0.3 percent in
March, as expected, a fresh sign that the manufacturing sector is
on solid footing. Business inventories grew by 0.5 percent in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The CPI report: http://stats.bls.gov/cpihome.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
