<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tentative Africa Trade Deal Praised  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders welcomed a tentative
agreement on legislation extending new trade benefits to African,
Central American and Caribbean nations Friday and suggested final
action could come next month.
</P>
<P>
   ''This agreement marks a significant milestone for a strong and
meaningful trade mechanism in the African and Caribbean Basin
areas,'' House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer,
R-Texas, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A monthslong logjam on the bill, a top Clinton administration
trade initiative, was broken Thursday night as leaders from the
House and the Senate met to hammer out a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Although some staff work remained, leaders characterized the
agreement as a major breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the legislation would boost investment,
economic growth and job creation in these countries and improve the
competitive position of the U.S. textile industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will help promote economic reform, reduce poverty and
broaden participation in the benefits of the global economy,''
Clinton said in a statement. ''I urge Congress to complete the
remaining work on the bill rapidly so that final approval can occur
during the first week after its Easter recess.''
</P>
<P>
   According to participants, House leaders agreed to a Senate
proposal to give Caribbean and Central American nations many of the
same duty-free benefits to be extended to sub-Saharan African
nations.
</P>
<P>
   And House negotiators, in turn, agreed to some Senate
restrictions on apparel imports designed to protect the
hard-pressed U.S. textile industry.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said he hoped for final
House and Senate votes on the measure ''as soon as possible,''
suggesting it might come up soon after Congress returns from a
two-week spring recess that began on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hastert and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
participated in the evening talks that produced the tentative
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Lott on Friday said that winning final approval of the bill
would be ''a major achievement ... It will help Africa and help the
Caribbean and help America.''
</P>
<P>
   Some details were sketchy, but those close to the negotiations
said House leaders agreed to accept a more-expansive Senate version
in terms of countries covered.
</P>
<P>
   The House-passed bill only dealt with the 48 countries of
sub-Saharan Africa. The Senate bill -- and now the compromise --
covers these nations, plus 24 Caribbean and Central American
nations as well.
</P>
<P>
   In another compromise, House leaders agreed to go along with a
cap on the volume of apparel shipments to receive duty-free
treatment, while Senate leaders agreed to lower restrictions than
in the original Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate leaders also agreed to drop a Senate-passed requirement
that African-assembled apparel use U.S. fabric and thread, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the poorest countries in Africa would be eligible
for duty-free treatment in U.S. markets with no restrictions for
four years.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirts manufactured in Caribbean and Central American
countries would be subject to some restrictions not applied to
other apparel, however, in a nod to U.S. textile manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something we have really wanted to accomplish for
sometime,'' Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told
reporters. He called the tentative agreement ''good news for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and congressional leaders hoped to
handle the measure before taking up an even more contentious trade
bill later in the spring, extending permanent trade benefits to
China to help ease the way for China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The bill, H.R. 434, may be found at
http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
