<DOCNO> APW20000414.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Freddie Mac Backs Minority Families  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Freddie Mac says it will try to help stimulate
minority home ownership by buying up to $1 billion in mortgage
loans made to minority families over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac said Friday it will purchase loans made through Bank
of America and minority-owned lenders in selected locations. It
also has pledged to provide $1 million to support the home
ownership project.
</P>
<P>
   ''Freddie Mac's mission is to make the dream of decent,
accessible housing a reality,'' Freddie Mac's chairman and chief
executive Leland C. Brendsel said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is a joint effort with the Rev. Jesse Jackson's
Rainbow/PUSH Coalition, officials said, and is an extension of the
coalition's effort to stimulate corporate investment in
minority-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago-based Rainbow/PUSH's partnership with Freddie Mac is
designed to help ''tear down the barriers blocking minority
families from the most significant financial opportunity facing
most American families: home ownership,'' Jackson said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac is a stockholder-owned corporation chartered by
Congress to increase the supply of funds that commercial banks and
other mortgage lenders can make available to home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Jackson urged shareholders to withdraw investments from
Freddie Mac amid a $15 million race-discrimination lawsuit filed by
a former executive.
</P>
<P>
   Last July, the Department of Housing and Urban Development said
it would require Freddie Mac and another housing finance company,
Fannie Mae, to finance more mortgages for low- and moderate-income
families. The move will boost their total to $2.4 trillion in such
mortgages over 10 years, HUD said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
