<HEADLINE> Chavez's Rival Gaining In Race  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The former army officer who helped
Hugo Chavez stage his famed 1992 coup attempt and is now seeking to
unseat the Venezuelan leader in May's presidential election is
closing in on his rival, according to an opinion poll published
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidate Francisco Arias would receive 41 percent
of the vote if elections were held today, while Chavez would
receive 45 percent, said a poll by the private Venezuelan firm
Mercanalisis.
</P>
<P>
   The group surveyed 1,000 people in seven major cities across the
country, Mercanalisis' Paul Villasmil told The Associated Press.
The poll, which was conducted between March 21 and April 6, has a
margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The survey comes as tensions over the upcoming presidential
elections intensified this week with opposition politicians,
Catholic Church leaders and retired military officials calling on
national election officials to move quickly to ensure fair
balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The National Election Council has come under fire after Arias
and opposition leaders said fair elections may not be possible
because Chavez's political movement hand-picked the electoral
council's members.
</P>
<P>
   This latest poll shows Arias making strong gains in his bid to
unseat his one-time comrade. A poll in March showed an 11 point
difference between the two candidates. Arias split with Chavez
saying the president abandoned the goals of their failed coup.
</P>
<P>
   Many Venezuelans believe Arias has a chance to unseat the
charismatic Chavez because he is not associated with the
traditional political parties that Chavez's political coalition has
decimated since he became president over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   A new constitution pushed through by Chavez last year requires
new elections for most public offices, including the presidency,
congress, governorships and local councils.
</P>
</TEXT>
