<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Transplant Bill Decision Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Backers of compromise legislation setting
rules for the nation's transplant system failed to move their bill
through the Senate before Congress left town for spring break.
</P>
<P>
   But its chief sponsors, Sens. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., and Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., say they'll try again when the Senate returns in
late April.
</P>
<P>
   The bill just passed out of committee on Wednesday, but
supporters had hoped to move it quickly using a process that
requires all members of the Senate to go along. Leaders in both
parties were willing to move it through quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one senator, Democrat Russ Feingold of Wisconsin,
objected, reflecting the views of his state's governor and
transplant hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's hoping to still work on a compromise,'' said
Feingold spokeswoman Laura Grund.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation attempts to balance power between the Department
of Health and Human Services and the private contractor that runs
the nation's transplant system, who have been battling over who
should have final say over transplant policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Frist-Kennedy bill, a panel of medical experts would
have final say over how the nation distributes scarce organs to
thousands of waiting patients.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation does not address the substance of the argument:
whether organs should be offered first to patients who live near
the donor, as in the current system, or go to the sickest patients
first, even if they live elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it sets up a mediation system to settle disputes between
HHS and the transplant network. An outside panel of experts would
have the power to make final decisions on policy, based on legal
principles.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-member panel will be comprised of seven people nominated
by HHS, by the transplant network and by the independent Institute
of Medicine. The network and the IOM will each nominate 12 people
and the HHS secretary will choose from among their lists.
</P>
<P>
   But Feingold and others from Wisconsin object to allowing HHS to
choose the members representing the transplant community, even if
they are picked from a list.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy spokesman Jim Manley said the bill has sufficient
support to pass the Senate and to overcome any attempt to keep it
stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if it passes, it must be reconciled with the House,
where lawmakers passed a bill giving the private transplant network
sole power over policy.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: United Network for Organ Sharing:
http://www.unos.org
</P>
<P>
   HHS Division of Transplantation: http://www.hrsa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1812 </TRAILER>
