<HEADLINE> Group Claims Irish Police Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A dissident republican group
claimed responsibility on Friday for a failed mortar attack on a
Northern Ireland border police base.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the abortive attack Wednesday, but the device
near some houses.
</P>
<P>
   The Continuity IRA, a splinter group opposed to the province's
1998 peace accord, used a recognized code word in a call to a
Belfast newsroom to claim responsibility for the attack -- a single
mortar shell that was fired at the police station at Rosslea,
County Fermanagh, but fell 150 yards short of its target.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth failed attack on a security installation since
Feb. 11, when Britain suspended Northern Ireland's new
power-sharing government to avoid a walkout by the pro-British
Ulster Unionist Party over the Irish Republican Army's refusal to
disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Bombers have since attacked military bases in Londonderry and
nearby Ballykelly. Police also said they found a primed rocket
launcher and stopped an attack at a Dungannon military base.
</P>
<P>
   Fermanagh is an area where the Continuity IRA has carried out a
series of attacks in recent years. Another splinter group, which
calls itself the Real IRA and was responsible for the 1998 Omagh
bombing that killed 29 people has been responsible for a series of
other attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The groups are among several that emerged to the IRA-allied Sinn
Fein party's decision to participate in the peace process with
pro-British Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   The British and Irish governments and Protestant and Catholic
parties to the peace agreement have continued to meet and discuss
solutions to the disarmament problem that has brought the process
to a standstill.
</P>
</TEXT>
