<HEADLINE> Ridge: Change GOP Abortion Plank  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Though he supports abortion rights,
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge won't fight to eliminate strict
anti-abortion language from the party's platform when his state
plays host to the Republican National Convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge, often mentioned as a possible running mate for George W.
Bush, believes the party would appear more inclusive if the
platform were changed, but he also feels such an effort would have
little chance of success and would only divide Republicans, said
spokesman Tim Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor has said repeatedly we have to keep our eye on
the ball,'' Reeves said Friday. ''That means helping Governor Bush
to get elected and there's nothing his opponents would like to see
more than to see the party expend its energy and resources fighting
over the abortion plank.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, Bush's strongest rival in the Republican
primaries, also was in Pennsylvania Friday and talking about
inclusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to make some efforts, along with Governor Ridge
and our candidate, to make sure that we have a platform that is
inclusive, that we send the message that the Republican Party is a
large party that practices the politics of addition and not
division,'' said McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   As for the anti-abortion plank, he said he favors exceptions in
cases of rape, incest or to protect the life of a mother.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting to eliminate the plank would be useless, Reeves said,
especially since Bush ''supports retention of the language, the
people on the platform committee support retention of the
language.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has said he personally would allow abortions
when needed to save a woman's life or to end pregnancies caused by
rape or incest, but he does not want to change the platform.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said he views the abortion plank as ''an
important statement of pro-life principles'' and realizes ''that
there are a lot of different people with a lot of different views
on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican convention four years ago, nominee Bob Dole
failed in an attempt to soften the platform after a bitter battle.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who will have his first post-primary meeting with Bush
on May 9, said he was sure he would be supporting Bush in the
election ''but I really do feel we need to discuss some issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
