<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Enhances Stock Program  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. is rewarding its stockholders with
some of the profits of a booming auto industry, offering to pay
them up to $20 in cash or additional stock for each share they own.
</P>
<P>
   Ford also announced Friday that, as expected, that it will spin
off the newly independent Visteon auto parts company to its
shareholders. Both events will take place this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new stock program, Ford plans to exchange its
shareholders' stock at market price, then give them back new shares
valued at $20 less. The shareholders can then choose to take the
$20 difference in cash or in more shares of Ford common stock.
</P>
<P>
   The Dearborn-based company said it would cap the cash portion of
the share program at $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The fairly radical stock move surprised Wall Street. Rating
services Moody's Investors Service and Standard &AMP; Poor's both
lowered their long-term debt ratings on Ford Motor Co. and its Ford
Motor Credit Co. unit, citing worries about how it would affect
Ford's liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the plan was a bold to increase the value of
Ford's stock, which has lagged in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ford fell $3.06\ to $51.37{ on a tumultuous day of
trading on the New York Stock Exchange after rising as high as $56.
Ford is well off its 52-week high of $67.87{, but has risen
steadily since hitting its 52-week low of $40.25 last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a major step in saying to the investing public 'We
truly believe our stock is undervalued relative to our profits,' ''
said David Sowerby, a portfolio manager with Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co.
in Bloomfield Hills.
</P>
<P>
   As of Dec. 31, Ford had $24 billion in cash or marketable
securities and was carrying $12 billion in debt. Ford officials
said the deal will leave it with plenty of cash to survive any
downturns in the U.S. auto industry or to pay for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the move will be similar to a stock split,
reducing the per-share price as more shares are issued. But Ford
believes the shares will climb in price.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. said all of the Ford family
members will take their payments in extra shares, and top
executives are expected to do so as well. The company expects 40
percent of the shares to take the additional cash, with 60 percent
taking the extra stock.
</P>
<P>
   ''These pioneering actions will allow us to immediately reward
our shareholders and accelerate our transformation into a leading
consumer-focused company,'' Ford CEO Jac Nasser said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ford had been under pressure to offer some sort of stock buyback
program to reward investors after the company's stock hit the
recent 52-week low. General Motors Corp. has offered such a program
by using the tracking stock of Hughes Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the size of the deal was an impressive bet
that Ford should have a higher market value.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact Ford is willing to distribute $10 billion in cash to
its shareholders -- that's one of the best value enhancement
programs in the industrial world,'' said analyst Scott F. Merlis
with Wasserstein Perella Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's move to make Visteon independent follows General Motors
Corp.'s spin off of its Delphi parts unit last year, creating the
world's largest auto parts company.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that the parts companies will be stronger by
competing for business outside of their parent companies --
something they could not do well unless they're independent. The
automakers benefit by increasing competition -- thereby reducing
costs -- for parts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe independence for Visteon will result in it being a
stronger competitor and is in the best long-term interest of both
Visteon employees and Ford Motor Company shareholders,'' Ford Jr.
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said its shareholders would receive Visteon stock based on
the number of Ford shares they own and the total number of Ford
shares outstanding when the deal is completed. The exact ratio of
Visteon shares per Ford share has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Visteon has about 81,000 employees in 130 countries. It had
revenues of $19.4 billion and earnings of $735 million in 1999,
ranking behind Delphi and ahead of the auto parts division of
Robert Bosch GmbH of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Ford has made several moves toward pushing
Visteon out of the nest. Ford appointed Peter Pestillo, its
longtime head of labor relations, as the parts unit chairman and
CEO last fall. A Visteon separation was the central point in
negotiations with the United Auto Workers last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Under the UAW contract, about 23,500 workers at Visteon will
remain Ford employees for life -- with Ford paychecks and pensions --
when Visteon becomes independent. Those workers also will be free
to transfer back and forth between Ford and Visteon.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ford.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.visteon.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1824 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President of CBOT Steps Down  </HEADLINE>
By HERBERT G. McCANN, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A year after beating back an attempt to oust him,
Thomas Donovan resigned Friday as president of the Chicago Board of
Trade after 18 years at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange's board will meet Tuesday to decide who will
replace him on an interim basis, according to an exchange
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   No reason was given for Donovan's resignation, although he has
been under fire in recent months from members who felt he was slow
to move toward electronic trading.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued after the close of trading, Donovan said:
''It has been an honor and a privilege to lead a world-class
institution like the Chicago Board of Trade for nearly 20 years and
to help shape its destiny. ... I leave the CBOT well-positioned to
meet the challenges of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, 62, came to the Board of Trade in 1979 as executive
vice president and took over the top job in August 1982.
</P>
<P>
   During Donovan's tenure, the CBOT has seen its dominant position
challenged by exchanges that do not employ the auction-style,
open-outcry trading method in use here for 152 years.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange, which trades futures and options on agricultural
and financial products, lost its title as the world's No. 1 futures
market last year to the all-electronic Eurex in Frankfurt, Germany.
Last month, both the Chicago Board Options Exchange, an offshoot of
the Board of Trade, and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange posted
higher volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan was criticized for a deal that will list Board of Trade
products on Eurex's trading system later this year. Critics contend
the Eurex system is not the most technically advanced trading
platform available.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the 27-member board of directors of the Board of
Trade gave Donovan a vote of confidence in his battle with chairman
David P. Brennan, who had mounted an effort to oust him as
president. Brennan had expressed unhappiness with Donovan's
management style, but was more conciliatory Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most recently, Tom has spent tremendous energy and time
preparing the Board of Trade for the restructuring which will
create new opportunities and new alliances for all our members and
our employees throughout the world,'' Brennan said of Donovan's
resignation. ''We wish him Godspeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, CBOT directors approved a plan to divide the
exchange into two for-profit companies, one focused exclusively on
electronic trading of futures contracts. That provoked a dispute
over trading rights with the CBOE, the world's leading options
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The two exchanges have since entered into talks to merge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
