<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Rise Modestly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose modestly Friday as stock
markets reeled and traders looked to park their money in safer
government-backed securities.
</P>
<P>
   But the marginal increase in bond prices suggested investors
remain cautious about Treasurys, which have seen their own
volatility in recent months. Increasingly, bond buyers have been
moving toward top-rated corporate securities and so-called agency
bonds, such as the securities of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 3/16, or
$1.87{ per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 5.78 percent from 5.79 percent late
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There were bigger gains in shorter maturities.
</P>
<P>
   The flight to bonds resulted from Wall Street's selling spree as
the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq composite index
both suffered their worst one-day point declines Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sank as a new government report of a bigger-than-expected
rise in consumer prices added to investor unease. Gains for bonds
were held back in part because of inflation jitters.
</P>
<P>
   Higher inflation could force the Federal Reserve to keep raising
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and high inflation both reduce the value
of investments that pay a fixed return, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds initially fell on the Labor Department report that
consumer prices shot up 0.7 percent last month, the biggest spike
in close to a year. Even more alarming to traders was a 0.4 percent
increase in the core rate of inflation, the biggest leap in five
years for the inflation measure that excludes volatile energy and
food prices.
</P>
<P>
   But bonds rebounded as the selloff in stocks accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, short-term notes were up 7/32 point,
while intermediate notes rose ] to 13/32 point, reported Bridge
Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.76 percent as the
discount fell 0.03 percentage point from Thursday to 5.61 percent.
Six-month yields were 5.96 percent, and the discount fell 0.09
percentage point to 5.72 percent. One-year yields were 6.02 percent
as the discount fell 0.08 percentage point to 5.72 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.12{ percent from 6.00 percent Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 at 95 11/16. The average yield to
maturity was 5.93 percent, up from 5.92 percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
