<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Health Affected by Embargo  </HEADLINE>
By JAMES ANDERSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Cuba has overcome a costly U.S. trade embargo to
provide its citizens one of the world's best health systems,
dispatch medical teams to impoverished nations and train thousands
of Third World doctors, Cuba's public health minister said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing themes of Third World poverty and health that
dominated the Group of 77 summit in Havana this week, Carlos Dotres
said Cuba would do more despite the embargo's constraints, which he
said have cost Cuba's health sector more than $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very difficult for us'' to provide free health care to
Cuba's 11 million people and to train foreign doctors and health
professionals, also at no cost, Dotres said.
</P>
<P>
   American trade sanctions against Cuba took effect in 1962, one
year after the United States cut diplomatic relations with the
island nation.
</P>
<P>
   Rules limiting U.S. medical exports to Cuba were eased last
year. There have been several proposals to fully lift restrictions
on food and medical sales, but they have failed to gain full
congressional approval. The first American trade show in communist
Cuba in four decades was held in January.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government says it licensed $19 million worth of
American medical sales to Cuba in 1998 and $26 million worth in the
first half of 1999. It also says more private donations of medicine
and humanitarian aid come from the United States than any other
country, totaling $472 million in fiscal year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Dotres acknowledged the limited sales -- but maintained that,
because the embargo blocks Cuba's access to credits and bank
transactions, ''the financial dynamics don't exist'' to expand
trade and support Cuba's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything that hurts tourism, sugar sales, impacts funds for
medicines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dotres noted that 10,000 people graduate from Cuban health
schools each year, Cubans' life expectancy of 75 years is one of
the world's highest and Cuba's infant mortality rate is 6 per 1,000
births, compared to 7 in the United States and 32 in Latin America
and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   At the Group of 77 summit, Cuba called for joint production of
medicines among lesser-developed nations, Dotres said.
</P>
<P>
   Within months, he added, Cuba would introduce an ''important
group of medicines'' to combat AIDS, while research on an AIDS
vaccine could produce results within several years.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,500 Cuban doctors are working abroad, from Gambia to
Haiti, Dotres said. They've responded to numerous natural
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   To allow underdeveloped countries to sustain their own health
networks, Cuba is hosting 5,000 foreign students at its medical
schools, Dotres said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1833 </TRAILER>
