<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage company operators admit falsifying papers  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Two former partners in mortgage companies
admitted in court Friday that they falsified papers in real estate
transactions worth up to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgages were granted by Walsh Securities Inc., a company
linked to a statewide ''land flip'' scam involving hundreds of
rundown, overvalued properties.
</P>
<P>
   Seth Hyman and Anthony Vispisiano told U.S. District Judge
Alfred M. Wolin that a Walsh principal, Betty Ann Demola, was aware
they prepared false documents in mortgage applications for loans
granted by Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Demola is the sister of Walsh president Robert C. Walsh and vice
president James Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   A former Walsh Securities employee who pleaded guilty last year
also implicated the Walshes and their sister in wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh Securities, of Parsippany, has maintained it was cheated
in the deals, and has sued 18 businesses and individuals, including
some of the five real estate appraisers who have pleaded guilty in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is on hold while the criminal cases are pending.
Company attorney Michael Chertoff said Friday the company looks
forward to getting its day in court, and said it finds
''regrettable'' the ''dribbling out'' of pleas.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman, 41, of Manalapan, and Vispisiano, 38, who had lived in
Millstone and now lives in Estill, S.C., have agreed to cooperate
with the continuing federal investigation, in which 11 people have
now pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Each pleaded guilty to a single conspiracy charge.
</P>
<P>
   Vispisiano, who prosecutors currently believe was responsible
for $5 million to $10 million in losses, faces about three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman, responsible for $2.5 million to $5 million in losses,
faces about 2{ years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing was scheduled for July 10, but is likely to be
postponed as the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-90s, they operated several Springfield-based
companies, including Target Mortgage Inc., a mortgage banking
company, and Heygo Inc., which bought and sold residential
property. Vispisiano also headed BAM Investments Inc. and Deerfield
Properties Inc., real estate companies in Millstone.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, they made downpayments for buyers who could not
afford to make the outlay, but made it appear that the money was
from the actual buyers, they admitted. After closing, the money was
returned to them by lawyers for buyers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Their transactions involved about 100 properties in Essex and
Union counties that sold for $50,000 to $100,000, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other properties involved in flip schemes were in Asbury Park,
Belmar, Long Branch and Neptune, all in Monmouth County; as well as
Paterson, Piscataway and Plainfield, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the schemes involved prearranged sales in which homes
were purchased at a low price and resold quickly at an inflated
price. The higher price was used to obtain a loan, which was used
to buy the property as well as for other purposes, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who have pleaded guilty is Gary Grieser, president
of Capital Assets Property &AMP; Investment Co. in Red Bank, one of
several companies linked to suspicious land deals.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have declined to estimate how much money was lost
through the deals, but apparently think that one of the main
victims was Greenwich Capital Markets Inc. of Greenwich, Conn.,
which provided funds to Walsh Securities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 1837 </TRAILER>
