<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Breaks $80 Million Mark  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has broken the $80 million mark
in his Republican presidential campaign, adding to his own
fund-raising record while replenishing his war chest after an
expensive primary effort.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign raised around $7 million between March 1 and April
6, spokesman Scott McClellan said Friday, three-quarters of the
goal of $10 million by the end of April. Bush's total for the
campaign is now more than $81 million.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign expects to raise an additional $550,000 next week
with events in North Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   It also has stepped up its online fund raising, sending
solicitations via e-mail. Through March 31, the campaign had raised
$1.6 million online.
</P>
<P>
   Even after reaching the $10 million goal, Bush campaign
officials said they would continue to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've made it plain from the beginning that we will raise the
resources to promote the governor's agenda,'' spokesman Ari
Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy primary spending to defeat Arizona Sen. John McCain had
depleted the Texas governor's $70 million. The campaign spent a
record $63.3 million through Feb. 29, leaving Bush with about $7.5
million in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent Democratic presidential nominee, Vice President Al
Gore, had around $10 million to spend as of the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are next scheduled to report their
fund-raising figures to the Federal Election Commission on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not accepting taxpayer funds for his campaign and
therefore can spend as much as he can raise.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is receiving federal funds, so he can spend no more than
$40.5 million, plus legal and accounting expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates will accept federal funding for the general
election, meaning they cannot raise additional money for their
campaigns after this summer's nominating conventions. Bush and Gore
will collect $67.6 million each in federal money after becoming
their parties' standardbearers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
