<HEADLINE> Wall Street Gets Sarcastic  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE MEYERSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Every so often Friday, such as when the day's
loss by the Dow Jones industrial average reached 700 points for the
first time in history, a hint of sarcasm surfaced on the floor of
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from the normal bustle of traders rushing about, it
was striking how calm and peaceful a stock market could be during a
record-setting plunge like Friday's.
</P>
<P>
   Since steep declines typically mean more work for those working
the floor, the relative hush that settled over the NYSE wasn't so
surprising. There's little time to fret or gab, or do much of
anything other than trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''Crazy, just crazy,'' said one trader, shaking his head as he
rushed back into the exchange from a cigarette break less than an
hour before the closing bell on the NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, as the Dow's loss crossed the 700 point level, a
smattering of sarcastic applause rose from the muffled chaos of the
trading floor. Then, as the Dow began rebounding in the final
minutes, a few mockingly chanted ''Rally!''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to work. In fact, it seemed like the market
stayed open for an extra 15 minutes as the frazzled traders
continued to scurry around, processing the closing crush of orders.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust finally settled, the Dow was off 617.78 points at
10,305.77, easily eclipsing the previous biggest one-day point drop
of 554.26, set back on Oct. 27, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index also rewrote the record books, but
only by a narrow margin over the record point drop of 349.15 set
just last week on April 4. At the close on Friday, the
technology-driven measure was down 355.49 points at 3,321.29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
