<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fifteenth annual beach cleaning has dual purpose  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARGATE, N.J. (AP) -- Trash bags in hand, a small army of
volunteers will hit the beaches of the Jersey shore this weekend to
collect cigarette butts, plastic bottles, candy wrappers and all
manner of other trash in what organizers call the biggest
environmental event in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cleaning the beaches, participants in Clean Ocean
Action's annual beach sweeps, scheduled for Saturday and Sunday
from Keyport to Cape May, will catalog what's collected in hopes of
identifying pollution trends.
</P>
<P>
   Among the unusual items picked up last year: 39 batteries, 28
flower pots, 392 spent shotgun shells, seven propane tanks, 19 baby
pacifiers and a car windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 3,000 people are expected to turn out at 46 locations for
the 15th annual event, according to Cindy Zipf, executive director
of Clean Ocean Action.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are really concerned about the state of the ocean these
days, between the dumping of dredge spoils and plans to sand mine.
This is one way they can help,'' said Zipf.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's two ways.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers are asked to show up at 9 a.m. at staging points
wearing gloves, hard-soled shoes, warm clothes and sunscreen. Once
there, individual ''beach captains'' will give them trash bags and
data cards.
</P>
<P>
   The bags are for the trash; the cards are for keeping track of
what's collected, be it run-of-the-mill or extraordinary. Clean
Ocean Action officials say the cataloging helps environmental
groups track pollution trends and use the information to lobby for
stricter enforcement of environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   Information from the data cards is collected and sent to the
Center for Marine Conservation in Washington, D.C., which uses it
in a national report on pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ''Instead of it being a one-day event, it becomes a long-term
help to the environment,'' Zipf said.
</P>
<P>
   Municipalities have arranged for trucks to take the trash and
recyclable plastics, glass and cans to recycling centers and
landfills, Zipf said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People really seem to enjoy it,'' said marine biologist Tony
Totah, Clean Ocean Action's education coordinator. ''It's like an
Easter egg hunt only it's the environment and the beach you're
looking out for. Kids, especially, get into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ==
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.cleanoceanaction.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 1854 </TRAILER>
