<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Times Staff Welcomes Changes  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Orlando Sentinel Publisher John Puerner will
take over as publisher of the Los Angeles Times and John Carroll of
The (Baltimore) Sun will be editor in a shakeup a month after the
Tribune Co. agreed to buy Times Mirror Co, the Times reported.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were welcomed by the Times staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could use some stability and some strong leadership,'' said
Henry Weinstein, a senior reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Chandler, a former Times publisher and member of the family
that has run the paper for more than a century, welcomed what he
called ''a clean sweep.'' He said the new leadership would ''start
to move the Times back into the kind of paper it was until recent
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as word of the executive sweep leaked out, a new
controversy erupted over an advertising campaign that includes
pictures of bikini-clad blondes juxtaposed with Muslim women in
long chadors. More than 200 reporters and editors signed a petition
denouncing the ads, and a Muslim group sent a letter of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Times reported Friday that Puerner will replace Kathryn M.
Downing and that Carroll will replace Michael Parks. The report
cited anonymous sources within the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Times Mirror and the Tribune Co. said they could
not comment on any planned management changes until the sale is
complete. The deadline for Times Mirror shareholders to respond to
a Tribune tender offer is midnight Monday. The sale is expected to
become final sometime this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The changes come during a period of turmoil at the paper. In
December, the Times apologized to readers for not disclosing an
agreement to share profits of a special edition of its Sunday
magazine with the Staples Center, which was the subject of the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The paper has also been criticized for breaking down the walls
that have traditionally shielded journalists from interference by
the business side of the paper. That policy was championed by Times
Mirror CEO Mark Willes, who began his tenure at the company in 1995
by slashing jobs and closing Times Mirror papers. Willes has said
he will resign once the sale is complete.
</P>
<P>
   The paper responded to criticism over the ad campaign by
scheduling a meeting between angry staffers and representatives of
the marketing department, said Weinstein, who circulated the
petition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Is the ad supposed to mean the blondes are 'us' and the Muslim
women are 'them?''' the petition asks. ''This campaign risks
alienating more readers and embroiling the Times in another
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The television, radio and billboard campaign, called
''Connecting Us to the Times,'' uses images of Southern California
next to images from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Council on American-Islamic Relations Southern California
demanded the ads be changed or canceled. ''This is deeply offensive
to the 600,000 Muslims in Southern California and to the millions
of Californians who value the diverse nature of their society,''
the group said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has been editor of The Sun since 1991. In 1998, the
National Press Foundation named him Editor of the Year, citing his
leadership in building The Sun, a Times Mirror newspaper, into a
''regional force.'' The Sun won Pulitzer Prizes for feature writing
in 1997 and investigative reporting in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Puerner, 49, has helped lead Tribune company into new media
advances. He was named publisher at The Orlando Sentinel in 1993
after serving as vice president of marketing and development for
the Chicago Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clearly important for the Times to take a deep breath, to
have a chance to sort of start over,'' said Roy Peter Clark, a
senior scholar at the Poynter Institute, a leading journalism
research and training organization. ''I think John Carroll is the
kind of person who will make this next transition very easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Times: http://www.latimes.com
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror Co.: http://www.timesmirror.com
</P>
<P>
   Tribune Co.: http://www.tribune.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 1902 </TRAILER>
