<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Urges Ban on Guns in Churches  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Al Gore called for a ban on guns in
churches and other places of worship Friday, taking a poke at
Republican presidential rival George W. Bush's Texas version of the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should ban guns from our churches and school events --
something that is shamefully legal in George Bush's Texas and in 20
other states,'' Gore told a group of young people. ''Our children
can't reach for their dreams if they're ducking for cover.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president was expanding his proposals on gun control, a
hot election-year issue in the nation's largest state, at the start
of a weekend trip that was also serving as an aggressive
fund-raising swing.
</P>
<P>
   In all, he planned to raise well over $5 million for his
campaign and for the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech here late Friday, Gore announced support for federal
legislation banning firearms in churches, synagogues and mosques,
as well as where school events are held.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is time to take further steps to deal with the flood of
cheap available handguns ... and get these guns out of the hands of
people who shouldn't have them,'' Gore said at a fund-raiser
earlier Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic nominee, noted that Bush signed
a law in 1995 that allows Texans to carry concealed weapons with a
permit.
</P>
<P>
   While that law banned guns from churches and synagogues, in 1997
Bush signed another law that said houses of worship would have to
post signs or hand out cards alerting visitors if the gun rule was
to be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a law that I would gladly overturn as president with a
new national law banning guns in all houses of worship,'' Gore said
at a community center here. The 300 young people gathered in a
gymnasium applauded, as did a minister standing next to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, who stood next to Gore, signed into law last
year measures that gave California the strictest regulations in the
nation on assault weapons and cheap ''Saturday Night Special''
handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ''You look at what Texas has done on gun legislation and you
look at what California has done on gun legislation and I can tell
you vice president is siding with California in this debate,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is viewed as an attractive running mate by some Gore
aides. The two met for about 20 minutes before the community center
event and discussed the campaign, but not the running mate
question, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore contended that Bush is beholden to the National Rifle
Association, pointing to a law Bush signed that prohibits Texas
cities and counties from suing gun makers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has passed virtually everything that the NRA has asked him
to pass,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Gore added that he has always believed in the
right of hunters to carry weapons. ''But America cannot afford
another Columbine, or another Paducah, or another Jonesboro,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been two church shootings in Texas in recent months.
Last month, a man opened fire in a Pasadena church, wounding an
18-year-old woman he was courting, her mother and two others before
shooting himself to death. Last September, a man fatally shot seven
people in a Fort Worth church before killing himself in a pew.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp noted that Tennessee had passed a law in 1994
allowing citizens to carry guns, including into churches.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why didn't he speak out when a concealed-carry law was passed
in his home state of Tennessee, where residents can also carry guns
in churches?'' Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports a number of gun control measures including
mandatory child safety locks, required background checks for
purchases at gun shows and a ban on ''junk guns'' and assault
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he would support background checks at gun shows,
but only if they were instant. He also has said that a federal law
requiring child-safety locks would be impractical but he would sign
it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was raising $100,000 for his campaign in San Jose, and
helping the DNC take in $2.5 million. Saturday night, he and
President Clinton plan a fund-raiser for the party that is expected
to raise $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the San Jose fund-raiser, Gore noted his support for a ban on
so-called soft money -- the very sort of unlimited contributions he
was aggressively raising Friday and Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
