<DOCNO> APW20000414.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials pin development dreams on light rail  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYONNE, N.J. (AP) -- This city hasn't had a train come through
in nearly 30 years. The one that's coming on Saturday cost $1.1
billion and carries dreams of towering office buildings, new jobs,
short commutes and no traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Bergen Light Rail Line, the costliest public transit
project in state history, begins service on 12 stations from
Bayonne to Jersey City in the first leg of what officials hope will
eventually go to Ridgefield in Bergen County and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say plans for the project have already raised
property values and brought 300 jobs to Bayonne and caused the
purchase of 4 million square feet of new office space in Jersey
City. They predict that once completed, the 20.5-mile line of
high-speed trolleys will make the most congested county in the
state more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be the best example of a public transit
investment spurring economic development that we've seen in the
United States,'' said Martin Robins, director of the Transportation
Policy Institute at Rutgers University and a former director of the
light rail project.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit expects 7,200 riders on the first weekday of service
on the 7.5-mile line connecting 34th Street in Bayonne to Exchange
Place in Jersey City, and 9,200 by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the agency says more than 100,000 people will park
and ride along the Hudson County waterfront and through Bergen
County cities like Saddle River and Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   Trains will run every 7 1/2 minutes during peak hours and every
15 minutes or so off-peak. Passengers will buy validated, $1.50
one-way tickets on station platforms that will be checked by random
inspections. Passengers can also purchase $53 monthly passes that
pay for free bus transfers.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit Executive Director Jeffrey Warsh said the system will
cost $15 million a year to operate and is not expected to turn a
profit for the agency until 2010. But the system ''has already more
than paid for itself in terms of tax ratables, new jobs,'' Warsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the funding for the project comes from federal
grants secured primarily by U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
chair of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The agency chose to build the high-speed trolleys because they
are better designed to travel along urban corridors, accelerate and
brake quicker than commuter rails, Warsh said. The trains are also
more flexible because they are easily able to stop at new stations
if they are created, Warsh said.
</P>
<P>
   For Bayonne, which last had a train station in the early 1970s,
the two stops should help connect the isolated peninsula it sits on
to fast-growing cities like Jersey City and Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to make Bayonne part of the mainline development,''
said Mayor Joe Doria.
</P>
<P>
   A paper business and a kosher food company have recently decided
to relocate here, bringing between 150 and 200 employees apiece,
Doria said. Property values are up 20 percent and fewer than 100
homes are for sale in the community of 61,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While crews painted poles and crosswalks at Bayonne's new
station Friday, residents seemed underwhelmed. Casimir Patufka, 80,
said he didn't think the trains would attract any incoming
passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nothing here,'' Patufka said. ''All the industry has
gone out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophie Jursza, 88, said her niece would be able to take a train
to Jersey City in 23 minutes instead of driving, which can take
twice that time in rush hour traffic. Jursza didn't know when she
might want to get on a train, though.
</P>
<P>
   ''I imagine I might go into New York,'' she said, shrugging.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 1915 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Winners, Losers on Wall Street  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   There were plenty of losers and few winners Friday as
the stock
market plunged, beset by worries about interest rates and
overpriced high-tech stocks. A look at some of the big losers, and
some of the few that eked out a gain:
LOSERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yahoo!, Internet portal operator, down $20.12{ at $116 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm, wireless communications company, down $21.12{ at
$105.37{
</P>
<P>
   Intel, computer chip maker, down $10.62{ at $110.50
</P>
<P>
   American Express, financial services company, down $12.56\ to
$133.43}
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers, investment firm, down $17.25 to $75.62{
WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   Newmont Mining, gold mining company, up $1 at $22.31\
</P>
<P>
   Placer Dome, gold mining company, up $1 at $8.75
</P>
<P>
   Ebay, online auction site, up 75 cents at $139.62{
</P>
<P>
   Harrahs Entertainment, casino operator, up $1.50 at $19.68}
</P>
<P>
   A.O. Smith, autoparts supplier, up $1.56\ to $20.68}
</P>
</TEXT>
