<HEADLINE> Investors' Quotes About Stock Plunge  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Quotes from people around the country on Friday's
stock market
selloff:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Oh my god, oh my god, oh my god! Agghhhhhh!''
</P>
<P>
   --Julia Pickar, who just left a high-flying Internet company to
start her own. She was watching the Nasdaq electronic signboard in
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've lost a lot of money over the past month, but I'm going to
stay in. I don't see any reason to sell. The earnings reports for
the companies I own are good.''
</P>
<P>
   --Karl Funderburk, a registered nurse from Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said it had to happen. The market has been extremely
overvalued. It's been seeming like a big Ponzi scheme with all
these Internet companies. It had to collapse, and it looks like
it's beginning to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jonathan Aurthur, a copy editor for a trade magazine in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a long-term investor. I don't sell when it goes down. I
hold. That's the concept of a long-term investor. You have to sit
there through the volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   --Eric Li, a systems analyst from New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a gamble, it's just like playing cards.''
</P>
<P>
   --Jeri Davidson, a bartender from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll just keep going with my mutual funds. I know I'm not
going to retire rich, I just try to keep going comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   --Janine Osterberg, an Army staff seargent in Fayetteville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm down about 20 percent of what I invested to begin with. I
tripled my money in about seven weeks, but it's dropped back.''
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Greenlee, a first-year Mississippi College law school
student.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a nice leisurely lunch without any indigestion. I feel
relatively relaxed, but this is still pretty spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   --Frank Woodward of Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's killing me. It's been a bad week. But I've got most of my
stuff in retirement accounts, so I'm hanging on for the long term --
I'm not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   --Joe Ayala, an attorney in Sacramento, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
