<HEADLINE> Israelis, Palestinians Outline Views  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, nearing
the end of another round of talks, have exchanged documents
outlining their views on a Palestinian state, the future of
Jerusalem and other tough problems.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said although these
could become the ''core elements'' of an overall settlement, he did
not want to overstate the significance of the step.
</P>
<P>
   While traveling in Atlanta on Friday, Clinton called Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat to update him on a nearly four-hour discussion
the president had earlier this week with Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak. Arafat is scheduled to meet with Clinton in Washington
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They spoke for about 10 minutes,'' said P.J. Crowley, a
national security spokesman for the White House. ''It is kind of
standard practice. When the president has a meeting with one, he
will give a perspective about where that one side is to help the
other side better prepare for the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks, in a second round at Bolling Air Force Base in
southeast Washington, are to wind up this weekend. In about two
weeks, the two sides will resume work at a site in the Middle East
on an accord and another Israeli withdrawal on the West Bank, Rubin
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians are demanding a state on the West Bank and in
Gaza, with part of Jerusalem as its capital. Rubin gave no
indication whether headway was made on these twin goals, or on
other knotty issues such as water supplies and refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Hasan Abdel Rahman, the PLO's representative in Washington,
agreed with Rubin that ''this should not be overstated.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Rahman said, ''It is an exchange of informal
papers. We presented the Israelis with our understandings, and they
presented us with theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahman added: ''There is no progress on substance. There is a
wide gap between the two sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Embassy spokesman, Mark Regev, said there had been
no expectation the current round of talks would produce historic
breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hoping for an energized process with the Palestinians,
and it can move if both sides show a seriousness and a level of
conciliation and a willingness to compromise,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
