<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Disturbed by Elian Video  </HEADLINE>
By ANITA SNOW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Disturbed by a new video of 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez saying he doesn't want to return to the communist island,
an increasingly frustrated Cuban government wondered Friday how
long the agonizing saga would continue.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why doesn't this sad show end?'' asked the international
weekly edition of the Communist Party's newspaper Granma.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one understands it,'' the article said. ''Least of all his
father, who after five months has not seen his son, except on the
news and questionable videos,'' it continued, referring to a home
video of Elian saying that he doesn't want to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   That video, evidently made after Elian's Miami relatives met
with Attorney General Janet Reno Wednesday night and obtained by
the Spanish-language network Univision, disturbed communist
officials and Cuban citizens in general.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Cubans do not have access to foreign news
reports and most did not see it until it was shown Thursday night
on Cuba's state television.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, speaking in Spanish on the video, addressed his father,
saying: ''I don't want to go to Cuba. ... I want to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   The video prompted Gregory Craig, the American attorney for
Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to call on the news media on
Thursday to stay away from the boy because he ''has been exploited
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The video ''was frightening,'' said Vilma Espin, president of
Federation of Cuban Women and the wife of Raul Castro, who is the
Cuban president's brother and chief of Cuban Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are trying to destroy that child,'' Espin said in a brief
interview with Associated Press Television News.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States does not have ''the force to make the Miami
mafia let go of the boy ... that is scary,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Granma International article said it was clear from the clip
that Elian was being coached. It said the boy was ''incoherent and
looking off to the side, seeming to receive orders from someone
behind the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was clearly shown that Elian was criminally pressured to
say these things without meaning them,'' commented Juventud
Rebelde, the daily of the Union of Young Communists, which called
the video ''abominable.''
</P>
<P>
   For 4{ months, Fidel Castro and his government have backed
Gonzalez in his battle to get his son, who was rescued off the
coast of Florida in late November. Elian's mother and 10 others
died when their boat sank during the illegal crossing from Cuba to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United States gave temporary custody of Elian to the boy's
relatives in Miami, who are fighting to keep him in the United
States. Attorney General Janet Reno revoked the temporary custody
on Thursday, after the relatives defied her orders to turn him over
so he could be returned to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez said Wednesday night that
U.S. authorities will have to use force to take Elian from his
house in Miami's Little Havana, which on Friday was ringed by
people who support efforts to keep the boy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There was astonishment in Havana at Reno's patience with the
Miami relatives, who are commonly referred to here as Elian's
''kidnappers.'' The government questioned why a cabinet-level
official would fly from Washington to Miami to meet with the
relatives only to have them defy her orders afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who, in any country, can publicly make fun of the law and then
be treated with the patience and respect deserving of a
gentleman?'' Granma International wondered, referring to Reno's
treatment of Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle caring for Elian in
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2015 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000414.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Who Faked Cancer Avoids Jail  </HEADLINE>
By BECKY BOHRER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Two years ago, Charlene Zimmerman told
her husband and three children she was dying of cancer. The story
circulated quickly around their suburb of Waukee and people all
over Des Moines rushed to help.
</P>
<P>
   Friends, neighbors and strangers brought food for Thanksgiving
and toys for Christmas. More help came in January when the family's
house burned down. Schoolchildren collected about $1,000 and
donated clothing and other goods.
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmerman, 34, didn't have cancer. She had shaved her head
to mimic the effects of chemotherapy, and the scars she displayed
weren't from biopsies -- they were self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   The lies led to a police investigation and a charge of felony
theft for taking more than $10,000 from charities and well-wishers.
On Thursday, Zimmerman entered a so-called Alford plea to a reduced
theft charge, admitting no guilt but conceding that prosecutors had
enough evidence to convict her, said her attorney, Peter Berger.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman was ordered to pay $1,400 in restitution and was given
a deferred sentence. She will serve no jail time if she completes
two years' probation, and her record will be expunged of the
charge.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happened to Charlene was the result of psychological
problems,'' Berger said. ''She truly believed she had cancer and
didn't intend to profit from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman had told neighbors in Waukee, population 5,000, that
she wouldn't live past a certain date. But when she didn't die, her
story changed and people grew suspicious, Dallas County Attorney
Wayne Reisetter said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman must write a letter of apology to be published in a
Dallas County newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''The letter won't say, 'I stole from you.' She will apologize
for hurting people,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, he said, suffered ''multiple traumatic events in her
childhood'' and has been ''in treatment off and on again for a long
time.'' He refused to elaborate but said he and his client had
agreed to an in-depth discussion on the ABC program ''20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've heard of no hard feelings,'' said Waukee Mayor Donald
Bailey. ''It's just one of those things. If this had to happen to
get that family back on track, and Charlene personally, I'm happy
for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
