<HEADLINE> Sixth NYC Cabbie Slain This Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A livery cab driver shot early Friday morning
was the sixth driver killed this year, prompting the mayor to
create a grant program to help the drivers install partitions or
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has created a task force to investigate
the six homicides. An arrest has been made in only one of the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the earlier cases appeared to have been motivated by
robbery. But the driver killed Friday, Luis Francisco Perez, had
cash on him after he was killed.
</P>
<P>
   A $5 million Safety Grant program will help drivers install
bulletproof partitions or digital security cameras in their cabs,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   The city requires partitions on all yellow cabs and livery cars
operated by more than one driver. But individual drivers who own
their cars say the devices are too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the partitions were installed in yellow cabs, murders
of those drivers are rare, Giuliani said. The last yellow cab
driver killed on the job occurred in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
