<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Assemblywoman Stepping Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Assemblywoman Elizabeth Connelly, the
longest-serving woman in the history of the New York Legislature,
said Friday she won't seek re-election in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   After 27 years in office, Connelly said she will step down when
her term ends in December to spend more time with her family.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been something I've been thinking about,'' Connelly said.
''It was time.''
</P>
<P>
   The 71-year-old Democrat cited the long, tiring commute between
her Staten Island district and Albany as well as the
unpredictability of the legislative schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly is speaker pro tempore, usually presiding from the
podium in the sometimes raucous 150-member House. As temporary
speaker -- the real speaker, Sheldon Silver, rarely presides -- she
recognizes speakers during debates and makes decisions on
parliamentary questions, all the while pleading for quiet and order
in the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The position is the highest-ranking leadership post ever held by
a woman in Assembly history.
</P>
</TEXT>
