<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rushdie Hopes For Ties With India  </HEADLINE>
By LAURINDA KEYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- On his first visit to India in 12 years,
author Salman Rushdie said he hoped to begin a new relationship
with his native country, where his book ''Satanic Verses'' was
banned following protests by Muslims across the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''This long rift between India and myself is now completely
over. I hope we can just turn the page and begin a new page,''
Rushdie told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie went into hiding in Europe after Muslim extremists
issued a religious edict in 1989 calling for his death for alleged
blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   Bodyguards surrounded Rushdie and photographers mobbed him as he
walked into a New Delhi hotel, where the Commonwealth Writer's
Prize for writers from the United Kingdom and its former colonies
was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie did not win. J.M. Coetzee of South Africa for
''Disgrace'' was named best book, while Canadian Jeffrey Moore's
''Prisoner in a Red Rose Chain'' won best first book.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim groups staged small demonstrations in the Indian capital
to protest the government's decision to grant Rushdie a visa.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie said he would like the ban on ''Satanic Verses'' lifted,
but had not sought to meet any government official.
</P>
<P>
   ''My message to Indian Muslims is that I've never been their
enemy and if they read my book, they would see that,'' Rushdie
said. ''I'm just here to restore a broken connection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
