<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State agency fines political fund-raising committees for incompletereports  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The state Election Law Enforcement
Commission has fined a Republican fund-raising committee almost
$11,000 for not including enough detail about contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The fine issued Wednesday was the most recent of five fines in
the past year against the six statewide campaign accounts that are
allowed to collect large contributions not designated for specific
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican State Committee was fined $10,950 because staff
members, in quarterly campaign finance reports, failed to provide
enough information about the occupations or employers of scores of
donors who gave more than $412,000 in 1995 and 1996. The
information was provided after the election commission notified the
committee of its complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Republican State Committee agreed to pay the fine
and settle the complaint without appeal, the commission reduced the
fine to $8,775 as a sort of prompt-payment discount.
</P>
<P>
   The election commission has been cracking down on political
committees that collect large ''soft money'' contributions but make
it difficult to trace the occupations of the contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Since last June, the commission has fined five of the six
statewide fund-raising committees $31,400 for more than 100
violations in which donors giving up to $25,000 did not list their
occupation or employer's address properly.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic State Committee was fined $15,175 in October. The
commission agreed to accept $12,015 to resolve the case without
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   State law permits the Republican and Democratic state committees
plus the legislative leaders of both parties in the Senate and in
the Assembly to each operate separate campaign fund-raising
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   While ordinary candidates can accept donations of only $1,800 a
pop, these statewide war chests can accept donations of up to
$30,000 a year and can dole out the money to whomever they choose
or for whatever ''party building'' purposes they deem necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The only regulation is that these committees must file reports
with the commission every three months disclosing their donors'
names, addresses, occupations and work addresses.
</P>
<P>
   A failure to include occupation or work addresses in these
reports makes it difficult for interested people to learn what sort
of industries or special interests are represented by these donors.
</P>
<P>
   Without knowing these special-interest or business affiliations,
lengthy lists of names and home addresses have limited value.
</P>
<P>
   The Doria Leadership Fund, which is designed to help Assembly
Democrats and is controlled by their minority leader, Assemblyman
Joseph Doria, D-Hudson, was fined $2,675 last year. The fine was
reduced to $2,150 because the committee agreed to pay without an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Republican Majority was fined $650 in July, and the
fine was reduced to $550. The Senate Democratic Majority Committee
was fined $1,950, which was reduced to $1,525.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican State Committee's reports shows that financier
Candace Straight gave the GOP $26,500 in 1996, but does not give
any more information about her. The GOP was fined for listing her
employer only as ''John Head Investment Finance,'' without the
required city and address that make it possible to learn more about
the possible political or legislative interests of the firm or its
clientele. Head Investments is located on Madison Avenue in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Many other partial listings for which the GOP was fined involved
donations from attorneys that named partnerships where they worked
but did not give addresses or even city or state locations, which
would be necessary to learn more about the firm and its other
partners.
</P>
<P>
   There were two $25,000 donations in 1996 from the two managing
partners of Interstate Properties, but the firm was not identified
in any way at all. Interstate Properties is a real estate and
development firm in Saddle Brook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-14-00 2050 </TRAILER>
