<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Dives 617; Nasdaq Plunges 355
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq composite
index suffered record one-day point drops today as the stock market collapsed.
After a bad inflation report sparked furious selling, the Dow dropped 617.78
points, or 5.7 percent, to 10,305.77. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 2,672-434.
The Nasdaq composite index dropped 355.49, or almost 10 percent, to 3,321.29.
Neither decline set a percentage record. This week, the Nasdaq fell 25.3
percent, while the Dow slid 7.3 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Seeks Court OK on Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A Federal Appeals Court was asked by the U.S. government today
to order the great-uncle of Elian Gonzalez to turn the 6-year-old Cuban refugee
over to the boy's father. The Justice Department said Lazaro Gonzalez should
receive no help from a court until he surrenders the boy. The Miami relatives
argued in federal court in Washington that Elian should be barred from leaving
the country until the U.S. government can certify that his human rights wouldn't
be violated if he returned to Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Lawmakers OK START II
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian lawmakers today approved the START II treaty to scrap
thousands of U.S. and Russian nuclear warheads, but the government warned it
would abandon all arms-control pacts if Washington goes ahead with an
anti-missile system. The approval of START II underlined President Vladimir
Putin's strong authority and the willingness of the new centrist majority in
parliament to work with the government. Putin warned that Moscow would pull out
of arms agreements if the United States breaches the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Hits GOP on Education, Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republicans today of shortchanging
schools to pay for huge tax cuts and said Americans should look at the GOP's
budget and ask, ''How does all this add up?'' ''I think it's wrong to spend
about $100 of the surplus on tax cuts for every $1 you spend on education,''
Clinton told reporters, university spokesmen and others at a gathering of the
Education Writers Association. The House and Senate approved a $1.83 trillion
package Thursday that that includes big tax cuts as well as reductions in many
domestic programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tentative African Trade Bill Reached
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders welcomed a tentative agreement on
legislation extending new trade benefits to African, Central American and
Caribbean nations today and suggested final action could come next month. A
monthslong logjam on the bill, a top Clinton administration trade initiative,
was broken Thursday night as leaders from the House and the Senate met to hammer
out a compromise. Although some staff work remained, leaders characterized the
agreement as a major breakthrough.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Urges Ban on Guns in Churches
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Al Gore called for a ban on guns in churches and
other places of worship today, taking a poke at Republican rival George W.
Bush's Texas version of the idea. ''We should ban guns from our churches and
school events -- something that is shamefully legal in George Bush's Texas and
in 20 other states,'' Gore told a group of young people. The vice president was
expanding his proposals on gun control at the start of a weekend trip that was
also serving as an aggressive fund-raising swing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bill OK'd To Study Undersea Energy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress approved money to study an energy source buried
under the sea and the arctic permafrost that has the potential solve many of the
earth's energy problems or cause the earth irreparable damage. The Senate on
Thursday voted by voice to authorize $47.5 million over five years for the
Department of Energy to study methane hydrates, ice-like crystals of methane
with the energy potential equal to more than twice that of all other fossil
fuels combined. The House earlier this month passed the bill, which now goes to
the president, who is expected to sign it.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Seniors To Help Refill Labor Supply
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Retirement-age Americans, newly freed from earnings limits
imposed by Social Security, will soon be putting in longer hours, much to the
glee of retailers, restaurants, vacation spots and other employers stressed out
because of worker shortages. While the newly employed seniors won't immediately
reshape the work force, economists say they could help curb inflation by
increasing the labor supply. Employers say their high-quality work ethic will be
a good influence on others.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hershiser Leads Dodgers To 8-1 Win
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Orel Hershiser, star of the 1988 World Series, made a
triumphant return to Dodger Stadium today. Hershiser, 41, back with Los Angeles
after a five-year absence, pitched six strong innings as the Dodgers beat the
Cincinnati Reds 8-1 in their home opener.
</P>
