<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Dow, Nasdaq, Suffer Worst Daily Point Drop
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- A one-two punch from strong U.S. inflation
numbers combined with the recent worries about overvalued
technology stocks dragged all three major North American markets to
their worst daily point drops ever Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's most watched index, the TSE 300, plunged 491.90 points
to 8,473.51 -- down more than five per cent on the day. For the
week, the TSE lost 10.53 per cent of its value, suffering its worst
five-day loss in nearly 13 years, since the global market crash of
late 1987.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow industrials plunged a record 617.78
points and the Nasdaq composite index also took a record hit of 355
points as inflation jitters led to feverish selling by investors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go hide under the bed for a while,'' advised Fred Ketchen,
chief of equities trading at Scotia Capital and one of the Toronto
market's most veteran traders.
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, the one-day loss was the worst for the Toronto Stock
Exchange since Oct. 27, 1997, when the index fell 434.25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Tour Buses, Semi-trailers, Pickup Truck Collide
</P>
<P>
   MAPLE CREEK, Saskatchewan (AP) -- Steel crunched, fires raged and
smoke billowed on a stretch of the Trans-Canada Highway when two
tour buses, two semi-trailers and a pickup truck collided on an icy
section in southern Saskatchewan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   RCMP confirmed at least two people were killed in the crash,
although a witness said three people lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Police also said five people were injured and one was missing.
</P>
<P>
   The crash happened around 9 a.m. CST just east of the
Alberta-Saskatchewan boundary.
</P>
<P>
   The buses weren't carrying passengers, said Danny Holmedal, who
was running water to the accident site to help extinguish fires
that engulfed some of the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The crash forced the closure of the highway about 350 kilometers
west of Regina.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Swissair Victims' Relatives Could Win Millions in Settlements:
Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- The relatives of people who died
aboard Swissair Flight 111 in 1998 stand to make millions in
settlements because of legal developments that remove limits on the
damages they can seek.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for 82 of the 229 victims of the air crash off Peggy's
Cove, Nova Scotia, says new American legislation and a recent
decision from a U.S. Appeal Court will increase the money paid out
to families suing the airline.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton quietly signed into law last week a
revised version of the Death on the High Seas Act.
</P>
<P>
   The new law, passed earlier by the U.S. House of Representatives
and Senate, will allow families to recover damages for loss of
care, comfort and companionship, which could make the cases some of
the priciest in aviation history.
</P>
<P>
   The previous act did not contain those provisions, limiting the
amounts for which family members could sue.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the relatives were also hoping the revision would
include provisions for ''conscious pain and suffering in
anticipation of death.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
One Million Stored Blood Samples To Be Tested for Hepatitis C
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canadian Blood Services will test about a million
samples of stored blood for hepatitis C as part of a massive effort
to determine who's eligible for long-awaited government
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Testing the samples, stored in Toronto and Winnipeg, should make
it possible for many tainted-blood victims to trace their disease
to a specific unit of infected blood.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is vital as thousands of people prepare to apply
for compensation under a $1.2-billion federal-provincial agreement.
Application forms are to be mailed out April 25.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear why the blood samples were originally frozen and
placed in storage, but they are now seen as an invaluable resource
given the complex criteria of the compensation deal.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 200,000 Canadians have hepatitis C, but it is
believed only a fraction of those were infected through
transfusions or blood products. Injection drug use is the most
common mode of transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Those who did become infected through the blood system must show
the infection occurred in the 1986-1990 period for which the
government has accepted responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Bernardo's Former Lawyer Used Videotapes To Broker Deal: Defense
</P>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) --The lawyer who eventually
surrendered Paul Bernardo's sex-and-torture videotapes to police in
1994 tried to use the tapes to broker a plea-bargain deal, court
was told Friday.
</P>
<P>
   John Rosen didn't want to turn the tapes over to the Crown, nor
did he think he was obligated to do so, said Austin Cooper, the
lawyer for Ken Murray, Rosen's predecessor on the Bernardo file.
</P>
<P>
   Murray retrieved the six tapes from a secret location in the
ceiling of the home Bernardo shared with Karla Homolka in the
upscale St. Catharines suburb of Port Dalhousie, Ontario
</P>
<P>
   He's on trial for obstructing justice after keeping the tapes
under wraps for 16 months, during which time Homolka brokered her
own deal with the Crown -- 12 years in prison on manslaughter
charges -- in exchange for testimony against Bernardo.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said he was ''disappointed'' with Murray for failing to
make it clear he was leaving the case because he had an
irreconcilable conflict of interest with Bernardo.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Rosen was left with the impression Murray wanted out
simply because he was out of his depth in defending the man who
would become Canada's most notorious killer.
</P>
</TEXT>
