<HEADLINE> Last Texas A&AMP;M Victim Released  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- The last Texas A&AMP;M University student to be
rescued from last year's fatal bonfire collapse has been released
from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   John Comstock, 19, was upbeat as he left Zale Lipshy University
Hospital after five months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to try to get back to A&AMP;M by next spring,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Comstock, a freshman, was wiring logs together on the fourth
tier of the 59-foot stack of logs when it fell on Nov. 18. He was
pinned under timbers for almost seven hours in the collapse that
killed 12 students and injured 27 others.
</P>
<P>
   He was partially paralyzed and his left leg was amputated above
the knee. He lives in the Dallas suburb of Richardson and is taking
college classes via the Internet from A&AMP;M's biomedical science
program.
</P>
<P>
   Comstock said he would like to see the bonfire tradition
continue, although he cautioned against working on the construction
at night and suggested it should be better supervised.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could be a lot safer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In three weeks, a commission investigating the bonfire collapse
will issue a report. Speculation on a possible cause has focused on
everything from a flawed structural design to a weakened center
pole.
</P>
<P>
   Comstock will undergo outpatient therapy at the hospital five
times a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
