</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Dives 617; Nasdaq Plunges 355
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation watched agape today as the stock market suffered
a history-making collapse, sending the Dow Jones industrial average and the
Nasdaq composite index to record one-day point drops. The Dow dropped 617.78
points, or 5.7 percent, to 10,305.77. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 2,672-434.
The Nasdaq composite index dropped 355.49, or almost 10 percent, to 3,321.29.
Neither decline set a percentage record. This week, the Nasdaq fell 25.3
percent, while the Dow slid 7.3 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Seeks Court OK on Cuban Boy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Elian Gonzalez case shifted to the courts today, where a
U.S. government asked a federal appeals panel to order Elian's great-uncle to
turn the 6-year-old Cuban refugee over to the boy's father. The Justice
Department said Lazaro Gonzalez should receive no help from a court until he
surrenders the boy. The Miami relatives argued in federal court in Washington
that Elian should be barred from leaving the country until the U.S. government
can certify that his human rights wouldn't be violated if he returned to Cuba.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Lawmakers OK START II
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- As Russian lawmakers approved the START II treaty to scrap
thousands of U.S. and Russian nuclear warheads, the government warned it would
abandon all arms-control pacts if Washington goes ahead with an anti-missile
system. The swift approval of START II was President Vladimir Putin's first
major foreign policy action and underlined his strong authority and the
willingness of the new centrist majority in parliament to work with the
government. Putin warned that Moscow would pull out of arms agreements if the
United States breaches the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Hits GOP on Education, Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republicans today of shortchanging
schools to pay for huge tax cuts and said Americans should look at the GOP's
budget and ask, ''How does all this add up?'' ''I think it's wrong to spend
about $100 of the surplus on tax cuts for every $1 you spend on education,''
Clinton told reporters, university spokesmen and others at a gathering of the
Education Writers Association. The House and Senate approved a $1.83 trillion
package yesterday that that includes big tax cuts as well as reductions in many
domestic programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tentative U.S. Trade Deal Reached
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders welcomed a tentative agreement on
legislation extending new trade benefits to African, Central American and
Caribbean nations today and suggested final action could come next month. A
monthslong logjam on the bill, a top Clinton administration trade initiative,
was broken last night as leaders from the House and the Senate met to hammer out
a compromise. Although some staff work remained, leaders characterized the
agreement as a major breakthrough.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Court To Address Death Appeals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The Florida Supreme Court today voided most of a
new law intended to speed death penalty appeals but promised to address the
issue itself. The justices unanimously found that parts of the Death Penalty
Reform Act of 2000, which was passed during a special legislative session in
January, violate the separation of powers clause in the Florida Constitution.
Only the judicial branch of government has the power to make court rules, the
justices concluded. They also found many parts of the statute would violate
defendants' rights of due process and equal protection.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bill OK'd To Study Undersea Energy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress approved money to study an energy source buried
under the sea and the arctic permafrost that has the potential solve many of the
earth's energy problems or cause the earth irreparable damage. The Senate
yesterday voted by voice to authorize $47.5 million over five years for the
Department of Energy to study methane hydrates, ice-like crystals of methane
with the energy potential equal to more than twice that of all other fossil
fuels combined. The House earlier this month passed the bill, which now goes to
the president, who is expected to sign it.
</P>
