<HEADLINE> Rep. Crane Talks About Alcoholism  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Phil Crane's alcohol use grew to almost
nightly 10-Heineken binges until a surprise intervention by
friends, family and fellow lawmakers made him reluctantly agree to
get help.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after three weeks in a Maryland rehabilitation facility,
the Illinois Republican is back in the fray of Congress, conducting
soul-baring interviews with reporters and even briefly running the
House floor for the first time in his 16 terms on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Crane, the House's most-senior Republican and a former
presidential candidate, declared Friday he has given up alcohol for
good and already feels better.
</P>
<P>
   ''My victories are on a roll. ... See, rehab and now I'm
speaker,'' the 69-year-old congressman from Chicago's northwest
suburbs joked during a wide-ranging interview.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Crane appeared to struggle with the widely accepted view
of alcoholism that it is a lifelong addiction and disease. Instead,
he repeatedly referred to it as a ''habit'' he has successfully
kicked, even bragging that he left his treatment program after 26
days -- four days early -- because counselors deemed him ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not that you conquer it,'' he quickly corrected himself. ''You
do it day by day, they stress that, hour by hour.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been invigorated since his return on Monday by
colleagues' ''hugs and pats'' and applause.
</P>
<P>
   But Crane said he was especially anxious to get back before
lawmakers left for a two-week recess so he could work on his
longtime pet project: extending new trade benefits to African,
Central American and Caribbean nations. Indeed, a tentative
House-Senate agreement was reached just Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that addressing his drinking problem was
important as he strives to become chairman of the powerful House
Ways and Means Committee next year.
</P>
<P>
   Crane is next in line to succeed retiring Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, as head of the tax-writing panel. But Crane faces a stiff
challenge from Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., and perhaps others, in
part because of his reputation for being largely absent from some
of the committee's toughest battles.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, the congressman said he had become
''vaguely aware'' he was drinking too much as he counted up to 10
empty bottles many evenings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It hadn't gotten that bad, except I had put on weight,'' Crane
said. ''This takes a toll on your health in terms of your vigor. My
scheduling was escalating in intensity at a time when I was really
undermining my capability to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crane traces his increased intake to the death of his
31-year-old daughter, Rachel, of non-Hodgkins lymphoma the day
after Christmas 1997. Two months later, after a bout with
pneumonia, he gave up 50 years of smoking Camels and, he said,
substituted one habit for another.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not have a problem with alcohol before that. But
his well-known affinity for Heinekens was talked about -- albeit
quietly -- as far back as his 1980 presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Crane's wife, Arlene, had recently pleaded with him to cut back,
or at least to switch to a lower-calorie brand, and he had started
considering whether he should quit.
</P>
<P>
   But it took an ''overwhelming'' confrontation by seven friends --
including Rep. Jim Ramstad, R-Minn., former Rep. Rod Chandler,
R-Wash., and another former congressmen he would not name -- in his
spacious Capitol Hill office the evening of March 15 to enroll him
in an inpatient program.
</P>
<P>
   Crane resisted for about an hour, concerned about speaking
engagements and other commitments on his calendar. Eventually, he
got in the car with his 36-year-old daughter, Rebekah, who had
packed a bag with some sweat suits and toiletries, and went to the
clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, he said he was struck by how many patients had
relapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't want to slip with the rationalization to yourself
that, 'OK, now I haven't had anything to drink for six months, a
year, whatever, so now I can go back to drinking in moderation,'''
he said. ''You've got to recognize that the war is eternal. You
take it one day at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now back at work, his office refrigerator is already stocked
with low-sodium V-8 juice. He also plans to go to Alcoholics
Anonymous meetings, though he hasn't yet.
</P>
<P>
   And though he hasn't had to tackle the requisite Washington
party circuit yet, he has a plan for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been looking forward to a reception to see what these
bottles of sparkling water are that people keep talking about,'' he
said. ''Somebody told me you can put a lemon or lime in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
