<HEADLINE> Sunjet Says Investigation Hampering  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANFORD, Fla. (AP) -- Sunjet Aviation Inc. has been unable to
operate normally since federal agents seized documents as part of
their investigation into the crash that killed golfer Payne
Stewart, the charter company's president said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took every piece of paper in this building,'' said James
Watkins. ''They have certainly hampered our operation. But we're
not quitters and we're going to keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Federal Aviation Administration has not revoked the
company's license to fly, nearly 50 agents conducted a daylong
search of Sunjet's offices and hangars at Orlando Sanford Airport
on Tuesday. They seized thousands of records in what the FBI said
is an investigation into possible illegal maintenance and
record-keeping practices and making false statements.
</P>
<P>
   Without those records, all but two of the company's eight planes
are effectively grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, business associates Robert Fraley, Van Ardan and Bruce
Borland and pilots Michael Kling and Stephanie Bellegarrigue died
Oct. 25 when their Learjet went off course on a flight from Orlando
to Dallas. The plane flew for hours, sometimes above 50,000 feet,
before crashing in South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators believe the
plane lost cabin pressure and oxygen during the flight, but have
apparently been unable to determine why.
</P>
<P>
   The company is negotiating with federal officials to return
maintenance and flight logs and other records needed to operate
their aircraft, Watkin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2210 </TRAILER>
