<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Miami Official Settles Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A former city manager on Friday settled securities
fraud charges without admitting any wrongdoing by agreeing not to
commit future violations.
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Odio and the city were accused by the Securities and
Exchange Commission of violating securities laws by making
deficit-ridden city finances look good on three bond offerings in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Odio, who testified for the commission at the city's trial last
month, acknowledged signing stacks of bond papers without reading
them. He agreed under the settlement that as city manager he was
ultimately responsible for the financial misstatements in the bond
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires cities to operate with balanced budgets, but
the city ran a $68 million deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the city argued in trial that city officials
relied on professional advice and couldn't anticipate the deficit
before it was uncovered by Odio's successors in late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A decision in the city's case is not expected for months. Former
city finance director Manohar Surana also faces the securities
charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
