<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex Cincinnatti Editor Sues Gannett  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NOLAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- The former editor of The Cincinnati Enquirer
has sued the paper's owner, Gannett Co. Inc., accusing it of
undermining him while retracting news stories critical of the
Chiquita banana company.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett and its lawyers secretly plotted to remove Lawrence K.
Beaupre as the Enquirer's editor to avert a threatened lawsuit by
Chiquita Brands International Inc. over the paper's stories,
Beaupre said in his lawsuit filed Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre also claims Gannett and its lawyers failed to give him
appropriate, independent legal representation or inform him of all
aspects of a Gannett settlement with Chiquita that he signed.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett, which publishes 74 daily newspapers in the United
States, issued a statement Friday saying the suit is ''full of
inaccuracies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Gannett intends to vigorously defend itself against Mr.
Beaupre's meritless complaint,'' the company said in a statement
from its Arlington, Va., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre presided over the Enquirer's May 1998 publication of
stories questioning Chiquita's business practices in Central
America. In June 1998, the Enquirer renounced the stories, fired
lead reporter Michael Gallagher, apologized to Chiquita on its
front page and paid Chiquita more than $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre's lawsuit said Gannett made him ''an official executive
scapegoat.''
</P>
<P>
   Gannett said the lawsuit was Beaupre's attempt to blame Gannett
for his problems, rather than ''accepting responsibility for the
news articles that he edited and for which he later personally
apologized.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre, now on administrative leave from Gannett, demands
unspecified damages. Reached at his Cincinnati home Friday night,
Beaupre declined to comment on Gannett's statements.
</P>
<P>
   Beaupre, a 32-year Gannett employee, alleges the company failed
to keep compensation and promotion promises made when he accepted a
transfer to headquarters as a news executive following the
settlement with Chiquita. He also claims Carl Lindner, Chiquita's
chief executive officer, insisted on the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Lindner spokeswoman Sandra Heimann did not return a call to her
home Friday night. Chiquita spokesman Joseph Hagin Jr. declined to
comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Gannett, Beaupre names as defendants two of
Gannett's corporate lawyers, Thomas Chapple and Barbara Wall, along
with Washington law firm Nixon Peabody LLP and two of its lawyers
who represented Gannett, Robert Bernius and Henry DePippo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2216 </TRAILER>
