<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Cypriot Leader Challenged  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) -- Rauf Denktash, the leader of Cyprus'
Turkish community for more than 25 years, faces a stiff challenge
in elections for president of the self-declared Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's election comes just a month before the third round of
U.N.-sponsored talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriots. Denktash
is urging Turkish Cypriots to give him a mandate as he pursues
talks with the island's Greek community.
</P>
<P>
   But Denktash, 75, faces a strong challenge from Prime Minister
Dervis Eroglu, 62, a center-right candidate who is picking up
support from Cypriots tired of Denktash's long rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for someone new,'' said Ahmet Ince, as he attended
Denktash's last campaign meeting Thursday in the historical seaside
town of Famagusta.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus has been divided into Turkish and Greek sections since a
1974 Turkish invasion, which came in the wake of an Athens-backed
coup by supporters of union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Denktash gets elected in the first round, it would be a
public declaration to the world that the Cypriots are behind him
and that he can make a (peace) deal on their behalf,'' said Yusuf
Kanli, an expert on Cyprus politics.
</P>
<P>
   Six other candidates are running Saturday, including five
left-wing candidates.
</P>
<P>
   If Denktash does not win a majority of the votes, he will face a
run-off with the other leading candidate on April 22. That is
likely to be Eroglu, who forced Denktash into a run-off in the last
election in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Eroglu's strength comes from his position as prime minister. In
this small community of 200,000 people, he is able to gather
support through popular policies and the distribution of social
aid.
</P>
<P>
   But many wonder if Eroglu would be the best representative for
Turkish Cypriots in negotiations with Greeks. The premier used to
say that the division of the island into two separate states was a
solution in and of itself.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash has the support of Turkey, which is key, particularly
among the tens of thousands of mainland Turkish settlers who have
moved to the island since 1974. Estimates of the number of settlers
range from 30,000 to 80,000.
</P>
<P>
   Denktash established the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus in
1983. It is only recognized by Turkey, which maintains 30,000
troops on the island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
