<HEADLINE> Friday's Baseball Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Rangers-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers didn't arrive in Cleveland until 2:30 a.m.
Friday morning after playing a 7:05 p.m. night game in New York on
Thursday. The team said the 18-hour time difference between
starting times was the shortest ever for the Rangers when playing
games in two cities. ''I've never experienced anything like that
before,'' said Rafael Palmeiro who homered in Texas' 7-2 win over
Cleveland. ''It was tough, but that's just part of the game.'' ...
Palmeiro has eight career homers at Jacobs Field. Only Mark
McGwire, Juan Gonzalez and Frank Thomas have hit more (9) for
visiting teams. ... Like the Indians, the Rangers were playing in
their third opening day game of 2000. Texas won its home opener and
lost in New York on Wednesday before beating the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: The Indians are now 5-2 in their seven home openers
at Jacobs Field. ... Before Friday's game manager Charlie Manuel
joked about being thrown out of the Indians' only two losses this
season. ''I think I might stick around for this one,'' he said. ...
Center fielder Kenny Lofton, who had offseason surgery on his
(left) throwing shoulder, twice made short relay throws to
outfielders Manny Ramirez and David Justice, who fired the ball
back into the infield during Friday's game. ... In winning five
straight AL Central titles, the Indians have been in first place or
tied for first for 825 of the 892 days (92.5 percent).
Athletics-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Oakland played its first road game of the season. ...
Frank Menechino, who homered in the first inning, has reached base
safely in nine of Oakland's first 10 games. ... Kevin Appier's last
shutout was at Fenway Park on May 5, 1997, while with the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: 3B Gary Gaetti retired before the game. He was 0-for-10
with one RBI in five games for Boston this year. ... Infielder Andy
Sheets was promoted to take his place on the roster. ... Brian Rose
retired only two batters and walked four, giving up a two-run homer
and a grand slam in the first inning.
Angels-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels, who played their first nine games at home
this season, were just 33-48 on the road a year ago. .. Anaheim
batted .289 with nine homers and 46 RBIs on its first homestand.
... April has always been one of the Angels' best months. It is
just one of two winning months in club history. The other is the
final one, October, when the Angels have gone 40-34. ... OF Garret
Anderson, who agreed to a contract extension Friday, is a Los
Angeles native. Asked if would like to play his entire career with
his hometown team, Anderson said, ''I don't know what's going to
happen. If it happens, it does. I'm not going to lose sleep if it
doesn't.'' . ... During his playing career, Angels manager Mike
Scoscia caught two no-hitters while with the Dodgers -- Fernando
Valenzuela against St. Louis and Kevin Gross against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO WHITE SOX: Frank Thomas was in the lineup as DH, despite
a sore right foot that restricts his mobility. Thomas was 20-for-42
with two homers on the Sox's opening road trip in which he hit in
all 10 games. ... James Baldwin, struck in the chest by a line
drive off the bat of Tampa Bay's Greg Vaughn on Wednesday, is still
not sure if will make his next start. Baldwin has a bruised rib.
''It was a scary situation, there was no time to react,'' Baldwin
said. ''To this day I can't even watch the replay. I opened my eyes
and everybody was out there. I was gassing, out of breath.'' ...
The White Sox had to switch their infield around for their home
opener because of injuries. SS Jose Valentin had a tight hamstring
so Craig Wilson went from third to short, Paul Konerko from first
to third and Greg Norton, also bothered by a sore hamstring, from
the bench to first base.
Devil Rays-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Right-hander Dwight Gooden makes his Devil Rays debut
Saturday against the Tigers. ''He's going to get the ball for the
next month or so,'' general manager Chuck LaMar said. ''If he
pitches good he's going to win that spot. And my gut feeling is
that he'll respond to it. He wants to be here and he wants to pitch
here.'' Gooden, a Tampa native, was obtained in a Thursday trade
with Houston. ... Should Fred McGriff homer in his first visit to
Comerica Park this weekend, he would add to his major league record
of home runs in 36 different ballparks.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Second baseman Damion Easley is likely to go on the DL
when the Tigers activate right-hander Jeff Weaver to start
Saturday's game against the Devil Rays. Easley has been out since
straining his right rib cage last Sunday at Baltimore. ... Gregg
Jefferies and Shane Halter have been doing more than an adequate
job of filling in for Easley. Jefferies had the first Comerica Park
RBI Tuesday and a key defensive play Thursday, both wins against
Seattle. Halter, who replaced Jefferies to start the eighth
Thursday, drew a walk to lead off the bottom half and scored on
Juan Gonzalez's double that keyed the 2-0 win.
Mariners-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays averaged 20,926 fans in their first four
home games. That's about 6,000 less than last season. ... Before
the game, a pizza company held a contest where if a kid caught all
three fly balls hit to him, everyone in attendance would receive a
coupon for a free pizza. The kid caught the balls, but the P.A.
announcer said the coupon wasn't redeemable at one of the Pizza
Pizza stands in SkyDome. They're only redeemable at Pizza Pizza
stores outside SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Before the game, John Olerud, who has played for the
Blue Jays, Mets and Mariners, compared the three managers he's had.
''I went from Cito Gaston, who was easy going and laid back, to
Bobby Valentine, who was high strung and very emotional. Lou
Piniella is kind of a blend of the two. He seems pretty laid back,
but I've seen him run on to the field.'' ... Seattle starter Jamie
Moyer walked two or less batters in 29 of his 32 starts last
season.
Royals-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals entered Friday night's game with the
most wins in the major leagues (8-3), having won four straight
games with walk-off hits (three homers and a single). ''In 34 years
of professional baseball, I've never seen it happen,'' manager Tony
Muser said. ''It's great to see the players excited.'' ... At 8-3,
which includes five come-from-behind wins, Kansas City was off to
its best start since 1978 (9-2). ... The Royals already have two
four-game winning streaks, which matches their longest streak last
year. They are five games over .500 for the first time since June
30, 1995 (21-25). ... The Royals were only one of three teams to
win last year's season series against the Yankees (5-4), joining
Boston (8-4) and Anaheim (6-4). ... Muser on confidence: ''It can
be fleeting. ... We'll learn a lot about ourselves in this
series.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK YANKEES: With Andy Pettitte on the DL, the Yankees
intend to start Jason Grimsley on Sunday, then bring Mike Stanton
out of the bullpen when Grimsley tires. Grimsley hasn't started in
the major leagues since 1996, when he had 20 starts and 15 relief
appearances for the Angels. He had 16 minor league starts the
following season. ... Tino Martinez came out of Thursday night's
game because of double vision. During batting practice, a ball hit
the screen in front of first base and dislodged dirt, which when
into an eye. ... Joe Torre entered needing one win for his 1,300th
as a major league manager (1,254 losses). ... Torre on the Royals:
''They have a good lineup. The question is how good is their
pitching going to be, and I think that's everyone's question. As
far as the 1-to-9 lineup, they're like us in that they don't strike
out a lot.'' ... Wilson Delgado started at third and Alfonso
Soriano (two errors in five games) was rested.
Orioles-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Cal Ripken's family joined him in Minneapolis as he
continued his chase for 3,000 hits. ''If I get a few hits, they
want to be here,'' said Ripken, who entered the game four hits shy
of becoming the 24th member of the exclusive club. Two others have
gotten their 3,000th hit at the Metrodome: Dave Winfield, with the
Twins, on Sept. 16, 1993; and Eddie Murray, with Cleveland, on June
30, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins scrambled to change their lineup when
manager Tom Kelly learned that Jose Mercedes and not fellow
right-hander Calvin Maduro was pitching for the Orioles. A Twins
spokesman said the Orioles made the change midweek but neglected to
notify anybody, so Kelly only found out about it less than two
hours before the game.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Marlins-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO CUBS: Cubs shortstop Ricky Gutierrez extended his
hitting streak to nine games with a first-inning single Friday. The
streak equals the longest of his career, which he achieved May
24-June 6, 1998, with San Diego. ... Right-hander Kerry Wood, who
is coming back from elbow surgery, will make his second injury
rehab start for Class A Daytona on Tuesday. Wood threw 90 pitches
over five innings Thursday for Daytona, giving up one run on one
hit and five walks. He struck out nine, including the last six
batters he faced. Cubs general manager Ed Lynch won't set a date
for Wood's return. ''We've never etched an anticipated return date
in stone,'' Lynch said of Wood, the 1998 Rookie of the Year. ''Now
it's less of a medical question. Now, it's a baseball question.''
... Cubs RHP Ismael Valdes, who is rehabbing from tendinitis in his
shoulder, will not pitch Friday as scheduled because of a small cut
on his right index finger. Valdes was to pitch in Mesa, Ariz., for
the team's extended spring training team. Lynch said Valdes will be
pushed back four to five days because of the injury. ... In a minor
league deal, the Cubs traded left-handed pitcher Ray King, who was
at Triple-A Iowa, to the Milwaukee Brewers for RHP Doug Johnston,
who was at Double-A Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins outrighted catcher Sandy Martinez to
Triple-A Calgary. ... SS Alex Gonzalez returned to the No. 2 spot
in the Marlins order Friday. Gonzalez was dropped to the bottom of
the order for the last three games. ... Andre Dawson and Tony
Perez, both special assistants to Marlins GM Dave Dombrowski, were
guest singers for the seventh-inning stretch. ... Florida manager
John Boles who was born in Chicago and attended Lewis University in
Romeoville, Ill., expected a large contingent of friends and family
at the weekend games. ''We'll invade the 'Cubby Bear' (bar) after
Sunday's game,'' Boles said.
Reds-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Pokey Reese, hit above the left elbow by a Rolando
Arrojo pitch Monday in Colorado, returned to the lineup Friday and
went 4-for-4 with a walk, raising his batting average to .500.
''I'm back to normal, I'm feeling fine,'' he said. ... Manager Jack
McKeon pointed out his team was playing its third opener -- its own
against Milwaukee on April 3, and Colorado's home-opener last
Monday. ''We haven't won one yet,'' he said before the Dodgers
became the final NL team to play a home game. ''We're due to break
our streak.'' Unfortunately for McKeon and the Reds, it didn't
happen. ... Barry Larkin, who hits second for the Reds behind
Reese, is hitting .349, but no other player in Cincinnati's
starting lineup Friday is hitting higher than .235. ''I've been
getting on for these guys, and they're going to come through,''
Reese said. ''We're not worried about that.''
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers arrived at Los Angeles International
Airport after 1 a.m. Friday -- some 12 hours before the start of
their home opener -- after completing a suspended game and then
playing the regularly scheduled game in San Francisco on Thursday
night. ''I don't think there was a lot of thought that went into
our schedule,'' Eric Karros said. Gary Sheffield agreed, saying,
''No sleep; It doesn't help the way our schedule is messed up.''
... Sheffield, who has been playing despite a sprained right ankle
that remains visibly swollen, went 3-for-3 with an intentional walk
against the Reds, raising his average to .429. He has hit safely in
all 10 games this season, and also had at least one hit in his
final six games last year. ... Rookie right-hander Eric Gagne is
scheduled to pitch for the Dodgers on Saturday night. Left-hander
Onan Masaoka was optioned to Albuquerque after Friday's game.
Braves-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Andres Galarraga has been hit four times already this
season. ''I'm getting tired of it,'' he said. ''I don't know what I
have to do to get the message to the pitchers. I don't know if I
have to fight or what, but there's a lot of room between my face
and the plate. If they don't want to pitch to me, they can throw it
outside, not at my face.'' ... Manager Bobby Cox doesn't seem
concerned about three straight losses to the Cubs and a 4-5 start
to the season. ''We'll get our team together next week,'' he said.
''We're fine.'' He referred to the return of OF Brian Jordan, LHP
John Rocker and LHP Rudy Seanez.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: SS Mark Loretta was 0-for-12 and batting .139
entering Friday's game against Atlanta. He ended the slide with an
RBI double in the first inning. ... Jason Bere, 2-0, leads the
majors with a 0.69 ERA after pitching seven innings in Thursday's
4-0 win over Florida. ... The Brewers named Elanis Westbrooks as
their advance scout. He worked the past two years for the Colorado
Rockies in a similar position. Westbrooks, 34, replaces Tim
Johnson, who resigned.
Expos-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: LHP Graeme Lloyd returned to the Expos for the first
time since the death of his wife Cindy on April 3. Lloyd was
already on the disabled list with left shoulder tendinitis when
Cindy died because of complications with Crohn's disease. Lloyd
will begin a throwing program but is expected to be sidelined for
10-14 more days. ... With Hideki Irabu pitching on Saturday, NHK in
Japan will televise the game against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Curt Schilling will make his third rehab start for
Clearwater on Saturday night. Many speculate that Schilling will be
available in early May but is scheduled to make two additional
starts in the minor leagues before rejoining the Phillies. ... The
Expos are Philadelphia's first opponent this season that did not
make the playoffs last year. ... Doug Glanville is set his to throw
out the first ball at the University of Pennsylvania's new baseball
field at Murphy Field before Saturday's Penn-Cornell college
baseball game. Glanville is a 1992 graduate of Penn.
Mets-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK METS: Rick Reed, who broke into the majors with the
Pirates, has started three of the Mets' four victories. He has an
0.79 ERA. ... The Mets were 7-2 against the Pirates last season,
sweeping a three-game series in New York the final weekend of the
season to force a playoff with Cincinnati for the NL wild-card
spot. ... LHP Glendon Rusch starts Saturday, his first outing since
an exhibition game in Norfolk, Va., on April 4. He allowed five
runs, four earned, in five innings that day against the Triple-A
Tides. ... Three of the Mets' first four victories were by 2-1
scores.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Pirates RHP Jason Schmidt's first three starts have
been against Houston's Shane Reynolds, Arizona's Randy Johnson and
the Mets' Al Leiter. ... Pirates pinch-hitters started the season
6-of-10 with two homers, both by John Vander Val, and eight RBIs.
... C Jason Kendall began last season as the Pirates' lead off
hitter, but lasted only 15 games before being dropped to No. 2.
This season, he figures to lead off for the foreseeable future. He
started and led off the Pirates' first 10 games. Since 1981, the
only catcher to lead off more than Kendall did last season was
Houston's Craig Biggio, now a 2B, who led off 17 games in 1989.
Biggio also led off 14 games while catching in 1991. Kendall said,
''Wherever they want me to hit is fine. But I'm not going to change
my approach. If I get a fastball to hit on 2-and-1, I'm ripping.''
Cardinals-Rockies:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Mark McGwire, who returned to St. Louis before the
start of a four-game series in Colorado on Thursday, was examined
for lingering back pain by team physician Dr. George Paletta. The
exam showed no new disk injury, and McGwire was treated for
inflammation in the lumbar region. He will rest and receive
treatment in St. Louis and will be re-evaluated Monday. ... St.
Louis recalled RHP Alan Benes from Triple-A Memphis. Benes, whose
most recent of two shoulder operations was in September 1998,
received a no-decision in last Sunday's start at Iowa. To make room
for Benes, the Cards sent left-hander Justin Brunette to Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Closer candidate David Lee, who faltered again in the
ninth inning Thursday night, probably will be moved temporarily to
middle relief, manager Buddy Bell said. ... Pedro Astacio, who made
his 2000 Coors Field debut Friday night, hasn't missed a start
since joining the Rockies in August 1997 -- a string of 78 starts.
Astros-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: 3B Ken Caminiti (strained left hamstring) missed his
fourth straight start, although he said he might be ready to play
Saturday. Caminiti, the 1996 NL MVP when he played with San Diego,
has yet to play against his former team since signing with Houston
as a free agent after the 1998 season. He missed all nine games
against the Padres last season when he was on the disabled list for
nearly three months. ... OF Matt Mieske (lower back strain) was
activated from the 15-day DL. ... RHP Scott Elarton is scheduled to
make his first start of the season Tuesday at Los Angeles. Elarton,
who began the season on the DL as he recovered from offseason
rotator cuff surgery, had been scheduled to start Sunday for Double
A Round Rock. Elarton's availability cleared the way for Thursday's
trade of pitcher Doc Gooden to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Tony Gwynn sat out his fourth consecutive game after
having his left knee drained Monday. Manager Bruce Bochy expected
Gwynn to be back in the lineup against Houston on Friday night, but
his knee is still too sore. ... Center fielder Ruben Rivera (wrist)
missed his fifth straight game. ... Pitcher Sterling Hitchcock said
he was going to keep the camouflage jersey the team wore Sunday to
honor the military. Asked if he still had the unsightly futuristic
uniform the Padres wore in a game last season, Hitchcock said,
''That one was torn up right away, as soon as I came out.''
Diamondbacks-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: LHP Randy Johnson has 127 career double-digit strikeout
games entering Friday night's contest. That's the second most to
Nolan Ryan's 215. Left-handed hitters are 0-for-8 so far this
season. Barry Bonds was the only lefty in the starting lineup on
Friday. ... OF Luis Gonzalez has a career .345 batting average
(57-for-165) with three homers and 30 RBIs in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: The Giants optioned RHP Ben Weber to Triple-A
Fresno of the Pacific Coast League before the game. Weber was 0-1
with a 13.50 ERA in six appearances with San Francisco. To take
Weber's place on the 25-man roster, the Giants recalled RHP Scott
Linebrink from Fresno. ... Giants leadoff hitters are 1-for-9 with
one walk and one run in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   END
