<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Essence Magazine Turns 30  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Famous faces crowded into Radio City Music Hall
Friday to wish Essence magazine a happy 30th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey and Bill Cosby were the hosts of the black-tie
bash, where Essence awards were presented to black Americans who
have worked to improve their communities and the world.
</P>
<P>
   The honorees were Michael Jordan, actor Danny Glover, the mayor
of a tiny Georgia town, a Texas couple who have arranged more than
100 adoptions and three doctors who teach city kids to follow their
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're here to make a joyful noise,'' Winfrey exulted. ''We're
here to celebrate 30 years of building a better world, and we've
got cause to celebrate. ... What other magazine has documented the
progress of so many pioneering black women?''
</P>
<P>
   Glover, honored for his years of political activism at home and
overseas, spoke about AIDS in Africa and elsewhere after accepting
his award from actors Susan Sarandon, Delroy Lindo and Omar Epps.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was reluctant to receive this award, in part because I feel
there's so much more that I can and should be doing,'' he said.
''There are no continents or communities that remain unaffected (by
AIDS). It's only a matter of degrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton turned up to give an award to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Not THAT mayor -- her likely Senate opponent, New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani. She honored Emma Gresham of Keysville, Ga., where
City Hall is a small mobile home and Gresham has rallied the town's
400 residents to get basic services like indoor plumbing, garbage
pickup, a medical clinic and a fire department.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. W.C. Martin and Donna Martin were cited for arranging
the adoptions of more than 100 orphaned and foster children by
members of the Bennett Chapel Baptist Church in Shelbyville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Three doctors who grew up together in Newark, N.J. -- George
Jenkins, Rameck Hunt and Sampson Davis -- got Essence awards for
their efforts to encourage young people to overcome the challenges
of poverty and stick to their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The show is to air May 25 on Fox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
