<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees 7, Royals 5  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Roger Clemens, struggling with his control,
became the first Yankees starter other than Orlando Hernandez to
win, and New York stopped the streaking Kansas City Royals 7-5
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (1-1) went to three-ball counts on 10 of 28 batters,
including five of his first eight, throwing 104 pitches, 53 of them
balls.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he improved to 19-7 against Kansas City, allowing five
runs, seven hits and four walks in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada hit a game-tying, two-run homer in the second,
Ricky Ledee put the Yankees ahead 3-2 with an RBI double in the
third. Bernie Williams chased Jay Witasick (0-3) with a two-run
double in the fourth -- a pop down the third-base line that third
baseman Joe Randa pulled off of, allowing it to drop between
himself and shortstop Rey Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter's two-run single off Brad Rigby put the Yankees up
7-3 in the fifth, but Gregg Zaun hit a two-run homer off Clemens in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees lead the AL East at 6-3, ''El Duque'' (2-0)
has been their only consistent starter. Clemens and David Cone have
stumbled, and Andy Pettitte is on the disabled list with a strained
back muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens repeatedly got himself into trouble on a night there
were just two 1-2-3 innings -- Kansas City in the third and ninth.
He gave up a two-out, two-run single in the second to Sanchez, the
Royals' No. 9 hitter, hanging his head as he walked off the mound
following the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens also threw a wild pitch in the fifth that allowed
Sanchez to score from third. He hit Mike Sweeney in the arm with a
pitch and nearly hit Randa in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, at 8-3 off to its best start in 22 years, came in
after a homestand that ended with four wins, three on last-inning
homers followed by another on a final-swing single.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson followed Clemens and struck out four in 1 2-3
innings, including Randa to end the seventh with runners on second
and third.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera retired pinch-hitter Scott Pose to escape a
second-and-third, two-out jam in the eighth and converted his 27th
consecutive save chance, his fifth this season.
</P>
<P>
   Witasick, who has lost four straight starts dating to last
season, was chased after 3 2-3 innings -- needing 101 pitches to get
those 11 outs. He allowed five runs and seven hits, including his
fifth homer, the 22nd off the Royals in 12 games. Only the Cubs,
with 23, have given up more.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Yankees have homered in eight of nine games this
season. ... The Royals had been 12-for-12 on stolen-base attempts
until Carlos Febles was thrown out at second by Posada in the first
inning. ... Chuck Knoblauch, who popped to third with the bases
loaded and one out in the fifth, has no RBIs in 41 plate
appearances this season. He made his second error, fumbling an
eighth-inning grounder. ... Rigby and teammate Jeff Suppan also
have allowed five homers each. Despite giving up two runs in two
innings, Rigby's ERA dropped from 18.69 to 15.63. ... Clemens tied
Vic Willis for 39th on the career list with 248 wins. Bob Gibson is
next at 251. ... Zaun left in the seventh with a sprained right
elbow after throwing out Shane Spencer at second. Zaun appeared to
get hit in the arm by the bat on Clay Bellinger's follow through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2259 </TRAILER>
