<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, April 14, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Dives 617; Nasdaq Plunges 355
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrials and Nasdaq composite index both
suffered record one-day point drops today as a new inflation report sparked
furious selling. The Dow dropped 617.78 points, or 5.7 percent, to 10,305.77. On
the NYSE, losers led gainers 2,672-434. The Nasdaq dropped 355.49, or almost 10
percent, to 3,321.29. The Dow and Nasdaq set one-day percentage decline records.
This week, the Nasdaq fell 25.3 percent, while the Dow slid 7.3 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Relatives Respond in Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's Miami relatives claimed tonight that the boy
would be psychologically harmed if he were turned over immediately to his
father. Relatives said they were willing to bring Elian to a meeting with his
father, but only within close driving distance of Miami so as not to traumatize
him. The U.S. government had asked a federal appeals panel to order Elian's
great-uncle to turn the 6-year-old Cuban refugee over to his father. The Justice
Department said Lazaro Gonzalez should receive no help from a court until he
surrenders the boy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Lawmakers OK START II
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- As Russian lawmakers approved the START II treaty to scrap
thousands of U.S. and Russian nuclear warheads, the government warned it would
abandon all arms-control pacts if Washington goes ahead with an anti-missile
system. The swift approval of START II was President Vladimir Putin's first
major foreign policy action and underlined his strong authority and the
willingness of the new centrist majority in parliament to work with the
government. Putin warned that Moscow would pull out of arms agreements if the
United States breaches the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Hits GOP on Education, Tax
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- President Clinton accused Republicans today of shortchanging
schools to pay for huge tax cuts and said Americans should look at the GOP's
budget and ask, ''How does all this add up?'' ''I think it's wrong to spend
about $100 of the surplus on tax cuts for every $1 you spend on education,''
Clinton told reporters, university spokesmen and others at a gathering of the
Education Writers Association. The House and Senate approved a $1.83 trillion
package yesterday that includes big tax cuts as well as reductions in many
domestic programs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tentative U.S. Trade Deal Reached
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders welcomed a tentative agreement on
legislation extending new trade benefits to African, Central American and
Caribbean nations today and suggested final action could come next month. A
monthslong logjam on the bill, a top Clinton administration trade initiative,
was broken last night as leaders from the House and the Senate met to hammer out
a compromise. Although some staff work remained, leaders characterized the
agreement as a major breakthrough.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Court To Address Death Appeals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The Florida Supreme Court today voided most of a
new law intended to speed death penalty appeals but promised to address the
issue itself. The justices unanimously found that parts of the Death Penalty
Reform Act of 2000, which was passed during a special legislative session in
January, violate the separation of powers clause in the Florida Constitution.
Only the judicial branch of government has the power to make court rules, the
justices concluded.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Girls Charged in Murder Plot
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Two seventh-grade girls were charged with scheming to bludgeon
three rivals with a bag of batteries and slash their throats in the latest in a
recent string of schoolyard murder plots around the country. The alleged plot
was thwarted when officials found the bag and pencil boxes full of knives and
razor blades. The arrests come the same week that three Indiana first-graders
were suspended for allegedly plotting to kill a classmate.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees Defeat Royals 7-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Yankees stopped the streaking Kansas City
Royals 7-5 tonight. Roger Clemens improved to 19-7 against Kansas City, allowing
five runs, seven hits and four walks in six innings. Jorge Posada hit a
game-tying, two-run homer in the second, and Ricky Ledee put the Yankees ahead
3-2 with an RBI double in the third.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Flyers Beat Sabres 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- John LeClair scored a disputed goal and Eric Desjardins
scored the go-ahead goal in the third period to give the Philadelphia Flyers a
2-1 win tonight over the Buffalo Sabres, taking a 2-0 lead in their playoff
series. LeClair blasted a slap shot that was shot so hard it was difficult to
see how it got past Dominic Hasek. A replay from behind the net showed that the
goal went in on the outside of the post.
</P>
