<HEADLINE> Cook To Pay Ex-Campaign Manager  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT GEHRKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Rep. Merrill Cook must pay a former
consultant $174,471 for debts incurred during his 1996 campaign, a
jury found Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed victory after the jury awarded R.T. Nielson
all of the $193,992 he sought in his lawsuit, but ordered the
consultant to repay Cook, R-Utah, $19,521 for double billings and
excessive markups.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you walked out of here with a net ruling of $175,000, I'd
call that a victory,'' said Russell Fericks, Nielson's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Nielson sued Cook two months after his 1996 election, claiming
Cook had orally agreed to boost Nielson's pay, then reneged.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's very unfortunate we had to go to court,'' Nielson
said. ''I feel we got a just verdict. ... I'm just very relieved
it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cook, who was in a court hallway when the verdict announced,
claimed the oral agreements never existed. He said he had no
regrets fighting the three-year court battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could have come out better today, but it's not all that
bad,'' said Cook. ''Sometimes you have to stand up and continue to
fight for the things you believe in, despite political or personal
risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict comes at a bad time for Cook, whose grip on the 2nd
District seat was already shaky after reports in the past year of
erratic behavior, mood swings and staff mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   He is being targeted by national Democratic groups and will face
two Republican challengers at the state party convention on May 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2331 </TRAILER>
