<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-14 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Within Three Hits of 3,000  </HEADLINE>
By ARNIE STAPLETON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Cal Ripken says chasing 3,000 hits is harder
than chasing Lou Gehrig.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a little bit more nerve wracking, I guess,'' Ripken said.
''At least the games just came and added up each time. Getting a
hit requires you to go out and get a hit. You have to do something.
You can't just show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, who broke Gehrig's consecutive games streak five seasons
ago, is three hits shy of becoming the 24th member of baseball's
3,000-hit club after going 1-for-4 Friday night at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken started the season nine hits shy of the milestone but has
just six hits in his first 34 at-bats, a .176 average.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pressure of the chase is giving him the jitters, the
last thing a hitter needs when he's at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your excitement level gets up inside, and the secret of
hitting is to try to control that and relax -- and maybe the secret
in athletics is to be able to control that and let your talent come
through,'' Ripken said. ''But it's not easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken said he didn't know if he'd play all three games of the
series, but it's possible that if he hasn't reached the mark by
Saturday, he'll sit out Sunday's game so he can get hit No. 3,000
at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles manager Mike Hargrove is giving Ripken regular days off
each week because of his bad back. Ripken said he feels fine but
the Metrodome's turf could take its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to play every game the rest of the year,'' said
Ripken, who holds the mark with 2,632 consecutive game played
between 1982-98. ''The way I played all those games all those years
was just to show up and say, 'I'm ready to play today.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken said he'd prefer to get his 3,000th hit at home but he's
not about to get picky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to leave here with eight hits in this series,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken said a stream of fans went up to him at breakfast Friday
to encourage him, and he appreciates the support. It's just that he
can never get away from the chase.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City this week, fans constantly yelled encouragement
when he stepped on deck.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all positive,'' Ripken said. ''But, again, I'm trying to
think, 'OK, what's the pitcher got? What's he going to throw? What
am I going to do? What am I going to look for?'''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Molitor, a member of the 3,000 hit club and a Twins coach,
said the adrenaline rush Ripken is experiencing as he closes in on
the mark is natural.
</P>
<P>
   ''But what's good about a milestone like 3,000 is that most
players who get to that mark have had to deal with those things in
the past,'' Molitor said. ''Cal in particular has had very
emotional games in the past few years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-14-00 2333 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
